<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessDeath     08-03 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Death,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Woman Sentenced In Boyfriend's Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless woman was sentenced to five to 10
years in prison Wednesday in the shooting death of her boyfriend, a
Vietnam veteran involved in the 1968 My Lai massacre.
   Allegheny County Common Pleas Judge Donna Jo McDaniel sentenced
Kathlynn T'Souvas, 36, for her conviction in the death of Robert
T'Souvas, 39, on Sept. 3, 1988.
   The homeless couple, who had lived together for nine years,
camped in a tent on the bank of the Monongahela River for a month.
They fished for food, sold their blood for money and worked part
time at the Jubilee Kitchen farm.
   Ms. T'Souvas told police that on the day of the shooting, she,
T'Souvas, and David Bozic, 42, another homeless person, had been
drinking and shooting rats and cans with Bozic's .22-caliber
handgun.
   Police found T'Souvas with a bullet in his head at their camp.
   During her trial in April, Ms. T'Souvas testified that her
boyfriend, who served under Lt. William Calley in Vietnam, had
become increasingly obsessed with the Vietnam War in the year
before his death. He was charged and later cleared in the 1968
massacre at the village of My Lai.
   She claimed T'Souvas shot himself in the head and that she had
tried to cover up his suicide by telling police she had shot him.
</TEXT>
