<FIRST>u a AM-ChemicalArms     08-03 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Arms,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Help Clear Way Toward Settlement On Banning Chemical Weapons
Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has accepted an American demand
that inspections be carried out before an agreement is formally
concluded to ban chemical weapons, The New York Times reported.
   The Times quoted unidentified officials in its Thursday editions
as saying the Soviet acceptance would help resolve one of the major
disputes remaining in the way of an agreement.
   The newspaper said the acceptance was conveyed in a paper
presented to Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d by Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze of the Soviet Union when they met
recently in Paris.
   The two countries previously had disagreed on whether chemical
weapons stockpiles should be inspected before or after a treaty is
signed.
   The United States had said they should be inspected and Moscow
had insisted that the inspections not be carried out until after a
pact is formally concluded.
   Moscow says it has no more than 50,000 tons of chemical
armaments but some analysts have said the Soviets have more than
300,000 tons.
   ``This is a sign that the Soviets are serious about concluding a
chemical-disarmament treaty,'' said Elisa D. Harris, an expert on
the chemical weapons talks at the Brookings Institution, the
Washington-based research and policy analysis institute.
</TEXT>
