<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-03 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPISTRANO BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Charles Cooper's girlfriend
won a $19.5 million jackpot, he had more than the money to
celebrate.
   The night she bought the winning ticket, Cooper had offered a
variation on his frequent proposal of marriage. ``If you win the
lottery,'' he said, ``will you marry me?''
   ``Sure,'' Christene Lentz responded.
   A year later, she fulfilled her promise. On July 15, the Orange
County couple were married. They returned this week from a
honeymoon in Florida at Walt Disney World.
   ``We couldn't have gotten engaged if I hadn't won the lottery,''
said Mrs. Cooper, 21. ``But since we had the money and we had
talked about it so many times ...''
   Her 20-year-old husband said he once feared his nouveau riche
girlfriend would change her mind. ``I was nervous at first because
I didn't think she would like me anymore,'' he said.
   But she said ``I do'' as she spent her money. Mrs. Cooper bought
a BMW, a yacht and a $500 Gucci purse for herself, and she bought
houses for her aunt and grandmother.
   The Coopers plan to build their own fantasy house with a bowling
alley, dance floor, video jukebox and toy trains in the living room.
   After her first year as a millionaire, Mrs. Cooper finds herself
living from $723,000 check to $723,000 check. ``I have enough money
to get me through to the end of next month,'' she said. ``That's
when the next check comes.''
   The Coopers insist the money has not changed them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Childhood fantasies of celebrating
Christmas year-round come true in southwestern Illinois, where
Alfred Meyers refuses to take down his artificial, seven-foot
scotch tree.
   ``I used to live in a little house across the street, and we
could only keep it up a short time,'' the septuagenarian said
recently. ``Here, I've got all this space. I don't have to take it
down, so I keep it up.''
   Shining through the picture window of the Meyers' home in
Hartford, a town of about 1,900 people across the Mississippi River
northeast of St. Louis, the tree has been a fixture for the past
three years.
   Meyers said the tree, decorated with some ornaments that are
more than 40 years old, is a conversation piece with local
residents.
   ``This is a fairly small town. The families are still able to
get out and walk around at night,'' he said. ``I hear the people _
and especially the kids _ go by and say, `See, I told you it was
up.'''
   Keeping the tree up throughout the year does not diminish the
Christmas spirit, Meyers said; rather, it extends the holiday to
every day of the year.
   ``To me, when I see the kids go by that Christmas tree and get a
smile on their face, it's all worth it,'' Meyers said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growers of sweet potatoes, claiming their
product's character is being maligned, want to divorce the
vegetable from other potatoes by giving it a new name _ sweetpotato.
   ``We could call it the `love spud,''' said Virginia Tech
vegetable specialist Charlie O'Dell, referring to a campaign once
developed for tomatoes as ``love apples.''
   Sweet potato advocates, whose efforts to promote the product as
yams resulted in only half-baked success, have no love for the
starchy image of the ordinary potato.
   ``Yam never was a good word,'' said Bill Mapp, regional
marketing manager with the Virginia Department of Agriculture and
Consumer Services. ``It's a Madison Avenue word.''
   The campaign for sweetpotato has its origins in the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, which has used one word to denote the
product for some time, said Billy Yeargin, executive director of
the North Carolina Sweetpotato Commission.
   ``Their contention is that to refer to it as two words is
inaccurate because it refers to a potato that is sweet,'' said
Yeargin, whose commission dropped ``Yam'' from its name in January.
   So what does a sweet potato marketing official do when he wants
to change the name of his spud? Go to the dictionary. Yeargin's
commission tried that, but the effort was a dud.
   ``A dictionary doesn't have anything to do with deciding whether
sweet potato should be one word,'' said Victoria Neufeldt, editor
in chief at Webster's New World Dictionary. ``What we use is
usage.''
</TEXT>
