<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0344EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthPension     08-03 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Pension,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dickinson Bill Would Restore North's Pension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key member of the House Armed Services
Committee is waging a battle in Congress to restore the $23,000
annual Marine Corps pension Oliver North lost when he was convicted
in the Iran-Contra scandal.
   Rep. Bill Dickinson, the senior Republican on the committee,
introduced legislation Wednesday to restore the pension.
   The Alabama congressman said that North earned the retirement
pay during his 20-year career in the Marines when he ``demonstrated
his willingness to give his life for his country.'' North retired
before his conviction with the rank of lieutenant colonel.
   ``He certainly shouldn't be asked to give up the security of his
own family over charges that may not have been his doing,''
Dickinson said.
   The bill would exempt North from a law that denies retirement
pay to any government officer convicted of destroying government
documents, one of three felony crimes for which North was convicted.
   The Navy suspended North's pension July 5, when he was fined
$150,000 and ordered to perform 1,200 hours of community service
for his convictions on charges of aiding and abetting an
obstruction of Congress, accepting an illegal gratuity and altering
or destroying classified documents.
   The Navy recommended to U.S. Comptroller General Charles
Browsher that North's retirement pay be restored, but Bowsher
rejected that recommendation Monday.
   The Navy's top lawyers disagreed over whether North should be
considered a government officeholder under the terms of the law
that denies pension benefits to officials convicted of destroying
government documents.
   Because of the conflicting opinions, Dickinson said Congress
should act to ensure that benefits earned by North aren't taken
away unjustly.
   James Hinchman, the General Accounting Office lawyer who
reviewed the Navy recommendation for Bowsher, said it was
``impossible to avoid the conclusion that there is serious doubt
that a retired regular officer'' convicted of destroying documents
can continue to receive retirement pay.
   Hinchman said denying retirement pay to North would clear the
way for the former White House aide to seek a court ruling on
whether the law applies to him.
   Dickinson said there remains ``very real and substantial
questions'' about whether the destruction of documents by North
``was done illegally or done within the score of his authority.''
   In a related move, the Senate on Tuesday added language to the
fiscal 1990 defense bill requiring the Senate Judiciary Committee
to study the North pension issue and report back to the Senate by
November.
   The amendment was a substitute for a proposal by Sen. Steve
Symms, R-Idaho, that would have restored the North's full pension.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
