<DOCNO> AP890803-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-Terrorism     08-03 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Terrorism,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Senators Urge Caution in Criticism of Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's supporters in the Senate are urging
colleagues to exercise caution in criticizing the Jewish state for
abducting a Moslem cleric linked with Lebanese terrorists.
   But Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas says Israel must
understand that vital U.S. interests, including the lives of
American hostages, may be at stake when it takes such unilateral
actions as the abduction last week of Shiek Abdul Karim Obeid, a
Moslem religious leader.
   The Lebanese captors of Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins
announced this week they had hanged him to avenge Obeid's
abduction. Higgins' murder has not been independently confirmed,
and there had been reports that he had been killed months ago.
   Dole said earlier this week that Israel had not told Washington
of its intent to kidnap Obeid and said that such ``free-lancing''
might place Americans at risk.
   ``I don't think my remarks have driven any wedge between the
United States and Israel,'' Dole said Wednesday.
   ``My basic message to Israel is this: `We are in this together.
We both have vital interests at stake. Whenever possible we ought
to act together. And always we ought to take into account the vital
interests of the other when we contemplate unilateral action.'
   ``That is the way to avoid any wedge being driven between us,''
he said.
   But other senators said Israel was justified in its actions and
implied Dole may have caused harm by his remarks.
   ``We ought to be very cautious about our criticism of what
Israel has done,'' said Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the
Senate Armed Services Committee.
   ``Certainly all of us have questions, certainly we want to be
able to have a dialogue with Israel and find out some of the things
that they may have known and may still know and we don't know,''
Nunn said.
   ``If there had been a complete release of the prisoners we would
now be saying this was a marvelous, marvelous action. I think we
should be very cautious in rushing to judgment in terms of what the
Israelis have done.''
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said Israel's situation, ``surrounded
constantly _ 360 degrees _ by terrorist groups'' _ should be taken
into consideration.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said Israel's exercise of ``long-arm
jurisdiction'' against an alleged terrorist suspected of violating
Israeli law was justified and is similar to actions against
terrorists taken by the United States.
</TEXT>
