<FIRST>r w PM-Savage-Travels     08-03 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savage-Travels,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Investigating Savage's Trips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., is the subject of a
State Department investigation into his conduct on official foreign
trips, a House member says.
   The decision to send investigators to at least two locations was
made after Inspector General Sherman Funk reviewed cables from
several embassies familiar with Savage's travels since 1984, said
the House member, who spoke Wednesday only on the condition of
anonymity.
   The member did not know the investigators' destinations.
   When asked for comment, Savage aide Donovan Dunkley replied, ``I
don't have anything to say about it,'' and hung up the phone.
   Funk also declined to comment on the investigation, saying only
that any information will be given to the House ethics committee.
The committee has been asked to look into allegations that Savage
fondled a Peace Corps worker against her will during a March visit
to Africa.
   Four newspapers _ The Washington Post, Chicago Tribune, Chicago
Sun-Times and Los Angeles Times _ published stories Wednesday about
the Chicago lawmaker's conduct during a 1986 trip to China.
   Savage was in China as part of a delegation from the House
Science and Technology Committee. The Post reported that Savage
revised his schedule after a few days to go to Hong Kong and South
Korea for shopping and sightseeing.
   Before he moved on to Hong Kong, however, Savage locked himself
in a hotel room to protest the U.S. embassy's failure to
immediately get him on a flight, the Post said, quoting anonymous
officials.
   The Times, citing unnamed witnesses, said Savage returned one
night to his official Beijing guest house with two women he had met
in a disco. Chinese security officials sought to prevent them from
entering, and Savage was seen ``raising hell at the guard
station,'' a source told the newspaper.
   The women were driven back to their hotels in an official car,
the Times reported.
   The House Science Committee issued an 80-page report on the
delegation's work, but Savage's name appears only once.
   ``I regretted that he did not stay with the (delegation) for the
remainder of our schedule,'' delegation chief Rep. James Scheuer,
D-N.Y., told the Post. ``We had a very productive trip.''
</TEXT>
