<DOCNO> AP890803-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages-Hezbollah     08-03 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Hezbollah,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hezbollah Created as Agent of Revolution a Decade Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hezbollah was formed seven years ago and
became an arm of terror for Iran's fundamentalist Shiite Moslem
revolution.
   Western intelligence agencies say black-scarved fanatics of the
Party of God have cut a trail of terror, kidnapping scores of
foreigners in Lebanon, hijacking airliners and killing hundreds of
Americans, Frenchmen and Israelis in suicide bombings.
   They believe Hezbollah's core of 3,500 fighters includes about
150 kidnappers using cover names including Islamic Jihad,
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth and Revolutionary Justice
Organization.
   ``All these groups overlap and in all likelihood are the same
people,'' said Adam Cherski, a specialist on Iran with the
Institute for the Study of Terrorism in London. ``Despite Tehran's
denials, the Iranian influence with these people is very, very
strong.''
   Hezbollah embraces the cult of martyrdom embedded in Shiite
tradition since the 7th century, when Islam was split over the
succession to the prophet Mohammed, founder of the religion.
   It was formed in 1982 by Shiite militants and Iranian
Revolutionary Guards who were sent to the Syrian-controlled Bekaa
Valley of eastern Lebanon to fight Israel's invasion army.
   The organization's roots are in 1969, when plans for a militant
movement were made in Najaf, Iraq, where Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini lived after the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi sent him
into exile.
   In Najaf, Iranian mullahs laid the foundations of the Islamic
revolution that toppled the shah 10 years later.
   Financed by up to $5 million a month of Iranian money, Hezbollah
tried to create another Islamic republic by building religious,
social, educational, agricultural and medical services for 1
million Shiites in Lebanon, the country's largest sect.
   Government authority had been eroded by a long civil war and
Hezbollah made a virtual state within a state while fighting for
control of the Shiite community with a more moderate rival, the
Syrian-backed Amal militia.
   In recent months, mirroring the power struggle in Tehran, four
factions have arisen in Hezbollah.
   One is allied with Iran's new president, Hashemi Rafsanjani, and
another with hard-line Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi. A
third is linked to Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri, once Khomeini's
designated heir, and the small fourth group has aligned itself with
Syria.
   There are indications Rafsanjani, leader of Tehran's so-called
pragmatists who see no future in exporting Khomeini's revolution,
is trying to rein in Shiite zealots in Lebanon.
   Shiite sources say Mohtashemi's influence over Hezbollah began
to decline when Rafsanjani emerged after Khomeini's death June 3 as
Iran's most powerful politician. They say Rafsanjani has sent some
of his allies in the Revolutionary Guards to the Bekaa to contain
the militants.
   Militants in Hezbollah have followed Mohtashemi, but its
political leaders in Beirut's southern slums side with Rafsanjani,
who controls their finances.
   When the movement's spiritual guide, Sheik Mohammad Hussein
Fadlallah, visited Tehran with other Hezbollah leaders in July to
mark the end of 40 days of mourning for Khomeini, he reported to
Rafsanjani.
   Previously, Fadlallah had reported to Mohtashemi or Hussein
Sheikoleslam, deputy foreign minister and a link for years between
Tehran and Hezbollah.
   Sheikoleslam was involved in the 1979 U.S. Embassy seizure in
Tehran. A former student at the University of California at
Berkeley, he trained with the Palestine Liberation Organization in
southern Lebanon in 1977 and was an interrogator of the U.S.
hostages in Tehran.
   He had close ties to Hezbollah in the early 1980s, when he was
based in Damascus and Mohtashemi was ambassador to Syria.
   U.S. intelligence has linked both men to suicide bombings in
1983 and 1984, including an attack on the U.S. Marine base in
Beirut that killed more than 240 military personnel.
   A central figure in Hezbollah violence is Imad Mughniyeh, 36,
its chief of security.
   Western intelligence agencies list him as leader of Islamic
Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, which holds two U.S. hostages. He is
believed to be the brains behind scores of kidnappings.
   Mughniyeh is wanted by the United States in the 1985 hijacking
of a TWA jetliner in which a U.S. Navy diver was killed and 33
Americans were held hostage 17 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
