<FIRST>r w AM-Ambassador-Watergate     08-03 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ambassador-Watergate,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moore Denies Watergate Listing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nominee as ambassador to
Ireland says he wasn't an unindicted co-conspirator in the
Watergate scandal.
   Members of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee asked Richard
A. Moore on Wednesday if had been one of the 18 unindicted
co-conspirators while he was an adviser to President Nixon. The
names have never been made public.
   ``No, sir, I was not,'' Moore told committee Chairman Claiborne
Pell, D-R.I.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., who served on the House Judiciary
Committee that voted impeachment charges against Nixon, also asked
Moore whether reports in the mid-1970s were true that he had been
one of the 18.
   ``False, totally,'' Moore replied.
   The committee is expected to approve Moore's nomination today,
with floor approval expected Friday. Nixon appointed Moore's
brother, John, ambassador to Ireland in 1969, a post he held for an
unprecedented six years.
   Meanwhile, the Senate confirmed Shirley Temple Black as U.S.
ambassador to Czechoslovakia. Mrs. Black, the former child actress,
has been ambassador to Ghana and served in a number of positions at
the United Nations.
   Four of Bush's other nominees also won confirmation:
   _William Howard Taft IV, a former deputy secretary of defense,
as U.S. representative to the Council of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   _Joseph Bernard Gildenhorn, a Washington lawyer and real estate
developer who gave nearly $200,000 to Republican Party causes since
1984, as ambassador to Switzerland.
   _Thomas P. Melady as ambassador to the Vatican
   _Keith Lapham Brown as ambassador to Denmark.
   Moore described an April 19, 1973, meeting with Nixon, saying he
told the president how he had urged Dean to come clean and tell
Nixon all he knew about the cover-up. Dean subsequently took his
advice, Moore said.
   According to Nixon's autobiography, Moore was more than just an
adviser.
   ``My friend and White House Special Counsel Dick Moore suggested
that I consider Assistant Attorney General William Rehnquist for
the other vacancy'' on the Supreme Court, Nixon wrote.
   Such was his trust in Moore's advice, that Nixon did name
Rehnquist, now chief justice, to the high court in 1972.
</TEXT>
