<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0524EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FederalPay     08-03 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Federal Pay,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Defense Bill Includes Novel Pay Provisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy and Defense departments will be
allowed to hire ``double dipper'' retirees and give huge salary
increases to critical technical personnel under the Senate's
version of the Defense authorization bill.
   The pay provisions are considered unprecedented.
   Some 525 scientists and engineers, 500 from Defense and 25 from
Energy, could thus get $134,250 per year, more than anybody in the
government except the president.
   The president makes $200,000; the vice president $110,000 and
members of Congress and Cabinet officers get $89,500.
   Current law forbids military officers from getting a pension if
they return to the government payroll, a practice called ``double
dipping.''
   The defense bill for the next fiscal year would permit the
Pentagon to hire 1,000 retired officers, and the Energy Department
250, who could still draw full pensions. The provision tries to
encourage specialists to take critical jobs.
   The Pentagon also would be authorized to set up four pilot
programs under which the department could adjust rank and pay of a
total of 100,000 civilian employees, giving the department a
flexibility that current law forbids.
   Individuals could receive pay increases as long as total payroll
costs did not change.
   Other government departments could operate a total of six such
programs. The Office of Personnel Management would have to approve
the provisions of these programs.
   The House version of the defense bill includes no such
provisions. A conference committee will have to produce an
agreed-upon version of the bill in September.
   Both versions include a 3.6 percent pay raise for Pentagon
employees.
</TEXT>
