<FIRST>r i PM-Thailand-USDrugs     08-03 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thailand-US Drugs,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Grand Jury Indicts Police General for Heroin Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. grand jury has indicted a Thai
police general on charges of smuggling heroin into the United
States, an American government official said today.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a federal
grand jury in Brooklyn, N.Y., indicted Assistant Police Inspector
Maj. Gen. Vech Pechborom on four counts July 13. Vech denied the
charges.
   The indictment followed more than four years of investigation by
the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in cooperation with Thai
police, the official said.
   U.S. action against Vech is limited, however, because the law in
Thailand forbids the extradition of a Thai national.
   The U.S. official said the DEA charged that Vech was a part of a
Southeast Asian ring that smuggled heroin into the United States at
least 15 times. The drug agency said the operation was based in
Chinatown in New York City and in Los Angeles, and that
Asian-Americans controlled it.
   The official said 22 members of the ring were arrested between
October 1984 and July 1988 in Bangkok, Japan, South Korea, New
Zealand, Hawaii, New York and Los Angeles, and that authorities
seized 77 pounds of heroin.
   Northern Thailand forms part of the ``Golden Triangle,'' the
source of more than 40 percent of the heroin reaching the United
States, the official said.
   He said that according to the indictment, Vech helped arrange
shipments of heroin from Thailand, directed financial investment in
a courier network and used his influence to get drugs through
Bangkok's airport.
   The indictment said Vech directed the shipment of 11 pounds of
heroin that was seized at John F. Kennedy Airport in New York City
in November 1984. Authorities arrested two Thais for possessing the
drug, including a second lieutenant in the Royal Thai Air Force.
   In a telephone interview today, Vech said: ``I deny the charge
and confirm that I am innocent. It has hurt me a lot.''
   Vech said he he did not know Suvit Taechaphana, the alleged
ringleader, who was sentenced in a Los Angeles court last month to
30 years in prison.
   Suvit was arrested in July 1988 and pleaded guilty to charges of
conspiracy to import heroin into the United States.
   A Thai police spokesman said the national police chief, Gen. Pow
Sarasin, on Wednesday appointed a committee headed by a deputy
police chief to investigate the charges against Vech.
</TEXT>
