<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CannibalismDig     08-03 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Dig,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests Supporting Prospector's Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19th century gold prospector may have
been telling the truth, according to a team studying the man's
claims he only killed one of his five prospecting companions.
   Alferd Packer was convicted in 1885 of killing the other five
members of the party and was sentenced to 40 years in prison. But,
although he admitted resorting to cannibalism to stay alive after
the group became stranded in the snow, Packer maintained until his
death that he had killed only one.
   A study of the prospectors' remains support that claim, Walter
Birkby, curator of physical anthropology at the University of
Arizona, said Wednesday.
   The remains were exhumed last month from their resting place in
the Rockies near Lake City, Colo., and are being studied at the
University of Arizona.
   Examinations of and tests on the bones of the five showed signs
that flesh was scraped off with a knife, Birkby said. The four
skulls removed from a common grave also showed signs of hatchet
blows, he said.
   The fifth skull was gone when the bones were buried in August
1874.
   Anthropologists have taken on the challenge to see if they can
determine the real story through scientific detection and see if
Packer was wrongly convicted.
   Packer insisted he shot only one of the men and hit him in the
head with a hatchet in self defense. Packer said the man had killed
the four others with a hatchet.
   Birkby said findings included a bullet hole in the pelvic bone
of one of the skeletons.
   The study team might be able to attach names to bones with
further study of the remains, which include buttons, belt buckles
and some partially decomposed clothing, Birkby said.
   The study team was assembled by James Starrs, a law professor at
George Washington University in Washington, D.C. Starrs has said
that final results of the study will be detailed at the annual
meeting of the American Academy of Forensic Sciences in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
