<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Stallings 500   08-03 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stallings, 500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Priest Fired by Bishop After Joining Dissident Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Richmond, Va. priest fired from his job by
his Roman Catholic bishop for trying to set up a separate
African-American Catholic congregation now seeks to ``challenge
other black priests.''
   The Rev. Bruce Greening announced Wednesday he would join the
Rev. George A. Stallings in setting up a separate African-American
Catholic congregation.
   ``What is happening at Imani Temple is in my opinion the right
method to take,'' Greening said, referring to the congregation set
up by Stallings, himself suspended by Washington Archbishop James
Hickey.
   Greening said he wanted ``to challenge other black priests and
other black sisters'' to follow Stallings' example.
   Greening, 38, was fired by the Catholic Diocese of Richmond, for
which he had worked since 1988 as the principal of an elementary
school in Norfolk. The priest, a member of the Society of the
Divine Savior, in Milwaukee, Wis., had requested a leave of absence
from his Virginia job to set up a separate congregation for blacks.
   He remains a priest.
   ``By the very fact of his free decision, Father Greening
automatically dissociates himself from the Diocese of Richmond,''
said Richmond Bishop Walter F. Sullivan. ``I am relieving him of
his duties as principal of St. Mary's Academy in Norfolk, effective
immediately.''
   Stallings, who has strongly criticized the Catholic Church,
accusing its leaders of not meeting the needs of its black members,
said Greening would assist him as a minister and in forming a
school at the month-old Imani Temple.
   The Rev. Keith Brennan, spokesman for the Society of the Divine
Savior, Salvatorian Order in Wisconsin, said no action had been
taken there by Greening's provincial, the Rev. Paul Portland.
   ``This is the first time that we have had anything like this
happen,'' said Brennan. ```We are trying to find as much
information about what occurred, and what our obligations are
within the law of the church.''
   Brennan said the Wisconsin office would first hold an internal
meeting and would then call Greening back to his home office for an
explanation.
   He said that Greening was the only black priest among 123 at the
Wisconsin religious order.
   In Atlanta, meanwhile, black Catholics are poised to begin today
their annual layman's conference, the first major gathering of
black Catholics since Stallings founded his splinter group.
   The Rev. James Goode, a San Francisco priest who will attend the
Atlanta conference, praised Stallings' movement as ``a beautiful
time of coming together of African-American Catholics across the
country.''
   At the press conference in Washington, Greening said he had been
warned by the Richmond bishop against becoming involved with
Stallings.
   Stallings, who appeared with Greening, said the congregation of
the Imani Temple would be meeting Aug. 19 to discuss the issues
they feel should be at the forefront of the church's agenda.
   ``We're going to look at teen-age pregnancy and the drug
epidemic in our community,'' he said. ``We see these issues as
being systematic of greater issues in our society.'' Other
priorities for the black community are unemployment and education,
Stallings said.
   He also said the Imani Temple has received several requests from
other cities to help them establish other African-American
congregations.
   Stallings said although he has his eye set on certain cities he
felt would respond enthusiastically, he first wanted to set the
groundwork for the ``Mother Church.''
</TEXT>
