<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0545EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Disabled-CivilRights     08-03 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disabled-Civil Rights,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House, Senate Agree to Bar Discrimination Against Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disabled Americans could enjoy civil rights
protections with a comprehensive measure approved by the Bush
administration and key senators.
   The Americans with Disabilities Act sailed unanimously through
the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee Wednesday and is
expected to be approved by the full Senate.
   ``This historic legislation will end segregation and
discrimination against people with disabilities in all aspects of
American society,'' said a statement released jointly by
co-sponsors of the measure, Sens. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa, and David Durenburger, R-Minn.
   The measure was hailed by civil rights groups as well as AIDS
advocacy organizations.
   Ralph G. Neas, director of the leadership conference on civil
rights, a coalition of 180 national organizations, said the bill is
``probably the most comprehensive civil rights measure since the
1964 Civil Rights Act.
   The agreement between President Bush and the senators was ``a
fair compromise that resulted in a strong and effective bill,'' he
said.
   Disability rights groups have been lobbying for years to give
the nation's estimated 37 million disabled Americans, including
people with AIDS, the same civil rights protections as minorities
and women.
   The AIDS Action Council said the measure marked ``a turning
point in the federal response to the challenges'' of the AIDS
epidemic.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush favors allowing
``maximum flexibility to implement effective solutions'' and
bringing the disabled into the mainstream ``without imposing undue
burdens.''
   ``The president believes this can be accomplished by using
reasonable measures, phased over time, as this legislation does,''
he said. ``The president has pursued a common sense approach,
seeking a practical bill that will help the disabled reach their
full potential.''
   The agreement provides for:
   _Federal protection for the disabled against job discrimination,
paralleling existing protections that apply to organizations that
receive federal funds. Initially, the new requirement would apply
to employers of 25 or more, but eventually it would cover employers
with at least 15 workers.
   _A ban on discrimination against the disabled in public
accommodations, including restaurants, stores and health care
facilities.
   _Enforcement of these new civil rights protections through the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission ``and suits seeking
injunctive relief.''
   Fitzwater said ``a core group of public accommodations would be
required to make readily achievable alterations to existing
facilities to accommodate the disabled.''
   ``This legislation is designed to achieve access for the
disabled in the most efficient manner, with emphasis on making new
buildings accessible,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
