<FIRST>r a PM-F-14Crash     08-03 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-F-14 Crash,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy F-14 Crashes in Pacific, Both Crewmen Eject Safely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy fighter jet crashed into the Pacific
Ocean after developing engine trouble, and both occupants ejected
safely, a Navy spokesman said.
   The pilot and radar-intercept officer of the F-14 Tomcat were
rescued by a Navy helicopter about two miles offshore from Point
Loma.
   Their names were not immediately released. Both suffered only
minor bumps and bruises and were taken to Balboa Naval Hospital in
San Diego for overnight observation, said Navy spokesman Joe Ciokon.
   Navy crews, aided by the U.S. Coast Guard, began trying to
salvage what remained of the $40 million warplane Wednesday night
as Navy officials began an investigation into the cause of the
crash, Ciokon said.
   The twin-engine jet had just taken off from the nuclear-powered
aircraft carrier Carl Vinson on a training mission at about 6 p.m.
Wednesday when it developed engine trouble. The carrier, based at
the Alameda Naval Air Station near Oakland, was on a training
exercise, Ciokon said.
   The pilot was attempting an emergency landing at North Island
Naval Air Station on the Coronado Peninsula when the two fliers
decided to eject, said Cmdr. Doug Schamp, another Navy spokesman.
   It was the second F-14 from the Vinson to crash within two
weeks, and the third Navy jet to crash off San Diego during that
period.
   It also was the 102nd F-14 crash since the fighter, built by
Grumman Aerospace Corp., was introduced as the Navy's front-line
fighter in 1972.
</TEXT>
