<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief, 600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucas Failed ``Litmus Test,'' says Thornburgh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is convinced
that William Lucas did not get the civil rights post because he
refused to criticize recent Supreme Court decisions.
   The attorney general said Wednesday he discounted the
significance of criticism by several Democrats on the Senate
Judiciary Committee that Lucas lacked expertise for the job.
   Lucas, 61, a former sheriff and chief executive of Wayne County,
Mich., has never tried a court case. The panel refused Tuesday on a
pair of 7-7 votes to recommend Lucas' nomination or send it to the
Senate floor for further consideration.
   Thornburgh said ``Mr. Lucas supported the views of the president
and the attorney general in this regard'' when he testified that no
legislation was needed at this time to overturn the rulings.
   ``I find it somewhat bizarre to expect an appointee of the
president to begin his career in opposition to the president in an
important area of the law,'' Thornburgh said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Cavazos Gets Cool Reception on Key Education Initiatives</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos is
finding it difficult to sell the administration's idea of
``parental choice'' to the chairman of the Education and Labor
Committee.
   Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., made clear Wednesday he was
not impressed by Cavazos' plea for support for proposals
emphasizing parental involvement that he said were needed to
revitalize school systems.
   Although initiatives outlined by Cavazos have been embraced in
principle by the Senate education panel and the House
Appropriations Committee, Hawkins told Cavazos he sees ``some
dangerous trends in the proposals being advocated.''
   For example, he characterized the parental choice approach to
school selection for their children as ``a very dangerous idea that
has not been fully scrutinized.''
   ``The selling of choice reminds me of the medicine man selling
snake oil,'' said Hawkins.
   The veteran committee chairman has been a major force in most of
the federal education legislation passed in recent years.
