<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Attorney General Urges Approval of International Drug Treaty</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee is
being urged to ratify an international anti-drug trafficking treaty.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh told the panel Wednesday the
pact will ``provide us with enhanced law enforcement tools and can
lead to substantial advances in our international cooperative
efforts'' to counter the illegal drug market.
   Thornburgh signed the U.N. Convention Against Illicit Traffic in
Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances on behalf of the United
States last December in Vienna.
   The treaty includes a provision under which ``all the nations
signing the convention have agreed to exchange evidence of criminal
conduct and to extradite accused traffickers so that safe havens
are no longer so readily available,'' he said.
   However, Thornburgh noted in response to questions from Chairman
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I, that the treaty does not obligate countries
to extradite their own nationals wanted on drug-related charges in
other countries.
</TEXT>
