<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     08-03 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Playwright Released After 11 Hours of Detention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vaclav Havel, the banned Czechoslovak
playwright, said today police detained him for 11 hours and warned
him upon his release that he may face similar treatment if he
``moves around and speaks with people.''
   Havel said he was detained Wednesday on his way to a lunch with
the West German ambassador at the nation's embassy in Prague. It
was the second day in a row that police picked him up; they
detained Havel for about three hours on Tuesday.
   ``The police told me that if I'm in Prague they don't like me to
move around and speak with people because I may face the same
troubles again, '' Havel said today in a telephone interview from
Prague.
   He said he arrived in Czechoslovakia's capital early this week
from his summer cottage in eastern Bohemia.
   ``They said they are not interested if I have lunch with an
ambassador when I'm in Prague but they don't like me to meet with
(my countrymen),'' Havel said.
   Havel, Czechoslovakia's most prominent human rights campaigner,
was jailed for eight months earlier this year but released on
parole midway through the sentence after unprecedented protests at
home and abroad.
   Officials say Havel and some other writers have remained under
prohibition because of their refusal to renounce political
activities.
   Czechoslovak human rights activists are campaigning increasingly
for an official revision of the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion that
crushed the ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   The Aug. 21 anniversary of the invasion is expected to result in
renewed anti-government protests.
   Politburo member and Prague party boss Miroslav Stepan said
Tuesday that authorities would not tolerate disruptions in August.
   Czechoslovak authorities have harshly condemned a current
petition, known as Several Sentences, that demands more democratic
reforms.
   More than 11,500 people, including Havel, have signed the
petition, say human rights activists in Prague.
</TEXT>
