<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryFinancing     08-03 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Financing,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Plans To Borrow $39.5 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department says it plans to
borrow $39.5 billion from the public next week in a series of debt
auctions being held to replenish the government's depleted coffers.
   Treasury officials said Wednesday the auctions are contingent on
passage by Congress this week of a bill to raise the limit on
federal borrowing by $70 billion to a record $2.87 trillion.
   The House approved the measure on Tuesday and it is expected to
win Senate approval before Congress begins a month-long recess on
Saturday.
   The administration has warned lawmakers that failure to boost
the debt ceiling before the August recess would force the
government into an unprecedented default on its bills on Aug. 15.
   Treasury Undersecretary Robert Glauber told reporters Wednesday
that the debt auctions scheduled for next week are contingent on
final passage of the increase in the debt limit. The national debt
as of Tuesday stood only $25 million below the current ceiling of
$2.8 trillion.
   According to Wednesday's announcement, the auctions for next
week will include:
   _$10 billion in three-year notes in minimum denominations of
$5,000 to be auctioned Tuesday.
   _$9.75 billion in 10-year notes in minimum denominations of
$1,000 to be auctioned Wednesday.
   _$9.75 billion in 30-year bonds in minimum denominations of
$1,000 to be auctioned Thursday.
   These notes and bonds are sold regularly during the large debt
auctions which are held four times a year.
   In addition, for this series of debt auctions the government
said it would also sell $10 billion in cash management bills that
would mature on April 19, 1990. These bills will be sold in minimum
denominations of $10,000.
</TEXT>
