<FIRST>r a PM-WaterTank-Body     08-03 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Tank-Body,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Decomposed Body Found in Water Tank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, W. Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers found a decomposed body in a
water tank after residents complained their water smelled and
tasted foul, authorities said.
   Tap water stored in the 100,000-gallon tank posed no danger to
residents, said Steve Edgemon, a manager for the West Virginia
America Water Co.
   ``It was really, really bad,'' said 16-year-old David Woolwine.
``Even when it wasn't looking bad, it smelled.''
   About 45 residents supplied by the tank were told to boil their
water, Edgemon said Wednesday after the body was found. Test
results received Wednesday morning showed no bacteria in the water
to indicate something had died in the tank, he said.
   Officials at the company's main treatment plant added extra
chlorine to supplies and flushed the lines surrounding the tank,
Edgemon said.
   ``I think I'll drink bottled water for a while,'' said resident
Pat Veneri.
   State Medical Examiner Irvin M. Sopher said the remains could be
those of a man who was reported missing since about June 20.
   Police refused to reveal the man's name or details concerning
his disappearance. Authorities also refused to speculate on the
cause of death.
   Water company workers found the access hatch to the 40-foot tank
open and a man's clothing on top, Edgemon said.
</TEXT>
