<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Shipwreck     08-03 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Shipwreck,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Soviets Dead After Ship Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two boats that participated in a training mission
organized by a sailing club were lost in the Azov Sea and 10 of the
12 people on board drowned, Tass reported today.
   The official news agency said the boats, including yachts,
sloops and motorboats, were part of a nine-vessel mission that
began in Mariupol, an Azov seaport about 620 miles south of Moscow.
   The flotilla set out July 15 and all but two boats arrived at
their destinations, it said.
   The other two, with a total of 12 people on board, were reported
last Friday to have been located at Kosa Dolga, a peninsula. On
Monday, the bodies of 10 sailors washed ashore.
   Two people, a 17-year-old girl and 8-year-old boy identified by
Tass as passengers, survived but were unable to give authorities
details of the accident. They were sleeping and awoke one morning
to find the crew missing because of ``unknown circumstances,'' Tass
said.
   The accident is under investigation, but Tass said carelessness
was involved because the boats did not have any radio contact with
shore or between themselves.
</TEXT>
