<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0912EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hostages-Higgins     08-03 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Higgins,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Ministry Says Obeid Heard Higgins Was Alive Last Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry today quoted a Shiite
Moslem clergyman as saying that U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R.
Higgins may have been alive last week, contrary to reports he was
killed months ago.
   An Israeli official said the clergyman, Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid,
may be given lie detector tests to help establish when Higgins died.
   A pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem group, the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth, claimed it hanged Higgins on Monday in
retaliation for Israel's refusal to free Obeid, who was kidnapped
by Israeli commandos July 28.
   Higgins was abducted Feb. 17, 1988, in south Lebanon.
   Despite Obeid's statements about Higgins, Israel officially says
it received word months ago that Higgins had been killed.
   An Israeli official said that during the interrogation, Obeid
gave the impression that he was ``afraid'' to be extradited to the
United States.
   Obeid has been isolated since his capture and has no knowledge
of reports Higgins has been hanged to avenge his abduction.
   Some Israeli officials claim Obeid was a ``central figure'' in
the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, an umbrella for factions holding
foreign hostages that also is believed to have provided support for
attacks and car bombings. But other sources in Israel and Lebanon
minimize his importance, describing him more as a religious leader
or a ``cheerleader.''
   A statement released today by Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin's
spokesman, Eitan Haber, said ``in his interrogation, Sheik Obeid
stated that while he personally has no information concerning Col.
Higgins' condition, he heard through hearsay that Col. Higgins is
alive.''
   It said Obeid told Israeli interrogators Higgins arrived in
Beirut shortly after he was kidnapped last year and was in good
condition. ``I am in no position to know what happened to him or
might have happened to him afterward,'' it quoted Obeid as saying.
   The statement quoted Defense Ministry sources as saying they
wanted to ``emphasize and reiterate that in accordance with the
information presently available to them, Col. Higgins was put to
death in Beirut already at the end of 1988 but that the ministry
has no definite confirmation of this.''
   Avi Pazner, a top aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
Israel believes Higgins died as a result of ``mistreatment and
torture'' and that there is ``strong evidence'' he died more than a
year ago.
   An Israeli official, asking not to be identified, said Obeid may
undergo a polygraph test to determine exactly what he knows. The
official said Israel believes Obeid is not telling all he knows
about the Marine's fate.
   Higgins, 44, of Lexington, Ky., was part of a U.N. observer
force in Lebanon when he was abducted. His captors accused him of
spying.
   After the July 1988 shooting down of an Iranian jetliner by a
U.S. warship in the Persian Gulf, the kidnappers announced that
Higgins had been sentenced to death.
   Israel said it captured Obeid in an effort to use the cleric to
free three missing Israel soldiers in Lebanon. It has offered to
exchange him and other Shiite captives for three captured Israeli
soldiers in Lebanon and the foreign hostages in Lebanon. Hezbollah
rejected a swap.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
