<FIRST>u i PM-Tunisia-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0520 08-03 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tunisia-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0520,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatah Movement Opens Congress, Higgins Killing on Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Arafat speech. Pickup 7th
pvs, ``Tunisian authorities ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fatah movement of the PLO opened its
first general congress in nine years today with Chairman Yasser
Arafat saying the goal of a Palestinian state may be realized soon.
   ``Fatah is entrusted with a historical responsibility that
becomes more important as we approach the objective,'' Arafat told
the congress, the fifth since Fatah was founded in Kuwait in 1959.
   Independence is ``a stone's throw away,'' he said, referring to
the stone-throwing Palestinians who have been conducting an
uprising in Israeli-occupied territories for 19 months.
   Arafat said he would favor elections in the territories if they
were a step toward creating an independent Palestinian state.
Israelis officials have said they will not allow a Palestinian
state in the territories.
   Tunisian President Zine Abidine Ben Ali opened the congress
saying ``breaches have appeared in the Israeli consensus concerning
the idea of the creation of an independent Palestinian state.''
   ``The just Palestinian cause has won new victories even inside
Israel, where the voices of some important forces have been raised
to call for negotiations with the PLO,'' Ben Ali said.
   Tunisian authorities took special security precautions to
protect delegates. Helicopters and F-5 fighter planes of the
Tunisian air force flew overhead today as they gathered at Congress
Hall in Tunis. The date and precise location of the meeting were
not made public until the day before it began.
   In October 1985, Israeli jets bombed the PLO general
headquarters in a Tunis suburb.
   Five Fatah central committee members have been assassinated or
expelled since the last Fatah congress in 1980 and are to be
replaced. The most prominent candidate was Intissar Wazir, widow of
Khalil Wazir.
   Wazir, also known as Abu Jihad, was assassinated by Israeli
commandos in Tunis two years ago.
   Another leading candidate was Hakam Balawi, the PLO
representative to Tunisia who has been the main Palestinian
official in regular talks with U.S. Ambassador Robert Pelletreau.
   Other major contenders included Sfar Habbash, or Abu Nizar _
known as the ``poet of the Palestinian revolution'' _ and two
Palestinian officers, Gen. Mohamed Jihad and Col. Nasser Youssef.
   The congress also will elect new members to the Fatah
Revolutionary Council, a 100-member body which meets regularly
under the Central Committee.
   The congress is due to consider a report from the central
committee on the uprising in Israel and propose ways to increase
Palestinian pressure on Israeli occupation forces.
   Arafat is president of the Central Committee. Despite some
hard-liners objecting to his policies, his position is not likely
to be affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
