<FIRST>r i PM-QueenMumPortrait     08-03 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Queen Mum Portrait,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Gallery Expects Portrait Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stark new portrait of Queen Mother Elizabeth
that was unveiled today may cause controversy, officials at the
National Gallery say.
   The painting, by 23-year-old Alison Watt of Glasgow, shows
Britain's most famous great-grandmother without her customary hat,
wearing a simple dress and staring almost grimly out of the canvas.
   ``I think it will shock people for about 10 to 15 seconds, then
they will get used to it, and in six months' time it will be one of
the most popular portraits of her,'' said Robin Gibson, the
gallery's curator of 20th century portraits. ``It is taking the lid
off the chocolate box.''
   The Queen Mother, who marks her 89th birthday Friday, is the
widow of King George VI and the mother of Queen Elizabeth II.
   Ms. Watt admitted that the portrait didn't look particularly
royal but that was her intention. ``She always appears fluffy,
light, wearing flowing clothes and I wanted to make her more solid.
She has a lot of character,'' Ms. Watt said. ``I didn't want her to
come across as a wee waif.''
   The Queen Mother, Ms. Watt asserted, was happy with the
portrait, but that could not be confirmed.
   ``I do not know what the Queen Mother thinks of it,'' said a
spokesman at her residence, Clarence House, who spoke on condition
of anonymity. ``Presumably she has seen it because she sat for it,
but we do not issue statements on silly little things like this.''
</TEXT>
