<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1008EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     08-03 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenade Attack on Israeli Patrol Injures Three Soldiers, Three Civilians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hand grenade thrown at a passing Israeli
patrol today injured three Israeli soldiers and three Palestinian
civilians in the occupied Gaza Strip, the army and Arab reports
said.
   Troops opened fire after the blast, wounding more than a dozen
Palestinians on the main street in Khan Yunis town, hospital
officials said.
   In another development, the Supreme Court ruled today that the
army's firing orders for plastic bullets are legal.
   Use of the bullets, introduced in August as a less-lethal
alternative to lead bullets, was challenged by Israeli attorney
Felicia Langer.
   In the grenade attack, the army said the soldiers were
hospitalized with slight injuries.
   A curfew ordering people off the streets was imposed on the town
of more than 30,000 people, the army said.
   Doctors at Nasser Hospital in Khan Yunis said 16 Palestinians
were admitted with wounds, but they were unsure if the grenade
victims were among them.
   Those injured included a 2-year-old boy, a 75-year-old man and
60-year-old woman, the doctors said.
   Also today, John Kelly, visiting assistant secretary of state
for Middle East Affairs, met with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   ``I am not going to be able to get into details of what we
discussed, but I did want to say it was a very useful discussion,''
Kelly told reporters after the hour-long meeting.
   Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokesman, said Kelly met privately with
Shamir for 10 minutes and then was joined by aides to discuss
Israel's peace initiative.
   Shamir has called for elections in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip to help end the Palestinian revolt by selecting
Palestinians to open talks with Israel on an interim autonomy
agreement. The plan also calls for Arab countries to make peace
with Israel.
   ``Mr. Shamir said that for him it was particularly important
that the United States should take up with the Arabs the question
of a change in their relationship with Israel, either make peace or
sign non-belligerency treaties,'' Pazner said.
   He also said Shamir complained about the U.S. dialogue with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, saying it is interfering with
Israel's efforts to get talks going with Palestinians from the
occupied lands.
   The Supreme Court judges said they cannot rule on the legality
of a particular weapon or ammunition, only on its use.
   ``There is no evidence of illegal orders being given,'' the
court concluded in response to a suit urging it to block use of the
plastic ammunition or put strict limits on when it can be fired.
   ``It is lethal, and the regulations should be the same'' as for
lead bullets, Ms. Langer had argued.
   Army rules call for lead ammunition to be used only when a
soldier's life is in danger. Plastic ammunition can be fired to
break up demonstrations. The army says it is not lethal if fired
from 230 feet or more.
   Human rights group say at least 100 of 527 Palestinians shot to
death in the 19-month-old uprising died from plastic bullets.
Thirty-eight Israeli civilians also have died in the violence.
</TEXT>
