<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     08-03 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Premier Wants Elections 90 Days After Vietnamese Withdraw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Hun Sen of Cambodia said he hopes free
elections can be held by the end of the year following Vietnam's
military withdrawal.
   Hun Sen also met Wednesday with his main rival, resistance
leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk, who likened the meeting to one
between ``a father and son'' and expressed sympathy for Hun Sen.
   The two are in Paris for peace negotiations, which have reached
an impasse.
   Vietnam invaded neighboring Cambodia in December 1978 and has
said its military withdrawal will be completed by Sept. 27. Hun
Sen, the head of Cambodia's Hanoi-sponsored government, said he
wants elections held within three months of the pullout.
   ``I do not wish to prolong things, because if you wait too long
... there is more possibility for violations, instability,'' he
said at his hotel. ``This will be the object of discussion with the
other parties, but three months is our position.''
   The United States and 18 other nations at the talks agreed
earlier this week to send the investigation team to help prepare
for a permanent peace settlement in war-ravaged Cambodia.
   But negotiations between Hun Sen and leaders of the three-party
Cambodian resistance alliance led by Sihanouk reached an impasse
after two days of negotiations. Sihanouk ruled Cambodia until he
was overthrown in March 1970, during the Indochina war.
   Hun Sen blames the breakdown in negotiations on the communist
Khmer Rouge, the most powerful resistance faction, which he said
refuses to resume the talks. The Khmer Rouge's role in a future
government in Cambodia has been a main sticking point at the
conference.
   Pol Pot and the Khmer Rouge governed Cambodia from the war's end
in April 1975 until the Vietnamese invasion. An estimated 1 million
people were killed or died of starvation under the brutal regime.
   After Hun Sen and Sihanouk met Wednesday night, the prince
expressed an ``affinity, a mutual sympathy'' for his rival. He
described Hun Sen's government and the Khmer Rouge as the key
rivals in Cambodia and himself as ``a sandwich between the hammer
and anvil.''
   A conference of 19 nations continues its work on a peace
settlement despite the disagreements among the four Cambodian
factions.
   In a three-day meeting that ended Tuesday, foreign ministers set
up committees to come up with a plan for monitoring the withdrawal
and an ensuing cease-fire, to deal with sovereignty questions and
to plan for repatriation of refugees. A committee of the Cambodian
factions also was created.
   All committees are to present their proposals to the foreign
ministers at another meeting in Paris on Aug. 28. A U.N.
fact-finding mission will aid the monitoring committee.
   The United Nations recognizes the resistance coalition as
Cambodia's legitimate representative.
</TEXT>
