<FIRST>r a PM-JurorArrest     08-03 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Juror Arrest,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Undercover Narcotics Agent Spots Juror as Person who Sold him Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sitting on a grand jury hearing testimony
from undercover narcotics officers was arrested after an officer
identified him as a dealer who once sold him heroin.
   Anthony Eisenberg, 23, was listening to an undercover narcotics
officer testifying before the grand jury he was serving on July 18.
   ``The officer looked at Mr. Eisenberg and Mr. Eisenberg looked
at him and there was a nod of recognition,'' G. Christopher Marzuk,
a prosecutor with the Office of the Special Narcotics Prosecutor,
told The New York Times Wednesday.
   The next day, after reviewing his notes about the May 26 sale of
two glassine envelopes of heroin, the officer returned to the jury
room, where the suspect was quietly removed and arrested.
   ``A lot of people said that it was the stupidest thing in the
world for him to go down there and sit on the narcotics grand
jury,'' Marzuk said. ``On the other hand, it could also have been
the smartest thing in the world, because if Mr. Eisenberg had gone
for the full month of the grand jury's term _ sat through 100 or
150 cases _ he could have learned who all of our undercover
officers are and which ones were working in his area.''
   Eisenberg saw seven undercover agents during his 1{ days as a
grand juror.
   He was indicted on charges of felony sale of narcotics.
</TEXT>
