<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1049EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Texaco-BackTaxes 1stLd-Writethru a0541 08-03 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texaco-Back Taxes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco, Exxon Say IRS Seeking Back Taxes on Cheap Saudi Oil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with comment from Exxon spokesman,
explain that IRS claims surfaced from Texaco bankruptcy audit, IRS officials
declining to comment. No pickup. A longer version moved on the financial
wire as PM-Oil-IRS.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has billed Exxon
Corp. and Texaco Inc. for more than $2 billion in back taxes and
interest, but the huge oil companies said they will challenge the
claims in court.
   Texaco said Wednesday the IRS claims the oil company owns $1.79
billion in taxes from 1979 to 1981, when it sold oil to its
affiliates at below-market value.
   Exxon Corp. said the IRS has billed it $269 million for 1979 in
connection with oil the government of Saudi Arabia sold to Exxon
and Texaco in a bid to stabilize the world crude market. Interest
on the Exxon payments could double the amount of money the IRS
seeks.
   ``They're trying to get us to pay for something we never earned
and which the American public benefited from,'' said Exxon
spokesman Bill Smith. ``We sold oil at lower prices. The American
public got the benefit of those lower prices.''
   Exxon said it had filed a petition in the U.S. Tax Court in
Washington over the IRS bill. Texaco, based in White Plains, said
it also would fight the IRS claim.
   The IRS had notified Texaco about possible claims stemming from
the earlier oil transaction with the Saudis during an audit last
year in connection with Texaco's Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization.
   The IRS claims are over the handling of crude oil purchased from
Saudi Arabia during 1979-1981, when the official price set by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was $34 a barrel.
   Saudi Arabia, OPEC's largest exporter, was selling its crude for
$28 a barrel to Texaco, Exxon, Mobil Corp. and Chevron Corp., its
four partners in the Arabian American Oil Co. with the provision
that if any of the companies resold the oil, they could not resell
it at a profit.
   Texaco said the IRS apparently believed that when it resold the
crude to its foreign affiliates, it should have charged the $34
rate despite the restrictions by Saudia Arabia _ and paid taxes on
the difference.
   Because it did not, Texaco said it is being held liable for
taxes on the profits that its foreign affiliates made by being able
to sell refined products made from the cheaper Saudi oil.
   IRS officials have declined to comment on the matter, saying
federal law prohibits the agency from commenting on the affairs of
any taxpayer.
   ``Texaco maintains that the IRS's position is wrong, and that it
cannot tax the company for revenues it never received when it
resold the Arabian crude and which, under mandate of the Saudi
Arabian government, it could not receive,'' Texaco said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
