<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Rafsanjani 1stLd-Writethru a0490 08-03 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Rafsanjani, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Sworn in as President, Hails Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Rafsanjani speech. ADDS byline.
Pickup 5th graf `Rafsanjani won...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani was
sworn in today as president and pledged to continue the 10-year-old
Islamic revolution, Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
   ``Despite the propaganda coming from the arrogant world powers,
our people will not accept anything but the continuation of this
path, which is the path of Islam and the Koran,'' he said in a
speech carried by the news agency.
   Rafsanjani's speech came after the swearing-in ceremony attended
by top religious and government leaders. The one-hour ceremony was
held at a mosque attached to the home of the late Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini in the north Tehran suburb of Jamaran, said IRNA,
which was monitored in Nicosia.
   Rafsanjani apparently made no public reference to the first
crisis facing his presidency: a death threat against American
hostage Joseph Cicippio, held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslem extremists.
   Rafsanjani, 54, the Islamic Republic's fifth president, is
considered a pragmatist who would like to ease tight governmental
control of the economy, and resume ties with the West.
   He succeeds Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who became the country's
spiritual leader after the June 3 death of Khomeini, Iran's
patriarch of the 1979 revolution that deposed Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi.
   In a statement read by Khomeini's son, Ahmad, the outgoing
president urged Rafsanjani to use the presidency's increased powers
to solve the nation's problems and ease hardships faced by the
poor, IRNA said.
   Ahmad's reading of Khamenei's statement appeared to amount to a
declaration of support for Rafsanjani. The younger Khomeini has
been considered a leader of the hard-liners who are locked in a
power struggle with the new president's pragmatist faction.
   Rafsanjani won a landslide victory in Friday's presidential
elections, capturing 94.5 percent of the vote. Constitutional
reforms approved in a referendum during the election give him
considerably enlarged powers by scrapping Prime Minister Hussein
Musavi's post.
   Earlier this week, Khamenei told Musavi in a letter to continue
his duties as prime minister until a new Cabinet is set up by
Rafsanjani.
   The presidential elections, originally scheduled for Aug. 18,
were advanced by about three weeks to hasten the transfer of power
after Khomeini's death.
   Khamenei's decision to step down as president before the end of
his term appeared aimed at allowing Rafsanjani to move quickly to
start reforming Iran's sluggish economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
