<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1055EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BlackCatholics     08-03 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breakaway Priest on Minds of Black Catholics at Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Catholics gathering for their first laity
conference since a breakawy by a Washington priest are preparing to
shape their own agenda and prod church officials to address their
cultural needs.
   The schism over race and church policies that boiled over last
month when the Rev. George Stallings split from the archdiocese and
launched a splinter congregation is of major concern to those here
for the four-day conference, which starts today.
   Stallings was suspended for founding the Imani Temple, which
holds ceremonies that mix Catholic prayers and liturgy with African
and black American religious tradition.
   Stallings contends the church has failed to deal with racism. He
also says his brand of Catholicism better addresses the cultural
and spiritual needs of black parishioners.
   ``Now is the time for the laity to come forth and take a
stand,'' said the Rev. James Goode, a San Francisco priest in
Atlanta for the conference. ``You have to stand up and speak the
truth and face the consequences.''
   Goode praised Stallings' movement as ``a beautiful time of
coming together of African-American Catholics across the country.
   ``The church has to be challenged, no question about it. We
cannot continue as we are,'' Goode said. ``Things that people were
talking about in the back room now are being talked about in the
open.
   People still see the Catholic Church as run white males, he
said. ``That whole thing escalated with the Father Stallings
issue.''
   Walter Hubbard, executive director of the National Office for
Black Catholics, said the laity conference wants to address ``what
has been raised to a level of consciousness by Reverend Stallings.''
   ``There's a rich history in the church of African men and women
being part of the genesis of the church. It's not told too
frequently,'' he said.
   ``The church has to come to understand more and more that we
have a need to exercise and focus on our own culture,'' Hubbard
said. ``We've got to shape our own agenda. That's our goal.
   ``What you have seen and what you have heard on this issue is an
expression from the clergy, seminarians and the deacons,'' Hubbard
said. ``You really have not heard from the lay people.''
   Hubbard said Stallings had not confirmed whether he would attend
the meeting. Stallings did not return telephone calls Thursday to
Imani Temple.
   About 400 people are expected to attend the conference,
sponsored by Hubbard's group and the National Black Lay Catholic
Caucus. Workshops have topics ranging from ``Catholicism and
Blackness: Is There A Future?'' to ``When The Saints Go Marching In
_ Black Catholics Will Be In That Number.''
   Goode, described as a ``soul-moving'' preacher, is scheduled to
address the group Saturday.
   Archbishop Eugene Marino of Atlanta, the church's first black
archbishop, and Cardinal John O'Connor, archbishop of New York,
also are scheduled to speak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
