<FIRST>r a PM-WinerySlayings     08-03 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Killing Seven Has Brain Dysfunction, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a former winery
employee charged with killing six family members and a co-worker
said tests indicate his client has a brain dysfunction.
   ``I was hoping for something like this and I've confirmed it,''
Sonoma County Public Defender Marteen Miller, attorney for Ramon
Salcido, said Wednesday.
   Salcido, 28, a former employee of Grand Cru Winery near Glen
Ellen, is accused of murdering seven people on April 14, including
his wife, Angela, 24, and two daughters, Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 2,
whose throats were slashed. A third daughter, Carmina, 3, survived.
   He also is accused of killing his wife's mother, Marion
Richards, 47; his wife's sisters, Ruth Richards, 12, and Marie
Richards, 8, and a winery co-worker, Tracy Toovey, 35.
   He is accused of attempted murder of another co-worker, Kenneth
Butti, who was wounded; Butti's wife, Terri, and Carmina.
   The tests were done by a neuropsychologist and interpreted by a
neurologist, said Miller, who plans to have more extensive tests
conducted at the University of California at Irvine Medical
Department.
   Miller previously said the technology available at UC Irvine is
more sophisticated than anywhere else in the state. The attorney
said he won't know how he'll use the findings in Salcido's defense
until all tests are completed.
</TEXT>
