<HEAD>Six Crewmen Still Missing From Capsized Rig; One Body Recovered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs with Coast Guard now saying one body found
overnight, sted two, as earlier reported. Picks up 4th graf, `The rig,
...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORGAN CITY, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four bodies have been recovered from an
oil rig that capsized in the Gulf of Mexico, with six crewmen still
missing and feared drowned, the Coast Guard said today.
   Three bodies were recovered Wednesday and another one overnight,
the Coast Guard said. The Guard had reported earlier that divers
found two bodies overnight but later said that information was
incorrect.
   Divers continued to search the submerged crew compartments today
for the remaining six crewmen, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Matt
McGovern in New Orleans.
   The rig, about 20 miles south of Morgan City, fell on its side
in 30 feet of water Monday while heading inland as Hurricane
Chantal approached.
   Four crewmen were rescued immediately.
   Authorities hoped some of the missing crewmen might have
survived in airtight compartments aboard the vessel, leased by
Chevron. The search, delayed by rough seas in the wake of Chantal,
resumed Wednesday.
   Chevron spokesman Jonathan Lifa said the three bodies recovered
Wednesday were found in the crew's quarters.
   The identities of the dead men were being withheld pending
notification of their families, Lifa said.
   The names of the missing crewmen have not been released. They
worked for Lafitte Welding of Lafitte, Global Divers of New Iberia,
and Owensby Kritkos of Gretna, officials said.
</TEXT>
