<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0514 08-03 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Kill 18 People, Wound 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 18 civilians killed. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese radicals shot and killed 18
people, including nine relatives of a legislator, officials said
today.
   In another attack, radicals wearing police uniforms raided a
government armory and shot and wounded five officers before
escaping, police said.
   The attacks on the civilians occurred Wednesday night in and
around the town of Kalutara, 25 miles south of Colombo, government
officials said.
   The victims included nine relatives of lawmaker P.D. Abeyaratna,
who were gunned down at his home in Kalutara, the officials said on
condition of anonymity. The lawmaker was not home at the time of
the attack.
   The other civilians killed in the area included four workers at
a government cement factory, a physician and his assistant, the
officials said.
   No further details on the attacks were immediately available.
   A police officer said at least 15 Sinhalese radicals entered a
Colombo police armory unchallenged on Wednesday and apparently
escaped without injury.
   The officer, who requested anonymity, said the radicals took 25
automatic rifles from the armory in the suburb of Thimbirgasyaya.
Two vans used by the radicals were found abandoned later about four
miles away, the officer said.
   He said authorities conducted a house-to-house search of the
area and deployed helicopters using night lights but found no sign
of the radicals.
   In what police called a diversionary tactic, bombs exploded in
three other areas of the capital minutes before the raid, injuring
one civilian.
   Sinhalese radicals have been attacking the government since
1987, saying it has made too many concessions to the nation's Tamil
minority.
   In a bid to appease Tamil rebels, the Sinhalese-dominated
government in July 1987 offered limited autonomy to areas in which
Tamils make up the majority of residents. The rebels have been
fighting for an independent nation since 1983.
   At least 4,000 people, mainly government officials, have been
killed in attacks by Sinhalese radicals. The Tamil insurgency has
claimed 11,000 lives.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
the Sinhalese make up 75 percent. Tamils accuse the Sinhalese of
discriminating against them in jobs and education.
</TEXT>
