<FIRST>r a PM-OralRoberts     08-03 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oral Roberts,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oral Roberts Ministry Dismisses 10 Percent Of Workforce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oral Roberts' evangelical empire, besieged
by financial problems and declining donations, has laid off more
than 10 percent of its 2,300 employees.
   The cost-cutting move is the latest attempt by the ministry to
recover from more than two years of financial hardships highlighted
by two dramatic fund-raising pleas by Oral Roberts that have netted
$19 million.
   Roberts' son, Richard, head of business operations for the
ministry, said Wednesday that 250 employees, mostly support staff,
have been dismissed.
   He would not say how much money would be saved with the layoffs.
``I refuse to equate money with human beings,'' he said.
   The dismissals were ministrywide but did not include Oral
Roberts University faculty, officials said.
   The cuts came as an accreditation team continued its
investigation of the university's medical school. University
officials said the review team has been at the school since early
this week.
   Seven of 10 department chairmen and the interim medical school
dean have resigned or been fired since March. The number of staff
doctors at the affiliated City of Faith Medical and Research Center
also has dwindled from 118 two years ago to 52 today.
   The ministry completed an $11 million fund-raising effort in May
to pay six months worth of past-due bills. The elder Roberts told
followers then that contributions had dropped dramatically in the
past two years.
   Richard Roberts said the ministry has maintained $2.5 million in
donations a month since May, a 50 percent drop from two years ago.
   In 1987, Oral Roberts completed an $8 million fund-raising
campaign, claiming God would ``call me home'' if he failed.
</TEXT>
