<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Jackson-Mayor     08-03 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Mayor,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Now a Voter in D.C.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson registered to vote in the
District of Columbia today, a move that would qualify him to run
for mayor in 1990.
   The former presidential candidate and his wife, Jacqueline,
spent about 10 minutes filling out a series of forms, and
registered as Democrats, according to city elections officials.
   After registering, Jackson read a statement outlining his
political agenda, which he said includes education, the eradication
of drugs and statehood for the district.
   He again refused comment on whether he would enter the city's
1990 mayoral race, saying instead he would turn his attention
towards getting statehood for the nation's capital.
   City law requires that mayoral candidates be registered to vote
in the district at least one year before the general election. The
next election is scheduled for Nov. 6, 1990.
   Jackson, who moved to the nation's capital from Chicago last
weekend, has not ruled out running for mayor.
   He has said he would never run against Mayor Marion Barry Jr.,
an ally from the civil rights movement, but after Barry declared he
would seek a fourth term Jackson refused to take himself out of
consideration.
   The two-time Democratic presidential hopeful has said he was
moving to the nation's capital to be closer to the legislative
process. The national offices of the Rainbow Coalition, his
political organization, is moving here as well.
   He is living in a northwest Washington apartment while the home
he purchased in 1984 is being renovated. He has said he has no
plans to sell his Chicago home.
</TEXT>
