<HEAD>Western Wildfires at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with today's situation in Idaho
and California. Pick up 5th graf pvs, `MONTANA:...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state look at wildfires burning in the West:
   IDAHO: Hundreds of lightning-caused fires have burned 90,000
acres, and more than 6,200 firefighters were on the lines. The
threat to two small mountain towns eased as cool weather slowed the
fires, but the forecast of rising temperatures through the weekend
had fire bosses worried.
   OREGON: Fires east of the Cascades have burned 88,000 acres and
were being fought Wednesday by 4,400 people. The worst of the
lightning-caused blazes were around Baker and the town of John Day.
   CALIFORNIA: More than 35,000 acres have burned, but the fire in
the Sierra Nevada foothills that destroyed homes over the weekend
has been contained. An 8,200-acre brush fire in the Cleveland
National Forest southeast of Los Angeles was 50 percent contained
today, but was within 5 miles of the Palomar Observatory and was
threatening a nature preserve that contains trees unusual in the
area.
   MONTANA: A fire burning in grassland and scattered timber in the
Custer National Forest was nearly contained at 800 acres. About 300
firefighters battled the blaze, which was started by lightning
Monday.
   WASHINGTON: Crews were mopping up an 850-acre forest fire in the
Pasayten Wilderness near the Canadian border. The first of more
than 1,000 Army troops trained at Fort Lewis to help fight fires
departed Wednesday for Oregon.
</TEXT>
