<FIRST>r i AM-Bourguiba     08-03 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bourguiba,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Marks Birthday; New Operation Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Habib Bourguiba marked
his 86th birthday Thursday in the hospital where he underwent a
prostate operation last month.
   There was no celebration of his birthday in Tunisia, where it
was once a national holiday, and most Tunisian newspapers took no
notice of the event.
   By coincidence, the day was a public holiday in Tunisia because
it was the Islamic new year.
   The weekly magazine Realites reported Thursday, without citing
sources, that Bourguiba might need a second operation to clear his
urinary tract.
   The government authorized 27 members of Bourguiba's family to
visit him in the hospital on the occasion of his birthday,
including his son, former Foreign Minister Habib Bourguiba Jr., the
magazine said.
   When Bourguiba tried to include four former members of his
government in the list of his birthday guests, ``these persons were
not authorized to visit him,'' it said.
   Bourguiba was ousted in a bloodless coup in 1987 by his prime
minister, Zine el-Abidine Ben Ali, who said the president was
senile and unable to carry on his duties.
</TEXT>
