<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Voyager-Neptune 1stLd-Writethru a0595 08-03 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Neptune, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0595,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spacecraft Finds Three New Moons Around Neptune</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 7 grafs of details and background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Images from the Voyager 2 spacecraft
revealed three previously unknown moons circling Neptune,
scientists at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory announced today.
   The discoveries, in addition to a moon spotted by Voyager 2 last
month, bring to six the number of satellites known to be orbiting
the blue planet, laboratory officials said.
   Voyager was more than 22 million miles from Neptune when the
moons were confirmed by scientists Wednesday, indicating there may
be many more discoveries as the space probe draws even closer in
coming weeks.
   The newly discovered moons were temporarily named 1989 N2, 1989
N3 and 1989 N4. The objects were tracked as ``candidate moons'' for
five days and then confirmed when they followed predicted orbits.
   The moons appear to range between 60 miles and 125 miles in
diameter and are in circular, equatorial orbits moving in the
direction of the planet's rotation. Neptune's big moon, Triton,
moves in the opposite direction.
   The moon 1989 N3 is closest to the planet, orbiting 17,000 miles
above Neptune's cloud tops and completing one orbit every 8 hour
and 10 minutes.
   Orbiting 23,000 miles above the clouds, 1989 N4 circles Neptune
in 10 hours and 20 minutes.
   The farthest out of the three, 1989 N2 is 30,000 miles above the
clouds and completes each orbit in 13 hours and 30 minutes.
   Voyager 2 is on a course that will take it within 3,000 miles of
Neptune on Aug. 24. The spacecraft was launched in 1977 and has
been past Jupiter, Saturn and Uranus. It is more than 2.7 billion
miles from Earth.
   Jet Propulsion Laboratory operates America's unmanned spacecraft
exploring the solar system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
