<DOCNO> AP890803-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Business Bjt   08-03 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Business, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Businessmen Latest Targets of Government Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's tiny but prosperous private business
community is the latest target of the government's crackdown on
so-called bourgeois evils.
   The bar owners and street vendors who once were the envy of
their neighbors now worry they may be shut down in the leftist
atmosphere that has followed the June army attack on student
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   ``Things are no good now. I'm trying to unload my business,''
said a clothing vendor in one of the city's largest private
markets. ``But no one wants to buy.''
   In the past decade, 14.5 million individually owned businesses
have sprung up across China, most of them vendors or offering
services such as bicycle repairs and hair cuts. They opened on the
promise of senior leader Deng Xiaoping that, after years of
enforced egalitarianism, it was permissible for some people to get
rich before others.
   Soon teachers and office workers began discovering that barely
literate snack vendors pulled in more money than they. Many young
businessmen bought motorcycles; a few could even afford cars.
   What the Chinese call the ``red-eyed disease'' _ envy _ became
epidemic.
   Hoping perhaps to bridge the deep gulf between the leadership
and an alienated urban population, Communist Party General
Secretary Jiang Zemin has seized upon this envy and made ``unfair
distribution'' of income a key theme of his first month in office.
   ``Self-employed traders and peddlars cheat, embezzle, bribe and
evade taxation,'' he wrote in the newspaper China Labor. ``On some
small commodity markets, over 80 percent of the self-employed have
an annual income exceeding 10,000 yuan ($2,700), five times higher
than that of the average government employee.
   ``These upstarts ... indulge in a life of luxury,'' he wrote.
``This greatly hurts the confidence of workers ... who live on
salaries. It has affected social stability and corrupted social
values.''
   Jiang has repeated the message in other essays and speeches, and
newspaper commentators have chimed in. All condemn alleged
illegalities by private businessmen. But the greatest offense seems
simply to be making money.
   ``How much do individual businessmen make?'' asked the party
newspaper, the People's Daily. ``No one really knows but them. But
the wives of some private bosses wear outfits that cost more than
1,000 yuan ($270) and not one, but several gold rings on their
fingers.''
   Such articles worry businessmen like Duan, who along with his
brother opened the Rose Bar two months ago on a busy Beijing street.
   ``For two years we've been going south and looking at bars,''
said Duan, who gave only his surname. ``But we didn't dare open one
in Beijing earlier.''
   In recent months, however, even staid Beijing began blossoming
with private bars, dance halls and pool halls.
   So Duan and his brother, who had saved money as a private
clothing seller, pooled about $5,350 to rent and renovate a
storefront.
   Then the army declared martial law May 20 to quell the student
protests, and armed police began dropping by to inspect customers'
identification papers. ``It was very bad for business,'' Duan said,
but he fears the newspaper criticisms bode even worse.
   ``I'm worried the government might shut us down. Then we'll lose
everything,'' he said, drinking a beer in his tiny, smoky bar.
   ``I don't like politics,'' he said. ``I don't understand
politics.''
   Bars are especially vulnerable because they represent a loose,
``bourgeois'' lifestyle the aging revolutionaries now in the
forefront are determined to wipe out.
   Two bars near the Rose Bar were shut down in the past month for
running prostitution rings. At the Rose Bar, four ``bar girls''
keep company with the male customers, flirting in exchange for
drinks. Whether they do anything else was not clear.
   Already, authorities have moved to increase controls on private
businessmen. The central government has announced special
inspections of their books and the quality of their products.
Several provincial governments have said businessmen will have to
submit their salaries for approval to ensure they don't earn too
much.
   But Duan's drinking friend, Yang, said he's confident the
private sector won't be shut down altogether. He reminded: ``Marx
said socialism means `to each according to his labor.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Agriculture     08-03 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Agriculture,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Official Sees Bumper Crop, But Harvest Not Assured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's European breadbasket is growing
a bumper grain crop, but shortages of spare parts and fuel are
hurting chances that farmers will be able to bring all the crop in.
   Yegor K. Ligachev, the Communist Party Politburo member in
charge of agriculture, said on Soviet TV Wednesday night that such
key farming regions as the Ukraine, Byelorussia, Moldavia, and the
Krasnodar, Stavropol and Rostov regions of southern Russia are
looking forward to a bumper harvest.
   The struggle to put more food on empty store shelves is not only
an economic problem, but a big political headache for President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He has been tinkering with the inefficient, state-run farm
system almost constantly since taking power four years ago, and a
good growing season could give him the kind of sorely needed
victory that has eluded his reform efforts.
   Newspapers follow the grain harvest, which is just getting into
full swing, nearly every day with front-page stories, and the
government newspaper Izvestia on July 19 cited reports of ``high,
and in some places record harvests.''
   Ligachev said the good news from the fields means ``we have all
possibilities to harvest enough crop as a whole,'' despite a
serious drought in grain-growing regions of Siberia and Kazakhstan,
and the chronic struggle with spare parts and fuel for combines,
and storage.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture, which closely follows the
Soviet grain crops, estimates the harvest will be about 210 million
tons, on a par with 1986 and 1987, and better than last year's
harvest of 195 million tons. Last year's crop was damaged by a dry
growing season, but damp weather that slowed harvesting.
   In story after story, however, Izvestia has warned that a good
crop doesn't guarantee a good harvest. The newspaper ended a biting
July 31 piece on the shortage of parts for combines in the Ukraine
and Russia with the depressing observation the harvest is so
inefficient that ``the more you grow, the more you lose.''
   Another story said fuel for the combines was in short supply
throughout the Ukraine.
   Ligachev said the Soviet Union loses 30 percent of its harvest
because of poor processing, and he cited conclusions by Dutch
specialists that Soviet food processing is decades behind the West.
   A Western diplomat who specializes in Soviet agricultural said
the improved crop appeared to a result of good weather rather than
anything Gorbachev has done.
   Mild weather minimized winter kill of grain planted in fall, and
timely rain has kept both spring and winter grains growing well, he
said.
   Gorbachev has abolished a Moscow superagency that oversaw
agricultural policy and a meeting of the party Central Committee in
March set the groundwork for allowing farmers to lease land to
partially break away from the inefficiency of the state-run system.
   Moscow has also promised payments in hard currency to farms that
delivery grain to the state over their assigned quotas.
   But the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
specialists ``haven't seen any indication that people are leasing
land in great numbers.''
   He also said that inefficiencies in the harvest, the weather in
the next six weeks, and the drought east of the Ural Mountains
could seriously damage the final harvest.
   Estimates of last year's harvest plummeted last fall because
damp weather prevented farmers from getting into the fields, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
