<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SovietJews     08-03 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet Jews,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another 4,000 Emigrate Last Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union continued
at more than twice last year's rate in July, with nearly 4,000
arrivals at a Vienna transit center, a resettlement agency said
Thursday.
   Soviet authorities allowed 3,971 Jews to leave last month, six
more than in June, which raised the year's total to 24,133,
according to a spokeswoman for the Geneva-based Intergovernmental
Committee for Migration.
   Only 104 of the latest arrivals chose to move on directly to
Israel, said spokeswoman Regina Boucault, with 717 emigres
resettled in the Jewish state this year. Most are going to the
United States.
   In June, 3,965 Jews left the Soviet Union, making the total for
the six months of 1989 already higher than last year's flow of
20,082.
   About 300,000 Soviet Jews have emigrated since the resettlement
program began in 1971. The largest official exodus, 51,328, was
recorded in 1979, before the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan
chilled East-West relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
