<DOCNO> AP890803-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CleanAir 1stLd-Writethru a0440 08-03 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Only 3 Democrats Sign On as Bush Bill Introduced in Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First 8 grafs new, picking up 5th graf pvs, Richard Ayers. Subs
12th graf pvs, Environmentalists have, to include tonnage of sulfur dioxide
reduction; deletes last 6 grafs pvs, ``They wanted, to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's clean air bill,
attacked by environmental activists as a sellout to industry, was
introduced in the Senate today with only three Democrats joining 21
Republican sponsors.
   Despite a strong effort by the administration to line up
sponsors from both parties, only Democratic Sens. Donald W. Riegle
Jr. of Michigan, J. James Exon of Nebraska and John Breaux of
Louisiana signed on as co-sponsors.
   The bill was introduced in the House with 57 Democratic and 90
Republican co-sponsors.
   Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I. and the bill's chief Senate sponsor,
referred to the lack of Democratic support indirectly, commenting,
``The introduction of the president's bill is not the end of the
process, but a major advance in the march.''
   Chafee, the ranking GOP member of the Senate Environment
Committee, added, ``After eight years of silence from the White
House on this issue, we now have a chief executive who recognizes
the need for a major overhaul of the Clean Air Act.''
   The administration moved on Wednesday to blunt criticism of the
legislation by meeting with environmental groups that have
criticized the bill.
   ``At this point, it's an information discussion and not a
negotiating session,'' said assistant EPA Administrator William
Rosenberg, assistant Environmental Protection Agency commissioner,
who met with top White House officials and seven environmental
groups.
   ``The administration's bill stands as it is,'' Rosenberg said,
also telling reporters that President Bush had briefly dropped by
the meeting.
   Richard Ayres, head of the National Clean Air Coalition,
characterized the administration officials at the meeting as ``very
upset by the criticism the bill has got from the environmental
community and members of Congress.''
   ``We responded with equal vehemence that `we don't think you've
been unfairly attacked. We believe what we're saying is based on
the facts.'''
   Participants said the administration promised future meetings.
   The environmentalists, who have characterized the legislation as
a gift to industry, said they told the administration the bill
would not protect public health and in some cases weakens current
law.
   The invitations to Wednesday's meeting immediately became
controversial because the White House initially failed to invite
Ayres, whose organization is the main environmental lobbying group
on clean air. He was summoned to the White House just 15 minutes
before the meeting began.
   An EPA source said EPA Administrator William Reilly and
Rosenberg, assistant administrator for air programs, ``were shocked
that Ayres was not invited'' and demanded the White House change
its mind. The source spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The meeting concentrated on the portion of the bill seeking to
curb acid rain, a form of pollution caused by emissions of sulfur
dioxide and nitrogen dioxide from power plants, autos and other
sources. These pollutants can be carried thousands of miles through
the atmosphere, and eventually return to earth as sulfuric or
nitric acids, ruining lakes, streams and forests.
   Environmentalists have considered the acid rain section the
strongest part of the legislation, because it would reduce sulfur
dioxide emissions by 10 million tons by the end of 2000 and ``cap''
the lower emissions figure to prevent growth of the pollutant in
the 21st century.
   But even this section has aroused criticism, with
environmentalists contending the real sulfur dioxide decrease would
be 9 million tons, while nitrogen dioxide would actually grow by 1
million tons by the end of 2000.
   The major unhappiness, however, has been with the sections on
urban smog and releases of toxic chemicals into the air, and
Rosenberg promised to hold further discussions on both topics,
participants said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
