<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Abortion-Congress 4thLd-Writethru a0626-a0593 08-03
0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Congress, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0626-a0593,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Threatens to Veto Legislation Liberalizing DC Abortion Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today passed legislation
liberalizing abortion restrictions in the District of Columbia, and
President Bush immediately threatened a veto.
   In a letter to Congress, Bush urged lawmakers to ``protect the
lives of America's unborn children.''
   The confrontation came over the first vote in either house of
Congress since the Supreme Court ruling last month permitting
states to impose further restrictions on abortion.
   On a 238-189 vote, the chamber approved a bill providing $532
million in federal funds for the district's government that
contained the abortion provision. The bill now moves to the Senate.
   Pro-choice advocates hailed the House vote as a turnaround and
predicted it will help reverse the tide nationwide against moves to
restrict abortion.
   The White House today released a letter Bush sent Congress on
Wednesday threatening the veto.
   ``If the bill presented to me permits the use of appropriated
funds to pay for abortions other than those where the life of the
mother would be endangered if the fetus were carried to term, I
will veto it,'' Bush wrote Rep. Julian C. Dixon, D-Calif., chairman
of the Appropriations Subcommittee on the District of Columbia.
   In a dramatic roll call that stunned lawmakers on both sides,
the House voted 219-206 Wednesday against an amendment banning
public financing of all abortions in the District of Columbia. As
the final tally became apparent, pro-choice lawmakers on the
chamber's floor embraced each other and roared with emotion.
   It was the first congressional showdown on the issue since the
Supreme Court decision last month enhancing state authority to
limit abortion, and a reversal of a 222-186 House vote on the same
question last summer.
   Abortion rights advocates said it was the first time since 1980
that the House had rejected an effort to restrict public financing
for abortions.
   The amendment would have banned the use of federal or district
funds to perform any abortions during the 1990 federal fiscal year,
which begins Oct. 1.
   Instead, the bill now would liberalize current law by allowing
the district to spend its own money for abortions and permitting
the use of federal funds in cases of rape, incest or to save the
mother's life. Current law forbids the use of federal or district
funds in Washington unless the mother's life is at stake.
   But the effect of the measure's rejection carried well beyond
the capital's borders, thanks to the high court's July 3 ruling in
the Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services case, abortion rights
advocates said. They said that with surveys showing most Americans
still support the right to choose abortion, Thursday's battle
showed lawmakers know their constituents are watching them.
   ``There is more emphasis on voting records in this issue now,''
Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., of the Appropriations District of
Columbia subcommittee said after the vote. ``The politics of it has
been turned up somewhat.''
   ``People since Webster understand this game is for real now,''
said another lawmaker who backs the right to abortion, Rep. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif.
   Supporters of the defeated provision credited the high court's
ruling with making the abortion issue a more delicate one. But they
also blamed their loss on freshmen lawmakers more sympathetic to
abortion than the legislators they replaced, and to misleading
lobbying by their opponents.
   The amendment, sponsored by Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif.,
contained no exceptions to the ban on public money for abortions.
   During the debate, he and his supporters repeatedly said they
intended to add an exception for pregnancies that threatened the
mother's life, but didn't because it would have left the provision
vulnerable to being stricken from the bill for procedural reasons.
   Opponents of the amendment, however, stressed the provision
contained no such language and that voters would look unkindly at a
vote for such a harsh measure. Some of them stood at the entrance
to the House chamber, telling members as they arrived to vote that
the exception for endangered mothers was lacking.
   Dornan noted that in a letter President Bush sent to lawmakers
earlier in the day, the president promised to veto the bill if it
permitted the use of federal money for abortion, except for cases
involving the mother's survival.
   ``I'm disappointed that a pro-life message did not go out, but
we are going to win in the end anyway,'' he told reporters.
   In the Webster decision, the Supreme Court ruled 5-4 that states
may forbid public employees and facilities from participating in
abortions, even if patients are willing to pay their own expenses.
</TEXT>
