<HEAD>Mrs. Higgins Sees U.N. Chief; Gets Call from British Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins
met Wednesday in New York with U.N. Secretary General Perez de
Cuellar and received a supportive phone call from British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher, a Pentagon spokeswoman said today.
   Robin Higgins traveled to the United Nations for her meeting
with the secretary general, who has dispatched envoy Marrack
Goulding to Lebanon to search for Higgins' body.
   A Shiite Moslem group claimed it killed Higgins on Monday in
retaliation for Israel's refusal to release a Shiite Moslem
clergyman it kidnapped last week.
   A Pentagon spokeswoman, Army Maj. Kathy Wood, said Mrs. Higgins
described the session with de Cuellar as ``private'' and relayed no
other information about it.
   Mrs. Thatcher telephoned Mrs. Higgins Wednesday morning, Ms.
Wood said.
   ``She just wanted Robin to know that she is in constant contact
with President Bush and that she will try to do anything, and if
they can, they will. She also said she admired Robin's strength and
courage in this crisis,'' Ms. Wood added.
   The spokeswoman described Mrs. Higgins as ``touched that the
prime minister would call her'' to express her concern.
   Mrs. Higgins, a Marine major, has been on leave for the past
several days from her job as a public affairs official in the
Defense Department's information office. She has refused
interviews, but comes daily to the Pentagon to be updated about her
husband's situation.
