<HEAD>Prime Minister Slightly Injured in Accident on Bicycle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Wilfried Martens, who is
used to negotiating the bumps and curves of Belgian politics,
showed less skill along its country roads.
   Martens, bicycling near his holiday home in Oostduinkerke on the
Belgian coast, crashed Wednesday when he suddenly had to brake to
avoid an obstacle along the road. He broke a finger and bruised his
face.
   ``We were scared because the accident was pretty spectacular,
but it did not jeopardize his summer holidays,'' said a government
official.
   Martens, 53, took up cycling after a 1983 heart operation.
   He has been prime minister for most of the 1980s, leading
center-right as well as center-left governments, and has excelled
in seeking compromises to keep his coalitions together.
   He heads a five-party coalition of Dutch- and French-speaking
Christian Democrats and Socialists, and a Dutch-speaking
nationalist party.
