<DOCNO> AP890803-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1344EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages-Navy     08-03 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Navy,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crisis Caught US Indian Ocean Fleet Out of Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush lost one of his options
for a quick strike against Iran in the latest hostage crisis
because the logical fleet to execute it was 4,000 miles away, U.S.
military sources said Thursday.
   U.S. forces in the Mediterranean were within minutes' striking
distance of Lebanon, but the Navy carrier force based in the Indian
Ocean was making a routine port call in Singapore.
   ``The military option was there, but the Navy in the Indian
Ocean wasn't,'' said one of the sources, all of whom insisted on
anonymity.
   He described it as ``just the breaks'' that the USS America and
its eight-ship battle group were so far away when Shiite Moslem
kidnappers in Lebanon said Monday they had hanged Lt. Col. William
R. Higgins.
   Washington officials said immediately that ``all options'' were
open, including military response to the killing of the U.S. Marine
officer, who was on U.N. peacekeeping duty in south Lebanon when he
was abducted Feb. 17, 1988.
   That seemed to be reaffirmed Wednesday when Bush, asked about
movements of U.S. warships in the region, said his administration
was ``prudently planning'' the response to be made if a second
American was killed.
   U.S. diplomatic sources have said potential targets include Iran
because of its support for Lebanon's Shiite kidnappers of Higgins
and other Westerners.
   They likened the situation to April 1986, when President Reagan
used air strikes to punish Libya for its alleged sponsorship of
international terrorism.
   The officials in Washington confirmed the 79,000-ton America and
five of its escorts had cut the Singapore visit short, but would
not say where the ships were going or whether the move was linked
to the hostage crisis.
   Sources said the carrier was returning to its current duty of
patrolling the Arabian Sea as part of the Navy's Joint Task Force
Middle East, which covers that area and the Persian Gulf.
   Although the America could make the 4,000-mile voyage in about
five days at its top speed of more than 30 knots, that pace would
leave some of the escorts behind.
   Its battle group has the carrier's 80 aircraft and a variety of
cruise missiles on the Aegis cruiser Mobile Bay, missile cruiser
Dale, destroyers Comte de Grasse and Lawrence, and the frigate
Joseph Hewes.
   After a cease-fire was reached a year ago in the 8-year-old war
between Iran and Iraq, the Navy reduced its Persian Gulf force and
began giving more port time to sailors, who sometimes had spent
weeks at a time at sea on high alert.
   Carrier groups in the Arabian Sea are rotated every three
months, but since the truce, weeks sometimes pass with no carrier
on station.
   ``Almost anywhere you go out there, it's a matter of great
distance,'' one officer said. ``The Indian Ocean is not the
Mediterranean. There just aren't that many good liberty ports
around there.''
   The nearest regular port of call for U.S. carriers is Karachi,
Pakistan, about 500 miles from the gulf.
   They also visit Djibouti, a French base on the Horn of Africa,
1,500 miles away; the Seychelles Islands and Mombasa, Kenya, each
2,000 miles away, and Bombay, India, which is 800 miles from the
Strait of Hormuz at the gulf's southern end.
   Sources said the America sailed 2,500 miles to the Indian Ocean
base of Diego Garcia for weapons training before setting out for
Singapore.
   One said Iran offered ``limited choices'' in targets, the most
obvious being Kharg Island, the offshore oil terminal in the
northern Pesian Gulf that handles most of Iran's oil exports.
   Kharg was a regular, sometimes daily, target of Iraq air raids.
   The United States attacked Iranian oil platforms in the Persian
Gulf twice during the war in reprisal for Iranian attacks on
U.S.-flagged vessels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
