<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     08-03 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Elections on Track despite Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racist laws and charges of police
harassment and detentions of dissidents by guerrillas won't delay
Namibia's independence, the chief U.N. official for the territory
said Thursday.
   ``I am reasonably confident that we are three months away from
holding an election,'' U.N. Special Representative Martti Ahtisaari
of Finland told a conference on the future of the South
African-ruled colony.
   ``Barring any unexpected major setback we should have elections
Nov. 6,'' said Ahtisaari.
   Sixty percent of the estimated 650,000 eligible voters have
registered, he said.
   U.N. police are having difficulty monitoring territorial police
on patrol in northern Namibia because land mine-resistant vehicles
the police leased them have broken down, Ahtisaari said.
   Nevertheless, he said, the U.N. police presence is having a
``reassuring and calming effect'' on people in the north, where
police are accused of harassing supporters of the guerrilla-backed
South-West Africa People's Organization.
   The organization ended its 23-year bush war for independence
when Pretoria signed a U.S.-brokered accord agreeing to grant
Namibia independence in exchange for the withdrawal of Cuban troops
in Angola.
   Ahtisaari said the integration into the police force of about
2,000 members of a paramilitary unit called ``Koevoet'' _ Afrikaans
for crowbar _ is unacceptable.
   ``There is no place for the continuance of a counterinsurgency
operation,'' Ahtisaari said. ``They should be fulfilling normal
police operations only.''
   Police retraining Koevoet men report only 15 percent are
literate and others would be unable to take down a citizen's
complaint or crime report, Ahtisaari said. ``Their skills must lie
elsewhere,'' he said.
   The South African administrator of Namibia, Louis Pienaar,
defended the presence of Koevoet during the one-day conference,
organized by the University of Pretoria. He said Koevet members are
needed to counteract any possible invasion by armed guerrillas who
remain across the border in Angola.
   Ahtisaari said he continues to investigate charges by prisoners
released by the guerrilla organization that up to 2,000 more
detainees are being held in neighboring countries where guerrillas
have refused to allow U.N. or Red Cross officials to inspect their
camps. About 200 detainees freed last month were accused of spying
for South Africa.
   ``I am not yet satisfied that all political prisoners have been
released and I am pursuing this with all concerned governments and
with SWAPO,'' Ahtisaari said.
   He said he also is continuing discussions with Pienaar about
repealing legislation that divides Namibia into 11 ethnic
governments providing schools and medical services on a racial
basis.
   ``This legislation is found by the majority of people, including
all the major political parties, to be repugnant,'' said Ahtisaari.
Pienaar wants to leave it to a new government, expected to take
office early next year.
   He also said he is ``not content with the impartiality of the
state-controlled media'' and will suggest proposals to rectify the
situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
