<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0574 08-03 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0574,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews Work to Consolidate Gains Against Wildfires</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `In Southern...' to UPDATE acreage; SUBS 2nd-to-last
graf, `_ In Montana' with new fire on Indian reservation, containment of
earlier blaze.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Flames neared California's Palomar Observatory and threatened a
nature sanctuary today as firefighters elsewhere in the West
struggled to consolidate gains made against hundreds of wildfires
with the help of cooler weather.
   An estimated 220,000 acres of timber, brush and grassland have
burned throughout the West in a bout of fires that began July 26,
according to the federal Boise (Idaho) Interagency Fire Center.
More than 20,000 firefighters were on the lines in Idaho, Oregon,
Washington, Montana and California.
   Cool, moist air slowed the spread of fires in Idaho and Oregon,
but a warming trend was predicted this afternoon and through the
weekend.
   ``Things haven't slowed down at all here,'' said spokesman Kris
Long at the federal fire center. ``With supplies and manpower
coming in and out, it stays busy.''
   In Southern California, firefighters dropped water and chemicals
and set fires of their own in a struggle to keep flames from a
10,300-acre wildfire away from the Eagle Crag nature sanctuary in
the Cleveland National Forest today. The fire was within 5 miles of
the Palomar Observatory, a mountaintop astronomy center operated by
the California Institute of Technology.
   Crews had cut lines around 60 percent of the blaze early today,
but their chances of containing the flames would be hurt if fire
got into the Eagle Crag area, about 90 miles southeast of Los
Angeles, said Forest Service spokeswoman Audrey Hagen.
   ``No equipment is allowed in the area,'' Ms. Hagen said.
Bulldozers might be authorized as a last resort, but the terrain is
so steep they probably wouldn't be able to get in, she said.
   In Idaho, a break in dry lightning that zapped the state in
recent weeks was enough to prompt stepped-up efforts to hack
containment lines around the worst of the fires burning 90,000
acres of timber and range.
   An estimated $36 million in resources have been destroyed in the
Boise National Forest alone, officials said.
   Cooler, moister air eased the immediate danger to two small
backcountry towns in west-central Idaho, which most residents
evacuated earlier in the week.
   Strategists called for at least 70 more 20-member crews to join
more than 6,200 firefighters already committed in Idaho. Hundreds
of Idaho National Guardsmen also were activated to support the
effort.
   In the forests, the first priority continued to be protection of
small communities and pockets of summer homes and cabins.
   Soapy white foam was sprayed on structures, and hundreds of
firefighters were diverted from frontal assaults on the blazes to
clear brush and other fuel from around private property.
   Besides the war on the ground, dozens of helicopters were
ferrying buckets filled with water from rivers to hot spots, and
air tankers have been dropping about a quarter-million gallons of
chemical retardant a day.
   The situation Wednesday elsewhere in the West:
   _ In eastern Oregon, teams worked to prevent erosion in the
Malheur and Wallowa-Whitman National Forests even before the fires
that had claimed 88,000 acres of timber and range lands were
contained. Several smaller blazes were contained, and the spread of
the bigger fires around the towns of John Day, Baker and Enterprise
had stopped, said U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman Wendy Evans in
Portland.
   _ In California, in addition to the Cleveland National Forest
blaze, a 3,000-acre fire burned out of control in the Sierra Nevada
foothills in the center of the state, but didn't pose a threat to
structures.
   _ In Montana, fire engines stood by to protect two mountain
cabins as a lightning-sparked fire in in dead timber grew quickly
to 500 acres on the Crow Indian Reservation southeast of Billings.
An 800-acre grass and timber fire in the Custer National Forest in
the state's southeastern corner was contained.
   _ In Washington, firefighters were mopping up the 850-acre
Lodgepole fire in the North Cascades near the Canadian border.
</TEXT>
