<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-03 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader: Interrogation Didn't Link Him to Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung said
Thursday a 22-hour interrogation by security agents failed to
implicate him in a secret trip to communist North Korea by a
lawmaker charged with espionage.
   Kim told a news conference at the headquarters of his Party for
Peace and Democracy that he was cleared of any suspicion and
charged that his questioning by security authorities was a
well-conceived government plan to undermine his party's image.
   But the Agency for National Security Planning, the main
government intelligence organization, said that since questioning
was legally limited to 24 hours and Kim issued ``adamant denials,''
they ran out of time and that Kim might be questioned again.
   ``They detained me for questioning without any evidence,'' Kim
told supporters after returning from the interrogation that lasted
until early Thursday.
   The head of the largest opposition party said investigators
could not present evidence that he had any part in a trip to North
Korea last year by National Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won.
   Suh was expelled from Kim's party after the lawmaker was
arrested June 28.
   South Korea bans unauthorized travel to North Korea and
maintains that dialogue or contacts must go through official
channels. Violators can be sentenced to prison terms under tough
national security laws.
   Kim and senior party lawmaker Moon Tong-hwan were interrogated
after being detained on a court warrant Wednesday.
   Government officials said Kim was investigated to determine
whether he funded a trip to North Korea a year ago by Suh, whether
Kim sent a message to North Korean leader Kim Il Sung, and how Suh
became involved in party politics.
   Suh is jailed on charges of security violations and espionage
and accepting $120,000 from communist agents. Nine people also were
arrested in the case.
   Kim, who has run twice for president, has denied any involvement
in Suh's trip. He accused the government of political harassment
aimed at disgracing his party.
   ``I rebutted point-by-point all points of suspicion raised by
the NSP (Agency for National Security Planning),'' Kim said. ``I
deplore our political atmosphere in which the head of the largest
opposition party was detained without sufficient grounds.''
   Kim said he had no prior knowledge of Suh's trip and so could
not have sent a message to the north. The opposition leader
admitted he had given Suh $1,000 but it was customary for him to
give some money to party members making overseas trips.
</TEXT>
