<SECOND>PM-Georgia Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Killed in Fiery Crash in Georgia; Two Die in Fla. Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with identities of victims. Picks
up 7th graf, `Ciaravella said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine airplane crashed on takeoff at
the Albany airport, killing all six people aboard as it cartwheeled
down the runway and burst into flames.
   Witnesses said the plane lost an engine Wednesday afternoon
after barely getting aloft. It dipped to the right, breaking a wing
and spewing fuel.
   In Florida, a single-engine plane crashed in the front yard of a
home shortly after takeoff, killing the two people aboard,
officials said.
   Both planes were based at a Sarasota, Fla., airport.
   The bodies of the six people in the Georgia crash were removed
from the wreckage Wednesday night and taken to two Albany hospitals
for identification, said Mike Armour, manager of the Southwest
Georgia Regional Airport.
   The plane was based at Dolphin Aviation of Sarasota, and owned
by D.L. Porter Construction of Sarasota, a commercial contractor,
said Ron Ciaravella, president of Dolphin Aviation.
   Porter Construction identified the dead as Donald Porter, 45, of
Sarasota, president of the firm; Steven Loer, 26, of Sarasota, a
Porter Construction vice president; Ernie Zimmerman of Port
Charlotte, Fla., a retired educator from the Cleveland, Ohio, area
who was a friend of Porter's; John Gianitsis, a company pilot from
Sarasota; Jamie Suarez, 22, a Florida International University
student working at Porter for the summer; and Nelson J. Miller, 28,
of Sarasota, a company construction superintendent.
   Ciaravella said the plane left Sarasota 7:30 a.m. Wednesday for
Savannah and flew on to Albany en route to Akron, Ohio.
   Investigators from the Federal Aviation Administration and the
National Transportation Safety Board were to begin an investigation
today.
   The propeller-driven aircraft had climbed only about 10 feet off
the ground at the Southwest Georgia Regional Airport when its right
engine caught fire, witnesses said.
   Witnesses reported that the plane's right wing then slammed into
the ground, spilling fuel as the aircraft cartwheeled several times.
   The plane, engulfed in flames, came to rest upside down and
broken apart in a grassy area near the control tower.
   The fire prevented any rescue, witnesses said. ``There's not
much you can do when that gas ignited,'' said off-duty Eastern
Airlines pilot Doug Powell, a witness to the crash.
   In the Florida crash, a plane took off from Sarasota-Bradenton
Airport on the Gulf Coast just before 2 p.m., but the pilot made
two distress calls a short time later, said Manatee County
sheriff's spokesman Dave Bristow.
   The pilot, whose craft apparently developed engine trouble,
tried to return to the airport, but crashed in the front yard of a
Bradenton home about a mile northwest of the airport, Bristow said.
   Ciaravella said tomato grower James Croley and pilot Alan
DeLoach were flying to Stuart, Fla., to meet with a prospective
buyer of the 1972 Beechcraft 824-R at the time of the crash.
</TEXT>
