<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     08-03 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zimbabwe Says it Won't Seize White-Owned Farms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Robert Mugabe's government
said Thursday it is under pressure to hand over white-owned land to
peasant farmers, but promised it won't seize private farms.
   ``I want to assure you the government is not a grabber,'' Rural
Development Minister Joshua Nkomo told a meeting of the
4,000-member Commercial Farmers' Union in Harare.
   But Nkomo said the state will push ahead to redress continuing
imbalances in land ownership in this Southern African nation of 9.2
million people.
   About 4,000 mainly white commercial farmers own one-third of
land in Zimbabwe, a country slightly smaller than California. Eight
million peasants occupy roughly the same amount of land as white
farmers.
   Land hunger was a key issue of the seven-year bush war that
ended when the white-ruled former British colony of Rhodesia became
independent Zimbabwe in 1980.
   But since then, only a few hundred white farmers have sold their
properties to the state for peasant resettlement programs funded by
Britain and the United States. The deals were made under a
``willing seller-willing buyer'' clause in Zimbabwe's first
constitution which expires next April, 10 years after independence.
   ``In the coming year, when this provision ceases to be
effective, government will not grab land from anybody,'' Nkomo told
about 200 white farmers at their annual convention.
   But, he said, ``The government has been under pressure. The
people have been saying: `We believed that after independence
things would change, yet we still sit here in exactly the same
manner as before.'''
   Mugabe's government says it is socialist but encourages a mixed
economy to flourish.
   Nkomo said the government plans a ``socio-economic evaluation''
of commercial and peasant farming to find ways of releasing more
land to peasants.
   He urged white farmers to ``sit together as citizens of this
country and address this problem.''
   Zimbabwe's agriculture-based economy produces $1 billion worth
of crops a year, including $500 million in foreign currency from
tobacco, cotton and other exports. It is one of the few African
nations that produces enough to feed itself and export food.
   Commercial farmers say they are the nation's largest single
employer, supporting a workforce of 380,000 people and 1.5 million
of their dependents.
   Since independence, 52,000 peasant families averaging six family
members have been resettled on about 1.2 million acres.
   About 1 million acres, 16 percent of total white-owned
farmlands, were bought by the state. The rest was former state land
turned over to resettlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-03 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Kill 18; More Talks in New Delhi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese radicals shot and killed 18
people in southern areas, including nine relatives of a government
lawmaker, officials said Thursday.
   In New Delhi, Indian and Sri Lankan officials held talks for a
sixth day Thursday on a timetable for withdrawing an estimated
45,000 Indian troops from the Indian Ocean island nation, an Indian
government spokesman said.
   The troops were sent more than two years ago to enforce a plan
aimed at ending the fight by Tamil rebels for autonomy in the north
and east. Radicals of the Sinhalese majority have attacked the
government, claiming it has given too many concessions to the Tamil
minority.
   The nine relatives of lawmaker P.D. Abeyaratna were shot and
killed Wednesday at Kalutara town, 25 miles south of Colombo, said
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Abeyaratna was not at home when the attack occurred.
   The other victims included four workers of a government cement
factory, a physician and his assistant and two unidentified
civilians. The deaths occurred in the southern province.
   Police in the area Thursday found the body of a man who was shot
to death.
   In Colombo, another group of radicals dressed in police uniforms
raided a government armory Wednesday and escaped with 25 automatic
rifles after a heavy exchange of fire, police said. At least five
government security men were wounded.
   Minutes before the raid, bombs exploded in three other areas of
the capital in what police said were diversionary tactics by the
radicals. One civilian was injured in the explosions, police said.
   The government offered limited autonomy to Tamil-majority areas
in July 1987 in a bid to appease Tamil rebels fighting for an
independent nation since 1983.
   At least 4,000 people, mainly government officials, have been
killed in the two-year Sinhalese uprising. The Tamil insurgency has
claimed another 11,000 lives.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and the
Sinhalese make up 75 percent. Tamils accuse the Sinhalese of
discriminating against them in jobs, education and use of the
Sinhalese language.
</TEXT>
