<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FHAFraud Bjt   08-03 0986</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FHA Fraud, Bjt,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0643 to correct category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>FHA Fraud in Oklahoma ``Probably Largest in the Country''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To appreciate the immense potential for
housing fraud in depressed Oklahoma, one needed only to look at the
numbers: At one point last year, the state had 1,459 foreclosed FHA
homes while New York City had 39 and Boston had one.
   Potential turned into reality, and now Oklahoma has ``probably
the largest FHA fraud in the country,'' says Charles Ming, area
manager for the federal Department of Housing and Urban
Development, which includes FHA.
   Some estimates of the Federal Housing Administration fraud have
approached $1 billion. A special team of federal investigators has
been poring over records and mortgage documents for months, and
already more than 20 people have either been convicted, pleaded
guilty or agreed to do so.
   The possible scope of the situation in Oklahoma was spelled out
by Ming, who estimated that fraud may have tainted up to two-thirds
of the 5,600 FHA loan defaults over the past 2{ years. Some
promoters were raking in illicit cash from 100 homes each, he said.
   Oklahoma's oil-related economic straits provided a calamitous
backdrop for illegal schemes. Thousands of homes stand vacant;
hundreds more are on the market with no buyers in sight. Along with
the high-rollers who made hundreds of thousands of dollars, the
lure of a few extra dollars also sucked in such people as a retired
policeman and an Air Force mechanic.
   Ming and Troy Grigsby, HUD deputy field office manager,
described three basic forms of fraud:
   _Submitting false documents to the FHA in order to obtain
mortgage insurance. Grigsby said this involved setting someone up
as a ``straw man'' purchaser of a house, often with money provided
by the investor. Generally, this ``straw man'' was an average
person looking to make easy money, officials said.
   _Kiting a property's value through sham sales. Grigsby said the
fraud came when someone would purchase a property, then ``sell'' it
to a friend at several times its value. ``Then using appraisals
based on the higher sale figure, they would get an FHA loan,'' he
said.
   _Equity skimming, where someone supposedly assumes a mortgage,
rents out the property but never makes any mortgage payments. ``The
lender never realized anything was wrong until the mortgage went
into foreclosure,'' Grigsby said.
   Ming said homeowners faced with crushing payments were all too
ready to bite when someone offered perhaps $1,000 and an agreement
to take over his mortgage, never realizing that the ``buyer'' had
no intention of making any mortgage payments, he said.
   Dozens of surprised renters have been forced to move when the
home on which they paid monthly rent was foreclosed. Even more
surprised was the original owner, who found himself liable for the
defaulted mortgage.
   An unusual twist was uncovered during the winter when
investigators found unsuspecting families living in foreclosed and
supposedly vacant homes. In each case, someone had removed the
locks placed by real estate agents and, posing as the owners, had
rented out the houses.
   Acting U.S. Attorney Robert E. Mydans says 13 people have been
convicted in connection with one scheme or another. Five others
have pleaded guilty and are awaiting sentencing and four more have
agreed to plea bargains but have not yet entered their pleas,
Mydans said.
   A federal court jury earlier this year convicted a real estate
investor, a minister and an Air Force civilian employee of making
false statements and using phony documents to obtain FHA-insured
loans in 31 transactions totaling more than $800,000. All ended in
default.
   Cecil R. Johnson was a typical illegal investor.
   The government alleged that in a standard deal, Johnson would
purchase a run-down property, have it appraised at a highly
inflated ``refurbished'' value, and then obtain a conventional loan
based on that higher value.
   He would use only a small part of the loan money to repair the
house while pocketing the rest, then get someone to buy the home
with an FHA-insured loan, the government said.
   One of the straw men set up by Johnson was Robert McKittrick, a
retired Oklahoma City police officer, who admitted receiving $4,000
for participating in several deals. He was placed on probation,
fined $50 and ordered to repay HUD the $4,000.
   Lloyde Billman, a retired meat salesman, testified in court that
he was almost broke and trying to care for an ailing wife when he
became involved with Johnson. Only when Johnson placed $14,000 in
his bank account was he able to qualify for an FHA loan, Billman
said. He was put on probation, fined $50 and ordered to repay
$2,400 to HUD.
   Johnson was sentenced to four years in prison, fined $3,540 and
ordered to repay $150,000 to HUD.
   FHA fraud isn't the only part of the burgeoning scandals at HUD
to touch on Oklahoma City.
   A HUD audit has linked Philip Winn, now ambassador to
Switzerland, and two other former HUD officials to a group alleged
to have made millions of dollars in ``unjustified profits'' on
multi-family rehabilitation projects, including one here.
   Winn, who served as an assistant secretary for housing for a
year, was partners with Philip Abrams, former HUD undersecretary,
and J. Michael Queenan, former director of HUD's regional office in
Denver.
   Jack G. Womack, executive director of the Oklahoma City Housing
Authority, said he had informed HUD that rent on a two-bedroom
apartment in the Oklahoma City project should have been about $250.
Instead, he said, the Winn group and Benton Mortgage Co., a
Nashville-based company that has been suspended from government
work, insisted it should be $357.
   After debt service for rehabilitation work was added to the
$357, the rent for a two-bedroom apartment came to $479, Womack
said. Since the typical renter will pay only $100 to $150, the
federal government has to pick up the rest, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
