<SECOND>AM-Hostages-UN, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon to Build Monument to U.N. Peacekeepers Who Died in Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT wording of title.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's U.N. ambassador said Thursday it
will build a monument to U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins
and 164 other U.N. peacekeepers who have died in Lebanon.
   ``Lt. Col. Higgins would be very prominent in the memorial,''
Ambassador Chawki Choueri told The Associated Press. ``He was one
of the commanders and lost his life for the peacekeeping force.''
   Choueri said the monument would honor Higgins and 164
peacekeepers who have died in service with the U.N. Interim Force
in Lebanon, called UNIFIL.
   Higgins was commanding an observer group of the U.N. Truce
Supervision Organization attached to UNIFIL when he was kidnapped
Feb. 17, 1988, by a pro-Iranian Shiite group, the Organization of
the Oppressed on Earth.
   They accused Higgins of spying for the CIA, and announced Monday
he had been hanged because Israel refused to release a Shiite
cleric it had abducted on Friday.
   A competition for the design of the monument will be announced
soon and consideration will be given to a site, most likely in
southern Lebanon where the peacekeepers have been trying to enforce
a truce zone, Choueri said.
   In addition to Higgins, six members of the U.N. Truce
Supervision Organization have died since its founding in 1948, five
of them in accidents or in action.
   U.N. officials say 125 of the UNIFIL casualties died in action
or in accidents, and the rest died of other causes.
   Four Irish members of the 5,854-strong UNIFIL force died in two
separate attacks in the last six months. Machine-gun fire from a
Christian militia killed one man, and three died when their truck
hit a mine.
   The nations contributing to the force are Fiji, Finland, France,
Ghana, Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and Sweden. UNIFIL is
commanded by Lt. Gen. Lars-Eric Wahlgren of Sweden.
</TEXT>
