<FIRST>r w AM-Hostages-RobinHiggins     08-03 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Robin Higgins,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Higgins Gets Call from British Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
telephoned the wife of Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins and
lauded her for ``strength and courage,'' a Pentagon spokeswoman
said Thursday.
   Mrs. Thatcher called Robin Higgins Wednesday morning, said Maj.
Kathy Wood, an Army spokeswoman.
   ``She just wanted Robin to know that she is in constant contact
with President Bush and that if there is anything they can do, they
will. She also said she admired Robin's strength and courage in
this crisis,'' Ms. Wood added.
   The spokeswoman described Mrs. Higgins as ``touched that the
prime minister would call her'' to express her concern.
   A Shiite Moslem group claimed it killed Higgins on Monday
because of Israel's refusal to release a Shiite Moslem clergyman it
kidnapped last week.
   Higgins, of Lexington, Ky., was part of a United Nations
observer force in Lebanon when he was kidnapped in February 1988.
His captors, the Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, accused
him of being a spy and said in July 1988 that he had been sentenced
to death.
   Ms. Wood said Mrs. Higgins also went to New York Wednesday
evening to meet with U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Mrs. Higgins described the session with the U.N. official as
private and relayed no other information about it, Ms. Wood said.
   The U.N. official has dispatched envoy Marrack Goulding to
Lebanon to search for Higgins' body.
   Mrs. Higgins, a Marine major, has been on leave from her job as
a public affairs official in the Defense Department's information
office for the past several days. She has refused interviews and
comes daily to the Pentagon to be updated about her husband's
situation.
</TEXT>
