<FIRST>r a AM-People     08-03 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0969</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT A.P. HILL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Spielberg, movie director and
Eagle Scout, said he came to the 12th National Scout Jamboree to
return a debt he owed to Scouting.
   ``Scouting helped me with leadership. It taught me how to speak
out,'' the director of such movies as ``Jaws'' and ``E.T. The
Extra-Terrestrial'' said Wednesday during the first day of the
jamboree.
   Scouting ``built my self-confidence,'' Spielberg told about 400
Scouts chosen as hometown news correspondents. ``I took out of
Scouting, then I never put back in. Here's my turn to put back in.
That's why I'm here.''
   The 41-year-old Spielberg, who started making movies as a Scout
to get his photography merit badge, was given the Distinguished
Eagle Scout award Wednesday night for his work in films and his
involvement in Scouting. He also introduced a new cinematography
merit badge.
   ``I think the proudest moment of my entire life was when I
became an Eagle Scout,'' Spielberg told a crowd of about 70,000
Scouts, leaders and visitors who gathered for the evening ceremony
in an outdoor amphitheater. ``I have never been as proud as I am
right now to be an American in this country.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly Gromyko, the son of Andrei Gromyko,
the late Soviet foreign minister, says the United States must
support social, economic and political changes occurring in his
homeland.
   ``One of the dangers we face more often than not is to adhere to
old stereotypes in social, economic and political behavior,''
Gromyko told an audience of about 250 on Wednesday. The forum was
sponsored by Town Hall, a 51-year-old non-profit, non-partisan
organization that provides topical speakers.
   ``Trade barriers between the U.S. and Soviet Union should
ease,'' Gromyko said in fluent English. ``With the help of Los
Angeles area business leaders, we can have normal trade relations.
We see a positive trend beginning in Los Angeles already.''
   Gromyko answered questions from a diverse audience including
high school students, civic leaders and former California Gov.
Edmund G. ``Pat'' Brown.
   The younger Gromyko is director of the Institute for African
Studies at the Soviet Academy of Sciences.
   His father died July 2 at age 79. He served as the Soviet
Union's foreign minister under five Kremlin leaders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN BRUNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Madden has chosen the new man
behind the wheel of his Maddencruiser, the touring home on wheels
used to transport the TV sports commentator around the country.
   David Hahn, a 49-year-old driver from Aurora, Colo., beat eight
finalists who faced off in competition this week to see who would
become the latest chauffeur for Madden, who doesn't like flying or
taking trains.
   The customized vehicle features a constant temperature, an
oversized shower, an abundance of telephones and electronic
gadgets, and a kitchenette that includes a microwave.
   ``For a driver's career, this is it,'' said Tony Martinez, a
driver from Hayward who got the slot as a alternate driver in the
1988 contest. ``This is serious. This guy is worth a million
bucks.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five singing Osmond brothers are
targets of a federal lawsuit alleging they failed to pay nearly
$150,000 owed on a 1980 loan from the now-defunct Utah Firstbank.
   A second suit, also filed by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
in U.S. District Court on Wednesday, charged that brothers Merrill
and Wayne Osmond and a Salt Lake City man, Joseph S. Gasser Jr.,
also owe more than $38,000 on a loan made in 1985 from the same
bank.
   The FDIC, suing as the receiver of Firstbank's assets after it
closed, is suing for recovery of the larger amount from Osmond
brothers Donald, Jay, Alan, Merrill and Wayne, and from Gasser and
the two partnerships under which the government agency says the
loans were taken out.
   Telephone calls to Merrill Osmond's office Thursday for comment
were unsuccessful because of repeated busy signals on the line.
   ``Although payment (on the larger loan) has been demanded, only
one payment, in the amount of $35,000, has been paid,'' claims the
suit filed concerning the 1980 loan.
   The second complaint states that ``neither the whole or any
part'' of the smaller loan had been paid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mister Rogers, the public television institution
who has been entertaining children for more than 30 years, is often
the butt of comedians' jokes, but he says it's only because they
like him so much.
   ``Mr. (Johnny) Carson has done quite a few of those, and I asked
him why,'' Fred Rogers told Parade magazine in its upcoming Sunday
issue. ``He said, `We wouldn't do those if we didn't have such
great affection for you.'''
   ``Eddie Murphy does a parody, too. I was at NBC one day, and he
came down the hall, threw his arms around me and said, `Ah, the
real Mister Rogers!'''
   Rogers, 61, whose ``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood'' has been
broadcast in various versions since the early 1960s, is an ordained
Presbyterian minister from Pennsylvania. He has written several
books _ on everything from potty-training to how to help children
handle divorce.
   Asked if he had any regrets about how he raised his two grown
sons, Rogers said: ``Neglect isn't just beating kids. It's ignoring
them. We didn't ignore the boys, but I'd like to have spent more
time with them.''
   Rogers says he has met shy children but never one who rejected
him.
   ``I never force myself. I just get out Daniel Striped Tiger (a
hand puppet) and slide him under my arm _ he's shy too _ and I
start talking to them.''
</TEXT>
