<FIRST>r a AM-TMICracks     08-03 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TMI Cracks,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Possible Cracks Seen At Bottom Of Unit 2 Reactor Vessel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers at Three Mile Island, site of
the nation's worst commercial nuclear plant accident, are studying
what could be two small cracks on the inside of the damaged
reactor, a spokeswoman said Thursday.
   It is not yet known if the small lines that showed up on a
remote television inspection of the reactor bottom are indeed
cracks, said plant spokeswoman Mary Wells. They could be scales or
rivulets of molten material left over from the March 1979 accident,
she said.
   ``We don't know the significance,'' Ms. Wells said, adding that
a team of six engineers has been set up to study the situation.
   The possible cracks were discovered by a team of experts
studying the Unit 2 reactor, which has been shut since the accident
and is being cleaned and readied for long-term closure. There are
no plans to restart the reactor.
   The bottom of the carbon steel reactor vessel is 5 inches thick
at the point the possible cracks were found and is covered on the
inside by a steel liner one-eighth inch thick.
   There has been no indication of any leaks through the bottom of
the reactor vessel, Ms. Wells said.
   Half of the 150-ton radioactive core at TMI-2 collapsed and
melted in the accident, when a series of mechanical failures and
operator errors blocked vital cooling water. Radioactive gases were
released.
   The possible cracks were found in early July at the base of two
of 52 nozzles where instruments once protruded into the core, at a
spot where temperatures were the hottest during the accident. One
of the lines is at the point where a nozzle is welded to the liner,
the other appears to extend from the weld to the liner itself.
   Many of the nozzles were covered with molten debris that flowed
to the reactor's bottom. Most of that debris was removed within the
past month, giving technicians their first good view of the reactor
bottom since the accident.
   Technicians have done remote television inspection of all but
five of the nozzles, but also want to take another look at 10
because of some visibility problems, Ms. Wells said.
   In mid-August, probing tools and, for the first time, a color
television camera will be lowered into the vessel to give the study
team a better idea of whether the lines are cracks.
   One theory is that small cracks could have occurred because the
stainless steel contracts at a different rate than the underlying
carbon steel, said spokesman Doug Bedell. The possible cracks are
on or near welds holding the nozzle bases to the vessel, he said.
   Bedell said any conclusions on whether the cracks _ should they
prove to be cracks _ meant the situation at TMI a decade ago was
worse than previously thoughtwould have to await completion of a
Nuclear Regulatory Commission study. In the study, set to begin
later this year, samples of the steel will be taken and studied.
   About 275,000 pounds, or 92 percent, of the debris, remaining
fuel and other metal components have been removed from the reactor
vessel.
   By the end of next year, the plant operator, GPU Nuclear Corp.,
plans to put the plant in long-term, monitored storage. The plan is
awaiting approval by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
