<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Elderly-MentalIllness     08-03 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly-Mental Illness,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nursing Homes Said to `Warehouse' Elderly With Mental Illnesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mentally ill nursing home residents often are
improperly drugged and denied adequate care because government
policies discourage treatment and trained aides are in short
supply, experts told a House committee Thursday.
   Janet Pacatte of the National Mental Health Association said
insufficient federal funds and the lack of adequately trained staff
``contribute to warehousing hundreds of thousands of elderly
Americans who suffer from a mental illness.''
   ``There is a substantial unmet need for mental health services
for the nursing home population,'' she told the House Select
Committee on Aging.
   Several mental health experts testified that mental disorders
affect from 50 percent to more than 90 percent of the nation's 1.5
million nursing home residents, with nursing home populations
likely to increase rapidly as the population ages.
   Mental illnesses frequently are undiagnosed or mistreated at
nursing homes because Medicaid and Medicare reimbursement policies
are biased in favor of the treatment of physical ailments, they
said.
   Dr. Barry Fogel of the American Psychiatric Association said
nursing homes shy away from diagnosing mental illness because they
could be reclassified as mental institutions and ruled ineligible
for Medicaid payments if too many of their patients are being
treated for such problems.
   In addition, Fogel said, Medicare and Medicaid reimbursement
rates for psychiatric services in nursing homes are inadequate to
attract enough psychiatrists, and nursing home staffs often lack
training for these problems.
   ``The consequence is the treatment of mental and behavioral
symptoms with psychotropic (mind-altering) drugs alone, rather than
with a comprehensive and holistic approach,'' Fogel said.
   Ms. Pacatte cited the experience of her own mother as a case of
overmedication.
   ``I cannot begin to share with the dismay and horror I felt when
I visited my mother in a nursing home and found her in a
drug-related stuper, hallucinating and completely out of touch
because she was on inappropriate use of psychotropic drugs,'' she
said.
   Ms. Pacatte called for changes to ``radically alter the
deplorable situation now found in so many nursing homes where staff
are untrained, lack professional support and residents go without
essential mental health treatment and are often inappropriately
restrained.''
   Dr. Michael A. Smyer, professor of human development at
Pennsylvania State University, said more federal dollars should be
earmarked for training geriatric specialists. He also called for
removing the barriers to mental health treatment that are built
into the Medicaid and Medicare programs.
   C. Ross Anthony, associate administrator for program development
at the Health Care Financing Administration, conceded that Medicaid
and Medicare are ``heavily weighted'' toward acute medical care
rather than mental health services.
   But he added: ``The Medicare and Medicaid programs now provide
more and better ways to finance medically necessary services for
the mentally ill than ever before.''
   Committee Chairman Rep. Edward Roybal, D-Calif., has introduced
legislation to shift more Medicaid and Medicare dollars toward
mental health services in nursing homes and to target $30 million
in community mental health money for the elderly.
   ``For far too long, mental health care has been a neglected
priority in our American health care system,'' Roybal said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
