<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AgentOrange     08-03 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Assistance for Agent Orange Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved legislation Thursday that
would give Vietnam-era veterans disability benefits for certain
illnesses associated with U.S. use of Agent Orange.
   The bill provides payments on an interim basis, through April
15, 1992, while providing for subsequent congressional votes to
make the benefits permanent. Benefits would be paid to veterans
with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and soft-tissue sarcoma.
   A broader version is pending in the House.
   Passage of the Senate bill by voice vote was a victory for
veterans advocates, who have been battling government scientists.
They have accused various agencies of ignoring evidence about the
deadly herbicide while government scientists have said that no
clear cause-and-effect relationship has been established.
   ``It has been a long, hard struggle,'' said Sen. Alan Cranston,
D-Calif., a co-sponsor of the bill and chairman of the Veterans
Affairs Committee. ``Too many Vietnam veterans and their families
have suffered anguish for far too long.''
   ``This bill is important ... obviously because it creates a
presumption in favor of veterans,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.,
a Vietnam veteran. He said the measure makes it clear that ``there
will not be an adversariness in the attempt by veterans to seek the
services that they are entitled to. ... It does not open up a
Pandora's box of benefits because these are two very rare
diseases.''
   The bill was discussed on the Senate floor late Wednesday and
passed with little difficulty Thursday morning.
   An estimated 2.6 million military personnel were in South
Vietnam during the war in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Some
250,000 have told the Veterans Administration, now the Department
of Veterans Affairs, that they believe they were exposed, and
35,000 have applied for disability benefits.
   Veterans already are allowed to receive outpatient and hospital
care for illnesses presumed to be linked to Agent Orange.
   Approximately 12 million gallons of the herbicide were sprayed
during the Vietnam War to remove the foliage providing ground cover
for the enemy. Agent Orange contains dioxin, one of the most toxic
chemicals known, as well as 2,4,5-T and 2,4-D, also harmful
chemicals.
   The bill in the House would allow veterans to be compensated
longer, and for more diseases. Under it, veterans with
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, soft-tissue sarcoma, melanoma and basal
cell carcinoma would be eligible for permanent disability benefits.
So would their survivors.
   The House bill has been estimated to cost $40 million. No such
estimate was available for the Senate version, although it would be
considerably less.
   The Senate bill establishes _ for the first time _ a presumption
of service connection for any Vietnam veteran with chloracne, a
skin condition, provided it occurred within a year of the time the
person's service tour ended.
   Both bills require extensive record-keeping by the Veterans
Administration based on health reports and tissue samples from
veterans. Both would ask the National Academy of Sciences to review
scientific studies on Agent Orange exposure every two years, with
the Department of Veterans Affairs making its benefits
determinations based on those reviews.
   The Senate passed an Agent Orange bill last year but the measure
never emerged from the House Veterans' Affairs Committee.
   Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., chairman of that
committee, and the senior minority member, Rep. Bob Stump, R-Ariz.,
sent colleagues a letter last month calling the House bill
``premature at best.''
   They cited a continuing study by the Centers for Disease Control
on the incidence of selected cancers among Vietnam-era veterans,
due for completion next spring, and noted a federal court order to
change the criteria used to evaluate Agent Orange studies and the
recent creation of a U.S. Court of Veterans Appeals to review
claims.
   But supporters of the bill said the CDC and VA had moved too
slowly to determine whether a link exists between Agent Orange and
the various afflictions.
   During a House Government Operations subcommittee hearing in
early July, the CDC was accused of rigging its Agent Orange study
to show no direct link. Officials of the health agency maintained
that it dropped a massive study of Agent Orange exposure because
there was no way to tell who was exposed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
