<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     08-03 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Complain of No Progress in U.S-PLO Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians told a U.S. envoy Thursday there
has been an ``alarming lack of progress'' in the U.S.-PLO dialogue,
and urged the United States to change what they called its
pro-Israel stance.
   Also Thursday, 17 people were wounded by plastic bullets when
Israeli troops opened fire on the main street of Khan Yunis in the
occupied Gaza Strip, hospital officials said.
   The troops fired after their patrol was hit by a hand grenade,
injuring three soldiers and three Palestinians, the army and Arab
reports said.
   The clashes came as the Supreme Court in Jerusalem ruled that
the army's regulations on the use of plastic bullets were legal and
denied a request that the bullets be banned or put under stricter
limits.
   Thirteen prominent Palestinians from the occupied lands met with
John Kelly, assistant secretary of state for Middle East affairs,
who is on the first leg of a tour that will include Egypt and
Jordan.
   The Palestinians said in a statement that they considered the
session ``to be part of the ongoing U.S.-PLO dialogue'' which was
launched in Tunis last December after PLO chief Yasser Arafat
renounced terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   They said that dialogue ``has so far demonstrated an alarming
lack of progress in matters of substance and the levels of
representation.''
   Earlier, Kelly met for an hour with Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir. Kelly told reporters after the meeting that they discussed
the peace process, but declined to give details.
   Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokesman, did not say if the meeting
touched on the Israeli abduction of Lebanese Shiite leader Sheik
Abdul Karim Obeid on July 28. The abduction led to the apparent
execution of a U.S. hostage, U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R.
Higgins, by his Lebanese captors.
   Higgins' killing was to be high on the agenda at the fifth
congress of the Fatah movement, the main component of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which opened Thursday in Tunis.
   PLO spokesman Ahmed Abdel-Rahman said the incident was to be
discussed as part of the congress' consideration of Lebanon, which
has been wracked by a 14-year-old civil war.
   Fatah on Tuesday condemned the killing of Higgins but put the
blame on Israel.
   In his opening speech at the congress, Arafat said the PLO
disliked the original Israeli plan for elections in the occupied
territories, but would have accepted it if it had been a step
toward Palestinian self-determination.
   The Israeli plan aimed at ``perpetuating the Israeli occupation
of the occupied territories'' and has now collapsed in failure,
Arafat said.
   Shamir has called for elections in the West Bank and Gaza,
occupied by Israel since 1967, to select Palestinians to open talks
with Israel on an interim autonomy agreement. The plan also calls
for Arab countries to make peace with Israel.
   Radwan Abu Ayyash, head of the Arab Journalists Association in
east Jerusalem, said the Palestinians told Kelly ``nothing could
happen here'' without approval of the PLO, and that Israel must be
convinced to accept the U.S.-backed concept of trading land for
peace.
   He said Kelly, in turn, warned that while the United States
would assist in the peace process, it was up to the two sides to
offer acceptable proposals.
   ``We are not going to deliver you to Israel, neither are we
going to deliver Israel to you. There is a table of negotiations,
and you have to make your own way to this table and you have to
learn how to live together,'' Abu Ayyash quoted Kelly as saying.
   In their statement, the Palestinians noted the United States had
endorsed Israel's plan for elections in the occupied lands but not
the PLO plan, which says the elections should lead to creation of a
Palestinian state.
   ``We view with the greatest seriousness the lack of
even-handedness and objectivity in the U.S. response,'' the
statement said.
</TEXT>
