<FIRST>u a BC-MosaicsTrial     08-03 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mosaics Trial,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Church Owns 6th Century Mosaics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled Thursday that four 6th
century mosaics purchased by a suburban Indianapolis art dealer are
the property of the Greek Orthodox Church of Cyprus.
   U.S. District Judge James E. Noland said in his ruling that Peg
Goldberg never obtained good title to the mosaics and has no right
to possess them.
   The two plaintiffs, the Republic of Cyprus and the Autocephalous
Greek-Orthodox Church of Cyprus, ``have made a proper showing in
all respects for the return of the mosaics,'' Noland said.
   Noland ruled that under the circumstances of the case, Ms.
Goldberg must return the mosaics but will not have to pay any
monetary damages.
   Ms. Goldberg purchased the mosaics in July 1988 after learning
of them in a trip to Amsterdam and viewing them in a Swiss airport.
   She said she had no immediate comment on the ruling but would
issue a statement later in the day.
   The seller was Aydin Dikman, a Turk living in Germany who
claimed he was a former archaeologist for the Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus. Court records show he has been linked to several
art thefts from Cyprus.
</TEXT>
