<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Hostages     08-03 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Hostages,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Insists on Prisoner Swap for Obeid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel said Thursday it will hold a kidnapped
Shiite Moslem cleric until Israeli soldiers are traded for him,
despite threats to American hostages in Lebanon.
   ``We still stick to our position that we are ready to exchange
kidnap victims and hostages,'' Yossi Ahimeir, spokesman for Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, told The Associated Press.
   ``Our goal is to rescue, save our people in Lebanon in the hands
of several organizations there. Of course, we are ready to make
exchanges of hostages.''
   Israel has offered to trade Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid and other
Lebanese Shiite prisoners for three soldiers held in Lebanon and
the Western hostages, who include eight Americans.
   Commandos abducted Obeid from his home in south Lebanon on July
28. Israel says he planned guerrilla raids and directed the
kidnapping of Lt. Co. William R. Higgins, a U.S. Marine serving
with U.N peacekeepers, in February 1988.
   Higgins' captors said they hanged him Monday in retaliation for
the abduction of Obeid, a spiritual leader of Hezbollah, the
pro-Iranian group believed to be behind the kidnapings.
   Several hours later, another group of kidnappers said they would
kill American hostage Joseph Cicippio, 58, unless Obeid was
released. After two extensions of the deadline, the death threat to
Cicippio was suspended on Thursday in connection with several new
demands on Israel.
   The kidnappers demanded the release of Obeid, as well as
Palestinian and Lebanese guerrillas held in Israel. The group said
it would provide a list of names of all the captives it wants
released to the Red Cross.
   Ahimeir reported ``all kinds of consultations'' within the
government about the hostage crisis.
   Yossi Ben Aharon, a top aide to Shamir, said Israel was in
``constant touch'' with the U.S. government, but he would not say
whether Shamir had talked by telephone with President Bush.
   The Foreign Ministry summoned the ambassadors of West Germany,
Italy and Britain, whose citizens are among the hostages in
Lebanon, and also the Japanese envoy.
   Israel radio said the Japanese ambassador was called in because
Japan was involved in contacts with Iran. The radio gave no details
and ministry officials could not be reached for comment.
   Italian Ambassador Alberto Leoncini Bartoli, asked later whether
his government was in touch with Iran, replied: ``No. I only know
that through the diplomatic channels there have been initiatives.''
   He said other countries in the region were involved in these
contacts, but ``to the best of my knowledge'' there has been no
response.
   ``My government has made approaches through diplomatic channels
to Iran, among other countries in the region. To my knowledge there
has been no response to these approaches yet.''
   Aharon said Israel would not change its position on Obeid.
   ``We took this gentleman for the purpose of releasing of our
three prisoners, and this remains the objective,'' he said.
   Higgins' captors released a poor-quality videotape of a man who
appeared to be the Marine colonel hanging from a gallows. There was
no way of telling when the tape was made, conflicting reports have
arisen about when he was killed.
   A Defense Ministry statement said Obeid told interrogators he
believed Higgins was alive last week, but quoted him as saying his
evidence was hearsay.
   The statement said Israel continued to believe Higgins was
killed late last year. Officials said they might give Obeid to a
lie-detector test to determine what he knew about the American
officer.
</TEXT>
