<FIRST>u w AM-CockpitTapes     08-03 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cockpit Tapes,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Condemns Broadcast of Cockpit Tape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Transportation Safety Board members
on Thursday condemned the public broadcast of a cockpit voice
recording from an airliner crash as ``lurid entertainment'' and a
threat to the board's work.
   The board voted 5-0 to express regret at an order by a Texas
judge that led to release this week of a tape from a Delta Air
Lines crash in Dallas last August that killed 14 people.
   The board's vote indicated support for Federal Aviation
Administration and Air Line Pilots Association calls for a law that
would bar release of automatically recorded audio tapes recovered
from crash scenes. The board, however, did not propose specific
legislation.
   The law already prohibits the safety board itself from publicly
releasing the 30-minute loop audio tapes which pick up sounds from
microphones in airliner cockpits. The board had turned over a copy
of the Delta tape to the Texas court as evidence in lawsuits
resulting from the crash.
   Delta appealed to the court not to release the tape, but the
judge granted pleas from the plaintiffs and news media for them to
be played.
   After each crash, the board by law makes a transcript and
releases a printed version only of portions relevant to its
investigation.
   Pilot communications with air traffic controllers are regularly
available to media, but FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said he can
recall no previous instance where sounds from a cockpit recorder
were aired publicly.
   The Delta tape, played in radio and television news reports
around the country, included sounds of the pilots of Delta Flight
1141 joking about politics and airplane crashes before the plane
crashed on takeoff. It also includes screams just before the crash.
The crew and more than 90 passengers survived.
   The NTSB, which expects to conclude its investigation of the
Dallas crash Sept. 26, said in a resolution: ``We believe that
transportation safety is better served by maintaining strict
confidentiality of the actual audio recording.''
   The board said it opposed the tape's public release ``or any
other actions which might inhibit effective communication between
crew members, or which might diminish its utility in the prevention
of accidents and the saving of lives.''
   Board member John Lauber said the recording is designed to be
used only in safety investigations, and ``certainly not for the
lurid entertainment of the public.''
   NTSB member Jim Burnett said cockpit tapes are ``painful things
to listen to, and why anyone would entertain the idea of making
either entertainment or drama out of them, I don't know.''
   The board deleted from a draft version of its statement language
that would have condemned the disabling of voice recorders by air
crews. Lauber said members oppose any tampering with the recorders,
which is illegal, but wanted to focus the statement on the
importance of the recorders in safety investigations.
   The pilots union withdrew Wednesday a threat to order its 41,000
members to disable the recorders. ALPA president Henry A. Duffy
said he was confident that Congress would correct the problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
