<FIRST>r w AM-Jackson     08-03 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Registers to Vote in Washington, Mum on Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson registered to vote in the
District of Columbia on Thursday, but shed no new light on a
possible run for mayor.
   Jackson has previously said he is ``not running'' for mayor in
the nation's capital, but he has refused to rule out entering the
race later. He declined to comment on the subject Thursday.
   He and his wife, Jacqueline, spent about 10 minutes filling out
a series of forms, and registered as Democrats, according to city
elections officials.
   After registering, Jackson said Washington would be the focal
point of his national political agenda, which includes improving
education, fighting drugs and gaining statehood for the District of
Columbia.
   ``I want to be of service to the people of the nation and
Washington D.C.,'' Jackson said. ``Washington, D.C., is the point
of challenge today for an urban policy for the nation.''
   City law requires that mayoral candidates be registered to vote
in the district at least one year before the general election. The
next election is scheduled for Nov. 6, 1990.
   Jackson has said he would never run against Mayor Marion Barry
Jr., an ally from the civil rights movement, but after Barry
declared he would seek a fourth term, Jackson refused to take
himself out of consideration.
   The two-time Democratic presidential hopeful has said he was
moving to the nation's capital to be closer to the legislative
process. The national offices of the Rainbow Coalition, a poor
people's advocacy group Jackson founded, is scheduled to open
offices here in September.
   He has said he has no plans to sell his Chicago home.
</TEXT>
