<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     08-03 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Senator Refuses Offer To Join Communist Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak on
Thursday offered a Solidarity senator a Cabinet position in his new
government, but the senator turned him down, an opposition
spokesman said.
   Kiszczak proposed the top post in the Ministry of Health to Dr.
Zofia Kuratowska, who is also a senior adviser to Solidarity on
health policy, the spokesman said.
   State TV later reported the offer but not the refusal.
   Ms. Kuratowska refused Kiszczak's offer and told him that
lawmakers belonging to the independent trade union movement did not
plan to enter the government, said Grzegorz Jaszunski, who is also
Ms. Kuratowska's husband.
   Ms. Kuratowska appeared to be the first opposition lawmaker to
be approached to enter the government since Kiszczak was elected
Wednesday by the Sejm, the larger chamber of the National Assembly.
   Efforts to reach opposition floor leaders in the Sejm to learn
of any further offers were unsuccessful.
   In his acceptance speech Wednesday, Kiszczak, Poland's interior
minister for the past eight years, said he hoped to attract
opposition members to his government and that he believed he could
name the Cabinet in about two weeks.
   Communist leaders would like some opposition legislators to join
the government to share some of the responsibility for reform
programs, but Solidarity says it cannot enter the government while
the Communist Party holds a monopoly on power.
   Ms. Kuratowska is a leading critic of state medical policy that
has led to overcrowded hospitals, a shortage of medicine and a
flight of poorly paid medical personnel to the West. She favors
establishment of small clinics to put patients in closer contact
with doctors.
   Jaszunski said she informed Solidarity floor leaders in the
National Assembly of her decision.
   The Sejm must approve the Cabinet. The communist-coalition holds
a 299-161 majority. The Solidarity-dominated Senate, the smaller
chamber of the National Assembly, does not vote on the government.
   Also Thursday, the main opposition daily protested the
Kiszczak's election as prime minister, blaming him in part for a
severe economic crisis.
   ``Society does not understand why someone who represents the
party which is responsible for this situation has to take the lead
of a Cabinet that wants to call itself a government of `national
rescue,' '' the opposition Gazeta Wybcorcza newspaper said.
   There was no immediate comment from Lech Walesa or other
Solidarity leaders.
   Official newspapers did not comment on the choice of the
nation's top policeman as the new head of government and instead
focused on food price increases that took effect this week as part
of market-oriented reform.
   The official communist party newspaper Trybuna Ludu and the
government daily Rzeczpospolita carried only official news agency
reports of the Kiszczak's election without commentary.
   The election of Kiszczak completes a top level political
reshuffle that began with the election of Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
to the newly strengthened post of president on July 19, and the
naming of outgoing Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski as first
secretary of the Communist Party July 29.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
