<FIRST>r w AM-Productivity 1stLd-Writethru a0633 08-03 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Productivity, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Farm Productivity Up Slightly; Inflation Erodes Wage Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDs 3 grafs with new productivity figures, bgng, The report,
etc</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The productivity of American workers increased
modestly in the second quarter of the year after declining in the
first, the government said Thursday in a report that also showed
workers got significant pay hikes but lost buying power because of
inflation.
   The Labor Department said non-farm productivity rose at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 0.2 percent in the April-June
period as output climbed 1.7 percent and hours worked by just 1.5
percent.
   That was an improvement over the revised 1.3 percent decline in
non-farm productivity at an annual rate reported for the first
three months of the year.
   Unit labor costs rose at an annual rate of 5.2 percent in the
second quarter, the government said, down from a 6.2 percent gain
in the first three months of the year but still a significant
increase that ultimately translates into higher prices.
   Merrill Lynch's Bruce Steinberg said persistent wage gains would
limit overall inflation declines.
   ``I think the inflation environment is looking somewhat better
than it had been, but this is a cautionary note,'' he said.
   Despite the wage gains _ hourly compensation rose at a 5.5
percent annual rate in the April-June quarter _ American workers
still saw their buying power erode. Real wages _ compensation gains
minus the toll of consumer inflation _ fell at an annual rate of
0.9 percent in the second quarter, the government said.
   ``In some ways we're in the worst of both worlds now,'' said
chief economist David Wyss of DRI-McGraw Hill. ``The worker is
seeing wages go up less than inflation and the manufacturer is
seeing employment costs going up more than prices because of wage
gains and the explosion of fringe benefit costs.''
   Analysts said the declines or only modest productivity gains in
recent quarters were consistent with an economy nearing the end of
an expansion but said they were not necessarily a harbinger of
recession.
   Improved productivity _ the output per hour of all workers _ is
considered vital to sustaining economic growth at times of
near-full employment.
   With the current slowdown in the economy, productivity gains or
declines also will have a large effect on business profits because
uncertainty about the economy has left many businesses,
particularly in manufacturing, reluctant to hire new workers as a
means of improving output.
   The report issued Thursday was based on preliminary data that
generally are revised in a more comprehensive report issued a month
later.
   Manufacturing workers posted a significant gain in productivity
in the second quarter _ 2.4 percent at an annual rate _ but that
figure was influenced by a 0.3 percent drop in total hours worked,
another sign of the slowing economy.
   Inflation's toll was even more pronounced on manufacturing
workers, whose hourly compensation rose at an annual rate of 2.5
percent in the second quarter while consumer inflation increased
more than 6 percent _ meaning real wages paid manufacturing workers
fell at an annual rate of 3.7 percent in the latest quarter.
   The report also included revised productivity data for the years
1986 through 1988 showing productivity growth was slightly better
than originally believed, rising by 2 percent in 1986, 1.1 percent
in 1987 and 2.1 percent in 1988. Earlier data had put the increases
in those years at 2.0 percent, 0.8 percent and 1.5 percent,
respectively.
   The Bush administration, which had been criticized for using
unrealistic productivity estimates for its economic forecasts, took
satisfaction in the upward revision.
   Michael Boskin, chairman of the president's Council of Economic
Advisers, said that the administration was ``quite pleased that
non-farm productivity growth for 1986-88 was revised to a rate
almost exactly in line with our current thinking about the
economy's long run growth potential.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
