<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Workers     08-03 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Workers,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Storm Strikebound Plant; 1 Worker Killed, Hundreds Detained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELWAN, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stormed Egypt's largest steel plant
during a sit-down strike, killing one worker, injuring 14 and
arresting hundreds, officials and newspapers said Thursday.
   Two policemen also were reported injured in the clash Wednesday
as up to 5,000 workers sat at the exit gate of the plant 18 miles
south of the capital Cairo, the reports said.
   The government-owned newspaper Al-Akhbar said 81 workers
probably would be charged with resisting arrest, blocking
production and destruction of public property at the sprawling
plant, which employs more than 24,000 people. It said 596 other
workers were being questioned.
   The daily Al-Ahram newspaper, in its early Friday edition, said
only 497 workers had been detained. It said prosecutors ordered 82
workers jailed for 15 days while 415 others had been questioned and
released.
   Due to a Moslem holiday, security officials were unavailable for
comment on the clash or the strike, which was called to press
demands for higher wages and better working conditions.
   But Diaa Tantawi, board chairman of the Iron and Steel Complex
at Helwan, said the strike ``was not a question of wages or
incentive payments.''
   He said about 60 employees blocked the exit preventing about
3,000 workers from leaving at the end of Wednesday's morning shift.
   ``They used iron bars to stop the workers from leaving,''
Tantawi said.
   ``There definitely were political elements involved'' in the
strike, he said. He refused to characterize their motives except to
rule out Moslem extremist fundamentalism, often at the center of
unrest in Egypt.
   The board chairman estimated the loss of a day's work cost the
company $800,000 and that property damage was about $5,800.
   Work resumed at about half capacity Thursday as investigators
toured the site to assess damage. There was no sign of unrest or of
extra security at the grounds, but 10 vans filled with riot-police
were at a police station about half a mile away.
   The Helwan complex employs 24,600 workers, Tantawi said. It was
a showpiece of Soviet aid to Egypt during the time of the late
socialist President Gamal Abdel Nasser, who led the coup that ended
the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
   The two alleged strike leaders, who escaped, were board members
elected under a Nasser-era law that sets aside half the seats on
the board of a public company for workers.
   Previous strikes and demonstrations at other state-run
industries allegedly involved members of leftist political parties
and communists.
   Strikes and demonstrations are banned under an emergency law in
force since Oct. 7, 1981, a day after Moslem extremists
assassinated Anwar Sadat, Nasser's successor.
</TEXT>
