<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2015EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-SDI     08-03 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-SDI,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Says Laboratory Test Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force said Thursday it successfully
completed a laboratory test for part of the Star Wars system
designed to destroy enemy missiles by colliding with them.
   The test, the fourth in a series, was conducted at the Air
Force's Astronautics Laboratory at Edwards Air Force Base on
Tuesday.
   The Star Wars system, formally known as the Strategic Defense
Initiative, would make use of space-based interceptors to destroy
hostile missiles. Orbiting interceptors would be launched at
extremely high speeds and destroy targeted missiles by the force of
impact.
   Tuesday's test involved technologies needed to locate enemy
missiles and guide interceptors to destroy them.
   The interceptor vehicle remained in a laboratory while it used
sensors to target a missile on the test range, said a statement
issued at the Pentagon.
   The intercepter vehicle was able to detect and track the
missile's plume and then distinguish between the plume and the hard
body of the missile, the statement said.
   ``This ability is essential if the SBI (space-based interceptor)
is to function effectively in a ballistic missile defense system,''
the statement said.
</TEXT>
