<DOCNO> AP890803-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-RockCircus     08-03 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rock Circus,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animated Theater Presents Music Greats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Lee Lewis' piano belched great balls of
smoke, David Bowie floated above the moon singing ``Space Oddity,''
and Madonna sang ``Like a Virgin'' while reclining on a divan next
to a cheetah with green flashing eyes.
   They are all part of Rock Circus, a new museum that tells the
story of rock and pop from Buddy Holly to Bruce Springsteen using
wax models, animated electronic figures and stereo headsets.
   ``It's a theater show where we bring the greats of rock and pop,
even the dead ones, to life,'' said general manager Martin King at
a preview Thursday. The museum at the London Pavilion, in
Piccadilly Circus, opens Monday.
   Fifty of the world's top rock and pop stars singing some of the
best-known songs from the mid-1950s onward were reproduced with the
help of sculptors and other artists at the famed Madame Tussaud's
waxwork studios in west London.
   The recorded sounds are converted through a modulator into
infrared signals which tune into the headsets of visitors making
their way from one exhibit to the next.
   The highlight is a 20-minute theater of ``animatronic'' robots
viewed from a revolving auditorium. The lifelike figures mimic the
stage antics of such stars as Springsteen belting out ``Born in the
USA,'' Bob Dylan singing ``The Times They Are A-Changin','' and
Elvis Presley, complete with curling lip, crooning ``Love Me
Tender.''
   A video of a spaceship blasting off for space leads into an
appearance by Bowie's computer-programmed double, dressed in an
astronaut suit and floating in a most peculiar way while singing,
``This is Major Tom to Ground Control ...''
   Janis Joplin narrates the 1960s rock 'n' roll culture from a
graffiti-strewn park bench, then stands up shakily to sing her hit
single, ``Me and Bobby McGee.'' Joplin died of a drug overdose in
San Francisco in 1970.
   The Beatles open and close the set with a rendition of ``Sgt.
Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band,'' dressed in replicas of the
costumes on the cover of the 1967 album of the same name.
   There's a wax model of Buddy Holly singing ``Peggy Sue'' in a
radio studio in 1958 and being interviewed by disc jockey Alan
Freed about the dangers of flying to dozens of concerts across the
United States. Holly was killed Feb. 3, 1959, in a plane crash near
Mason City, Iowa.
   Jerry Lee Lewis gets his piano smoking with ``Whole Lotta
Shakin' Goin' On'' alongside Chuck Berry's rock classic ``Johnny B
Goode.''
   Others include Mick Jagger and Keith Richards (``I Can't Get No
Satisfaction''), Marvin Gaye (``I Heard It Through the
Grapevine''), and Simon and Garfunkel (``Sounds of Silence'').
</TEXT>
