<FIRST>u i AM-PLO-Tunisia     08-03 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Tunisia,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Says PLO Was Prepared to Accept Original Election Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat said Thursday that although
the PLO disliked Israel's plan for elections in the occupied lands,
it would have accepted it if the plan had been a step toward
Palestinian self-determination.
   The PLO chief added that the plan was merely aimed at
``perpetuating the Israeli occupation of the occupied territories''
and has now collapsed in failure.
   Arafat made the comments in an opening address to the fifth
general congress of the Fatah movement, the main component of the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The congress has drawn about 1,050 delegates from throughout the
Arab world, and spokesman Abdul Abdel-Rahman said that high on the
agenda would be the hostage crisis in Lebanon.
   The Fatah leadership on Tuesday condemned the reported killing
of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, but blamed Israel.
Israeli commandos on July 28 abducted Lebanese Shiite leader Sheik
Abdul Karim Obeid from his home in southern Lebanon.
   Arafat did not mention the hostage crisis in his address.
   The PLO has rejected an offer by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir to hold elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
and talks with elected Palestinian representatives on interim
self-rule for the 1.7 million Arabs living there. It has said no
elections are possible under occupation, and has demanded at least
a partial Israeli withdrawal.
   Shamir is sharply opposed to both notions.
   Speaking to frequent applause, Arafat said ``the PLO would have
accepted this plan if it had constituted a stage in the realization
of the rights of the Palestinian people to self-determination and
freedom.''
   ``I take this opportunity to ask the American government how
long it intends to continue ignoring the right of the Palestinian
people to self-determination, and how many wars we will still have
to fight to emerge from the vicious circle of blood and
suffering,'' he said.
   ``The intefadeh (uprising) will not stop until the conclusion of
a peace treaty and the realization of the Palestinian people's
inalienable right to return to self-determination and to the
establishment of a Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its
capital.''
   The congress went into closed session immediately after Arafat
spoke and was due to elect half the members of a new 21-member
central committee. Three of the present members have been
assassinated and two others have joined the hard-line dissidents.
   Twice during the opening session, the delegates observed a
moment's silence in memory of Arafat's deputy, Khalil Al Wazir _
better known as Abu Jihad _ and other martyrs. Abu Jihad was killed
in Tunis in an Israeli commando raid last year.
   Abu Jihad's widow, Intissar Al Wazir, was given a standing
ovation on entering the congress hall and is virtually certain to
be elected to the central committee.
   Tunisian President Zine Abidine Ben Ali also spoke to the
opening session, claiming that the summit of the world's seven main
industrial countries, held in Paris during the bicentennial
celebrations of the French revolution, had endorsed the PLO demand
for an international conference on the Middle East.
   ``The acceptance, by the seven, of such a conference shows how
Israel's isolation on the international scene has grown while the
just Palestinian cause has made new achievements even inside
Israel,'' Ben Ali said.
</TEXT>
