<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     08-03 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syriand and Christians Shell Residential Areas, Kill 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sleepy residents raced to bomb shelters
Thursday as Syrian and Christian gunners unleashed a barrage of
shellfire on residential districts of the ravaged city, killing
three people and wounding six.
   By police count, 514 people have been killed and 2,176 wounded
in the 20-week-old confrontation between Gen. Michel Aoun's
predominantly Christian Lebanese army troops and Syrian soldiers.
   The fighting has driven 1.3 million of the capital's 1.5 million
residents from the city.
   Shell explosions and ambulance sirens echoed before the barrages
ebbed into sporadic exchanges of gunfire across the dividing Green
Line.
   The few remaining civilians in this virtual ghost city emerged
from underground shelters early in the day to inspect their
apartments.
   Thousands of cars flooded the highway south of Beirut, which is
the only road connecting the city's western Moslem sector with the
rest of the country.
   ``Most of those who have fled Beirut returned for a short visit
early in the day to check on their apartments and businesses after
a night of shelling,'' said a police spokesman who cannot be named
by regulation.
   He said it could not be determined who started the duels that
erupted around 1 a.m. with 155mm U.S.-made howitzers and 130mm
Soviet-designed artillery.
   Both sides targeted residential districts as well as enemy
batteries, at times blasting the city with eight shells a minute,
he said.
   Several shells scored direct hits on apartment buildings,
shattering walls and glass and hurling pieces of gutted furniture
into deserted streets.
   The renewed heavy shelling came two days after an Arab League
committee announced that a two-month diplomatic effort to negotiate
a lasting cease-fire in Lebanon has failed because of differences
with Syria.
   Syria is the main power-broker in Lebanon and has 40,000 troops
in Moslem areas of the country under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, and other Christian leaders accuse
the Syrians of betraying their mandate by siding with the Moslems.
   Christian leaders have welcomed Tuesday's statement by the
foreign ministers of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria because it
explicitly accuses Syria of blocking peace efforts.
   King Hassan II of Morocco, King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and
Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid were asked at an Arab summit
May 26 to find a peace settlement by November. But their foreign
ministers shuttled in vain between Beirut and Damascus.
   Iraq, Syria's main Arab enemy, called Wednesday for an emergency
Arab summit to try and end the strife that has killed more than
150,000 people since Lebanon's civil war began in April 1975.
   Iraq supports the Christians in Lebanon and has been arming
Aoun's 20,000-strong force.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said Wednesday the Bush administration is ``disappointed that the
Arab League has not received the necessary cooperation from all
parties to the conflict, both the Lebanese and Syrians, to end
immediate fighting, lift blockades and address the underlying
political issues.''
   ``We urge the Arab League not to lay down its burden, despite
the enormous difficulties it has encountered,'' she added.
   The violence broke out after Aoun blockaded illegal ports run by
Syrian-backed militias.
   Syrian and allied Moslem forces retaliated by shelling and
laying siege to the enclave that usually is home to 1 million
Christians.
</TEXT>
