<SECOND>AM-Congress-Soviet Trip,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Members to Tour Soviet Military Facilities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee and 13 other congressmen will travel to the Soviet Union
Saturday for a first-hand look at military facilities and for
meetings with Kremlin officials.
   ``Much has been said about restructuring the Soviet military for
defensive purposes but we'd like to see those changes, not merely
hear about them,'' said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the
Armed Services Committee.
   The group plans to visit army units in the Soviet Union and East
Germany, the Soviet General Staff Academy, the Baikonur space
launch facility and a location where intermediate-range nuclear
weapons are destroyed.
   The delegation also will meet with officials in Moscow and
members of the Committee for Defense and State Security, which is a
panel of the Supreme Soviet recently created to deal with military
matters.
   The group leaves Washington on Saturday and returns Aug. 18. The
exact itinerary has not been set.
   The delegation includes members of the Armed Services panel. In
addition to Aspin, they are: Reps. William Dickinson of Alabama,
ranking Republican on the committee; Earl Hutto, D-Fla.; Thomas M.
Foglietta, D-Pa.; Frank McCloskey, D-Ind.; George Darden, D-Ga.;
Joseph E. Brennan, D-Maine; James H. Bilbray, D-Nev.; Bob Stump,
R-Ariz.; Larry J. Hopkins, R-Ky.; John R. Kasich, R-Ohio; Herbert
H. Bateman, R-Va.; Arthur Ravenel Jr., R-S.C.; and Jim McCrery,
R-La.
