<FIRST>r w AM-ProductivityRevisions     08-03 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Productivity Revisions,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recalculation Raises Estimate of Productivity Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's low productivity rate, which has
worried economists for years, is not as bad as originally believed,
the Labor Department said Thursday.
   The department said that productivity has increased at an
average annual rate of 1.8 percent over the last three years, up
from an original estimate of an average increase of 1.4 percent per
year.
   The 1.4 percent figure, which reflected sub-par productivity
rates in 1987 and 1988, had analysts concerned about the country's
economic outlook. Rising living standards hinge on the ability to
keep productivity increasing at a healthy rate.
   Economists had also questioned the Bush administration's
economic outlook, which was based on a projection that productivity
would grow in the years ahead at a 1.8 percent rate.
   Michael Boskin, the president's chief economic adviser, took
note of the Labor Department revisions in a statement released by
his office.
   ``We had been anticipating some upward revision in the
productivity estimates and were quite pleased that nonfarm
productivity growth for 1986-88 was revised to a rate almost
exactly in line with our current thinking about the economy's
long-run growth potential,'' he said.
   The revised figures showed that nonfarm productivity increased
by 2.1 percent in 1988, compared to a previous estimate of 1.5
percent. For 1987, the increase was put at 1.1 percent, up from a
previous estimate of 0.8 percent. Productivity growth in 1986 was
unchanged at 2 percent.
   Some private economists, however, remained sceptical about the
new figures.
   Michael Evans, head of a Washington forecasting firm, said he
believed that the government was miscounting total economic output
as covered by the gross national product. He said this had the
effect of inflating productivity, which is defined as total output
divided by the number of hours worked.
   ``I think the Commerce Department has committed a serious error
with their measurment of GNP,'' Evans said. ``They have
artificially raised real growth and this makes productivity look
better than it is.''
</TEXT>
