<FIRST>r w AM-Nuclear-Waste     08-03 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear-Waste,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says NRC Must Tighten Controls Over Shutdown of Sites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission must tighten
its controls over the shutdown of nuclear sites to assure they are
properly decontaminated of radioactive wastes, a congressional
study concluded Thursday.
   The report by the General Accounting Office, an arm of Congress,
said the NRC in the past has approved the decommissioning of some
nuclear facilities without adequate attention being paid to a
thorough decontamination.
   In two of eight cases reviewed by the GAO, investigators found
that sites were allowed to be closed and the land opened for
unrestricted use while there was still substantial radioactive
contamination in the area.
   Each of the eight sites examined were locations of former
nuclear fuel processing facilities.
   At one site contamination was found to be as much as 320 times
greater than allowed by NRC guidelines, while at another site it
was as much as four times greater, although the government approved
the facilities' transfer to general use.
   The GAO found that in four of the eight cases, licensees kept
incomplete records on where contaminated wastes were buried on a
site, making it impossible to determine later where wastes had been
buried. At one location, radioactive materials were discovered 10
years after the NRC decommissioned the site and opened it for
unrestricted use.
   There has been no major nuclear power plant decommissioned in
this country, but the decommissioning process has concluded or is
under way at seven smaller plants, scores of research or military
reactors as well as fuel processing plants.
   The GAO findings were released at a hearing of the House
Government Operations subcommittee on the environment where NRC
Chairman Kenneth M. Carr acknowledged past shortcomings in the
agency's decommissioning program.
   ``The GAO conclusions ... are in line with our own conclusions
and their report has highlighted actions we believe to be
necessary,'' said Carr. He said many of the closings approved by
the NRC occurred years ago and ``decommissioning procedures that
were once considered appropriate may no longer be so today.''
</TEXT>
