<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Nash     08-03 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Nash,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former AP Paris Photo Editor Dead at 69</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Nash, former photo and communications chief
in Paris for The Associated Press, died Thursday of cancer. He was
69.
   Nash, former assistant chief of bureau, photo editor and chief
of communications, retired in 1985 after 44 years with AP, one of
the longest-serving members of its foreign service.
   He restored AP newsphoto services in France after World War II
ann when photographers used bulky box-like Speed
Graphic cameras and ended as the era of electronic darkrooms and
computerized photo editing terminals was beginning.
   During World War II, Nash used a Speed Graphic to make pictures
of German V-1 rockets falling on London that appeared on front
pages around the world.
   When Nash retired, he was awarded the City of Paris Vermeil
Medal for distinguished accomplishment in one's profession.
   Nash also was decorated by Tunisian President Habib Bourguiba
for widely published photographs he took in 1952 showing unrest in
the French colony, which became independent four years later.
   ``Mike was a rare bird in the early days of the AP picture
service in Europe,'' said Harold G. Buell, assistant general
manager for NewsPhotos. ``He could shoot pictures, he could handle
the desk and he soon came to provide needed insights into
networking and development of AP's complicated picture system.''
   ``Nash drove no one harder than himself in doing a first-class
job in every respect,'' said Paris AP Bureau Chief Harry Dunphy.
``He trained a generation of photographers and editors.''
   Nash was born Aug. 6, 1919, in London, where he joined the AP in
1942 as a photo editor. A few months later he switched to
photographer.
   After the 1944 liberation of Paris from German occupation, the
25-year-old Nash was sent to rebuild the AP photo service. On June
1, 1945, the AP resumed delivery of news photos to Paris newspapers.
   A year later, Nash returned to active service as a photographer
and for the next six years worked in Europe, the Middle East and
Africa.
   In 1952, Nash returned to the photo editor's job in Paris, a
position he held for 34 years. He established AP's wirephoto
network in 1956.
   Nash developed and trained photographers and editors who covered
wars and rebellions in Indochina, North Africa, the Congo, Vietnam,
the Middle East and Iran.
   In 1978, Nash took on additional duties as chief of
communications in Paris.
   Nash is survived by his wife, Elsie, and their sons Max, AP's
photo editor in Tel Aviv, and Timothy, an architect in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2003EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-`Yesterday Today'Ratings   08-03 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-`Yesterday, Today' Ratings,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>New News Show Gets Highest Share for News Special in 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The critics may have hated it, but NBC's new
news program, ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow,'' had the highest
A.C. Nielsen rating for an NBC news special in 10 years.
   The first of three summer specials launching a ``news
anthology'' trounced the reruns on CBS and ABC on Wednesday
evening. ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'' had a rating of 12.0 and
a 23 share to an 8.2 and 16 for ABC's `ezing in
Idaho's Boise and Payette National Forests. But the forecast was
for rising temperatures through the weekend.
   ``Obviously we would very happy if the weather stayed the
same,'' said fire center spokesman Arnold Hartigan. ``Higher
temperatures and low humidity are going to complicate matters for
firefighters.''
   In Idaho, where the fires have blackened 98,000 acres,
firefighters and National Guardsmen struggled to hack containment
lines around fires in the western and central parts of the state.
National Guardsmen helped firefighters cut lines around the fires
and protect scattered buildings in the Boise and Payette national
forests.
   In Oregon, Army infantry troops joined the fight Thursday
against fires that have burned 85,000 acres of forest east of the
Cascades.
   About 650 soldiers from Fort Lewis, Wash., joined 330
firefighters on the lines around a 13,300-acre fire in the Monument
Rock Wilderness southwest of Baker, Ore. Because machinery is
barred from about 70 miles southwest of Baker and three miles
from a 13,300-acre fire in the Monument Rock Wilderness. Because
machinery is barred from wilderness areas, the soldiers will be
assigned to the tedious task of cutting fire lines with hand tools.
   One more day of ``on-the-job'' training was planned Friday along
relatively safe fire lines already established at the fire, said
U.S. Forest Service spokesman Steve Sorseth.
   A 23,300-acre fire on the boundary of the Eagle Cap Wildneress
area northwest of Baker destroyed a small snowmobile hut, but
spared the Lick Creek Guard Station, which is on the National
Register of Historic Places, said Bruce McMillan, Wallowa-Whitman
National Forest spokesman.
   In California, where 35,000 acres have been charred, the weather
was no help to crews fighting a fire Thursday in the Cleveland
National Forest 90 miles southeast of Los Angeles.
   The 10,300-acre blaze was two miles from the Eagle Crag nature
sanctuary, home to spotted owls and bald eagles, and was within 5
miles of the Palomar Observatory, said Forest Service spokeswoman
Rosalinda Ewen.
   The observatory, which houses a museum, gallery and telescope,
sits atop a hill and is surrounded by three smaller dwellings, and
by dry chaparral brush.
   The fire had been headed toward the observatory, but then turned
away late Thursday morning, and didn't pose an immediate threat,
said Forest Service spokesman Bill Bruggema.
   The blaze was 60 percent contained, but if it reached the nature
sanctuary, the battle would be tougher because of rough terrain and
a ban on using equipment.
   The Eagle Crag area contains giant stands of native Douglas firs
and manzanita trees believed to be the oldest in the Southwest.
   One firefighter suffered a broken collarbone Wednesday battling
the blaze that was started by gunfire.
   In Montana, fire engines stood by to protect two mountain cabins
as a lightning-sparked fire in dead timber grew quickly to 500
acres on the Crow Indian Reservation southeast of Billings. An
800-acre grass and timber fire in the Custer National Forest in the
state's southeastern corner was contained.
   The fire season is worsening throughout the West, Allan West, a
Forest Service deputy chief, said at a Washington, D.C., news
conference Thursday. Fire conditions are extreme to severe in 14
states.
   ``Long-range weather forecasts indicate continuing severe fire
conditions, leaving this fire season with the potential to be as
severe as last year's,'' he said. ``We see no relief through the
month of October in precipitation and temperature.''
   So far this year, more than 39,400 fires have been reported
burning 1.38 million acres. That compares with almost 61,200 fires
covering 2.37 million acres through the same time period last year.
