<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-FiresOutlook     08-03 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Outlook,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service Says Current Fire Season Could Be As Bad As '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the long-range weather forecast calling
for little relief through October, U.S. Forest Service officials
said Thursday the current forest fire season in the West could be
as bad as 1988.
   Extreme to severe fire conditions already exist in most Western
states and the situation is expected to worsen, Allan West, a
Forest Service deputy chief, said at a new conference.
   West said that ``no improvement is expected in the foreseeable
future. Long-range weather forecasts indicate continuing severe
fire conditions, leaving this fire season with the potential to be
as severe as last year's.''
   Last year was the worst fire season since 1910 with major fires
burning through roughly one-third of Yellowstone National Park and
more than 5 million acres scorched nationwide.
   More than 39,400 fires have been reported burning 1.38 million
acres so far this year. That compares with almost 61,200 fires
covering 2.37 million acres through the same time period last year.
   West said that even though the pace of the 1988 fire season was
almost double this year's at the beginning of August, the Forest
Service concerns were prompted by the long-range weather forescasts.
   ``We see no relief through the month of October in precipitation
and temperature,'' he said.
   Since Sunday alone, West said 66 major wildfires in Idaho,
Oregon, California, Washington state and Montana have swept over
220,000 acres destroying about 60 structures and forcing the
evacuation of hundreds of people.
   The worst fires are burning in southern and central Idaho and
eastern Oregon.
   West said that in one recent 24-hour period 1,000
lightning-caused fires were reported in the Boise National Forest.
   West said that large fires such as those that burned through
Yellowstone National Park in 1988 were always a possibility. He
singled out an area including Glacier National Park in northwestern
Montana with ``overmature'' lodgepole pine damaged by insects where
major fires could erupt.
   Extreme fire conditions exist in most of California and Nevada,
large portions of Wyoming and North Dakota, southern Idaho, eastern
Oregon and the Cascade range in both Oregon and Washington state.
   Severe fire conditions exist in Montana, South Dakota, western
Minnesota, central and northern Idaho and throughout the remaining
sections of Washington and Oregon.
   Despite scattered showers and cooler temperatures in some parts
of the West over the past several days, West said the moderation in
weather will do little to reverse the dry conditions.
</TEXT>
