<FIRST>r w AM-DrugPrevention     08-03 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Prevention,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro Athletes Press Congress for Drug Prevention Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two professional athletes, including one who
said he ``went from stardom to depression and near destruction''
because of drug abuse, urged Congress on Thursday to expand drug
prevention programs.
   ``It is important we start at an early age,'' said Delvin
Williams, who played football for the San Francisco 49ers and the
Miami Dolphins. Williams said he began experimenting with marijuana
in grade school.
   Williams and John Lucas, a veteran guard in the National
Basketball Association, told the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee that drug education programs should stretch from
kindergarten through high school.
   Drugs ``took my dreams and eventually it took my soul,'' Lucas
told the senators. ``I went from stardom to depression and near
destruction. I know firsthand what it means to hit bottom.''
   Lucas described how his daughter at age 6 tried to sniff ashes
through a straw, imitating how her father snorted cocaine.
   ``There are many examples that would frighten most of you, but
it's happening every day,'' he said.
   ``It starts after the game when you lose. It starts after the
game when you win,'' said Williams. ``You think you can handle it,''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the committee, said
the type of prevention programs aimed at youth, which both Lucas
and Williams now participate in, are a critical part of fighting
drugs.
   But Kennedy said prevention, as well as treatment programs, are
badly underfunded, with about three-fourths of the federal drug
money going to law enforcement and interdiction.
   ``It is a political fact of life that law enforcement and
interdiction have an easier time obtaining funds. But we will never
purge our society of drug addiction with a strategy that
shortchanges prevention and treatment,'' Kennedy said. ``The war on
drugs must be waged on all fronts, and that means prevention and
treatment, too.''
   The senator said the Department of Health and Human Services is
getting twice as many approved applications for local prevention
programs as it can fund. The government's commitment to
school-based anti-drug education programs through the Education
Department equals $1 a month per student, he said.
   Keema McAdoo, who is entering her senior year of high school in
the Dorchester section of Boston, has been a peer counselor in
local anti-drug programs for the past 2{ years. In that time, she
said, she has been to 16 funerals of teen-agers who were either
killed by drugs or were drug addicts and committed suicide.
   ``It is time for the schools, churches and businesses to invest
now instead of having to invest later,'' she said.
   On the treatment side, Kennedy said the nation has the capacity
to treat fewer than one of every six drug addicts seeking help.
   New Jersey Public Health Commissioner Molly Coye said there are
an estimated 50,000 intravenous drug users and 150,000 cocaine
users in her state, but treatment funds are available for only
6,000 addicts. There are 3,000 on a waiting list, and she estimated
that the majority of addicts would participate in drug treatment
programs.
   ``The evidence is overwhelming that drug users want treatment,''
Ms. Coye said. ``We simply don't have the resources.''
</TEXT>
