<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--PneumococcalInfections     08-03 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Pneumococcal Infections,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pneumococcal Vaccine, Ignored By Public, Should Be Pushed, CDC Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Disease Spreading, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than 10 percent of people at high risk for a
type of infection that can cause pneumonia, meningitis and even
death have ever gotten the vaccine for it, and health officials
Thursday urged doctors to do better.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said 48 million
Americans are at high risk of pneumococcal infections, but a 1985
study found that not one in 10 of them have ever received the
vaccine.
   The vaccine, a one-time-only shot, is recommended for adults 65
and over and for adults with chronic illnesses such as heart and
lung disease, kidney failure, cirrhosis and suppressed immune
systems.
   Pneumococcal infections cause 150,000 to 570,000 cases of
pneumonia and contribute to an estimated 40,000 deaths annually,
the CDC said.
   ``Assuming an overall vaccine efficacy of 60 percent ... an
estimated 12,000 deaths related to pneumococcal disease might be
prevented annually'' if only 60 percent of high-risk people were
vaccinated, the CDC said in its weekly report.
   The CDC praised a two-year California State Department of Health
Services program promoting the use of pneumococcal vaccines. Local
health departments received more than 60,000 doses, and were
encouraged to provide the vaccine during scheduled autumn
flu-vaccine clinics or other health department clinics.
   From July 1986 through July 1987, 56 participating health
departments gave more than 24,000 vaccinations. The following year,
59 participating departments administered more than 44,000
vaccinations.
   The CDC urged health-care providers to give their patients
pneumococcal vaccine along with their other vaccinations whenever
appropriate.
</TEXT>
