<FIRST>u w AM-QuayleResidence     08-03 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle Residence,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Approves Money to Renovate Vice Presidential Residence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee voted Thursday to spend
$200,000 for renovations to Vice President Dan Quayle's official
residence and $125,000 to restore furniture in the living quarters
of the White House.
   The expenditures were approved by voice vote as the Senate
Appropriations Committee sent to the full chamber its version of
the fiscal 1990 spending bill for the Treasury, Postal Service and
a variety of other government agencies.
   The $18 billion spending bill also contains a provision to
prevent the Internal Revenue Service from enforcing Section 89 of
the tax code. Designed to encourage companies to provide health
plans to low-paid employees, the section has been attacked by
businesses that contend compliance is too difficult and costly.
   The money for the vice president's residence, an 1894 Victorian
mansion on the grounds of a U.S. Navy compound in the Embassy Row
section of Washington, would be spent on constructing four new
bedrooms, an office for Mrs. Quayle, three bathrooms and a laundry
room.
   After last year's election, the Quayles said renovations were
needed to accommodate their family with three school-age children.
They said repeatedly they would pay for renovations with private
donations.
   Denise Balzano, Marilyn Quayle's chief of staff, said this week
that $200,000 has been raised and that the money will be used to
buy furniture and other items.
   The House has already approved the $200,000 for the Quayle
residence renovations, but the Senate added the money for the White
House furniture.
   According to the committee, that money would go toward
refurbishing furniture now in storage because it's worn out.
   The spending bill covers a wide range of routine government
programs and projects, including the Treasury and Customs Service,
the Executive Office of the President, and the Postal Service.
   The committee also included a provision in the bill designed to
close a loophole in postal rules. Some credit card issuers have
teamed up with charitable organizations in making their
solicitations and have thus benefitted from subsidized mail rates,
and the committee language would attempt to end subsidies in those
cases.
