<FIRST>u w AM-Higgins-Pathologists     08-03 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Higgins-Pathologists,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forensic Experts Say Victim May Already Have Been Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forensic experts who have examined the
videotape purporting to show the body of Lt. Col. William R.
Higgins believe it shows evidence ``inconsistent'' with a person
who has just been hanged, an administration official said Thursday.
   Other experts said in interviews that the body shown on the
videotape appears to be that of a man who had been dead for a
while, not someone who was killed on Monday as the kidnappers
claimed.
   A group calling itself the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth sent the 30-second videotape to a news organization in
Beirut, saying the American Marine was killed in retaliation for
Israel's kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric in Lebanon.
   The gruesome tape showed a crew-cut man, with a noose around his
neck, blindfolded, his ankles and arms bound. The tape had been
reproduced several times by the time it was given to experts in
Washington, and the quality was grainy and unfocused, officials say.
   ``No one can say for sure, but there are many things there
inconsistent with a man who has just been hanged,'' said one
official who spoke only on condition he not be named. He declined
to elaborate.
   Another official said experts who viewed the tape noted the
body's shoulders appeared rigid rather than slumped, as they would
probably have been on a man who died by hanging, and the heavy
clothing was inconsistent with Lebanon's summer heat.
   Pathologists will probably not know for sure whether the body is
that of Higgins, when he died, or how, unless the body can be
recovered. A U.N. envoy arrived in Beirut Thursday to search for
the body.
   Michael Baden, Director of Forensic Sciences for New York State
Police, said that despite the poor quality of the tape experts
should be able to study individual frames and determine whether it
is Higgins or not.
   For instance, he said, there is a clear shot of the left ear
lobe which is a distinctive identification mark for pathologists.
   Baden said the body in the videotape does not look bloated,
suggesting either it was kept refrigerated or the tape was shot
within 12 hours of death.
   U.S. authorities have been hampered by the lack of reliable
intelligence information about Higgins and the other eight American
hostages believed held in Lebanon. Some reports have said the U.N.
peacekeeper was killed soon after he was kidnapped in south Lebanon
in February 1988, or in retaliation for the U.S. downing of an
Iranian jetliner last December.
   Werner Spitz, a professor of forensic medicine at Wayne State
University in Michigan, said that as soon as he saw the tape on
television, ``I said to myself, `This body is not fresh.'''
   Spitz, formerly the Detroit medical examiner, said the skin
appeared dry and discolored. ``That would be consistent with a body
that has been dead a while and has undergone mummification,
especially in a hot climate,'' he said.
   Other experts have noted the videotape indicates the man's
tongue was not hanging out, the eyes were not bulging, and the face
and neck did not appear to have turned dark _ all characteristics
of death by hanging. Baden suggested this indicates the man was
dead before being placed on the gallows.
   But Spitz and Baden both said the absence of those conditions
does not prove conclusively the victim was not hanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
