<FIRST>r a AM-Megamuseum 1stLd-Writethru a0706 08-03 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Megamuseum, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Money Problems, State Still Considers $72 Million Art Museum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `The $72...', to CORRECT spelling of convert,
sted covert, and SUBS last graf to delete extraneous word `I'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heating bill is unpaid, there's
controversy over those chosen to help run the joint, and
consultants may be spending money that doesn't exist.
   Worst, the state probably doesn't have its share of the
estimated $72 million needed to convert 750,000 square feet of
abandoned factory into the world's largest contemporary art museum.
The state's deepening money troubles have left it without cash to
pay for schools, police and other services.
   Still, boosters of the planned Massachusetts Museum of
Contemporary Art are pushing ahead.
   Pending the results of a $1.25 million feasibility study, Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis, one of the project's earliest backers, remains
committed to it, press aide Susan Kaplan said Thursday.
   ``It is going to be a big boost for northern Berkshire County,''
she said.
   Dukakis has maintained that the town needs the museum and its
estimated 600 jobs to revive its economy. North Adams' unemployment
rate is just 4 percent, but it has little industry and most people
have to seek work in other towns.
   Supporters claim the museum could attract 150,000 visitors
annually to the remote mill town of 18,000, located in the state's
northwestern corner more than a three-hour drive from art-lovers in
Boston and four hours from New York.
   The unlikely project was the brainchild of Thomas Krens, former
director of the Williams College Art Museum, who shortly after
launching the project was named director of the Guggenheim Museum
in New York.
   Ties between the private museum and an international committee
headed by Krens to review the feasibility study have come under
question. Although they have denied any conflict of interest,
committee member Carmen Gimenez, former director of national
exhibitions for the Ministry of Culture of Spain, was recently
hired by Krens as a curator of 20th century art at the Guggenheim.
   The $72 million would go to convert the dingy 28-building
manufacturing complex into at least 380,000 square feet of
exhibition space for environmental art works and other contemporary
sculptures too large for most museums.
   Among the works promised to the museum are abstract sculptures
more than 20 feet high in such non-traditional materials as neon
tubing and scrap metal.
   Count Giuseppe Panza, an Italian industrialist who has an
extensive collection of American art from the 1960s and 1970s, has
agreed to lend many works to the museum. The German Architecture
Museum in Frankfurt plans to send much of its collection of modern
architectural drawings and models.
   The $35 million state share of the cost would come from
borrowing spread over two to four years, Kaplan said. The remainder
is to come from private donations.
   But so far, only the state has come up with any cash and that's
fast disappearing. At the end of June, only about $170,000 was left
out of a $1.7 million state appropriation to hire staff of six and
pay for the $1.25 million feasibility study.
   The study, split among nearly 50 outside consultants charging up
to $300 an hour, was to have been completed last month. It is now
expected to be finished in September, according to Joseph C.
Thompson, executive planning director of the museum project.
   ``Six weeks is not that late,'' Thompson said. ``We are working
as quickly as possible, but we've been delayed by the number of
reports and the fairly astounding types of technical analysis and
engineering studies required.'' Topics that have to be studied
range from the heating and ventilating system to art installation
and transportation, he said.
   Thompson said the group has not begun private fund-raising,
although its quarterly financial report lists a net take of $13,000
from a $46,000 ball last winter, $15,000 in donations from local
supporters and a $100,000 loan due in January from the state
Industrial Finance Agency.
   ``It's all about timing,'' he said, maintaining the feasibility
studies include a blueprint for fund-raising.
   He was equally vague about what the museum is doing about an
overdue $175,000 heating bill. Berkshire Gas Co. spokesman
Christopher Farrell said that after carrying the unpaid heating
bill for the buildings through the winter, the utility cut off
service in March.
   Thompson said the state grant does not include operating
expenses. And he declined to say how the museum planned to pay the
bill or what it would do this winter.
   ``We didn't apply for grants for it. We will raise the money.
That's all the comment I will have about it,'' Thompson said.
</TEXT>
