<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-03 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Very Widely Scattered Thunderstorms; Much of Nation Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered across the
nation Thursday with mostly light rain, and much of the nation had
fair weather.
   The remains of Hurricane Chantal, centered over west-central
Missouri, produced showers and thunderstorms there and in eastern
Kansas.
   To the north, showers and thunderstorms developed in warm,
unstable air ahead of a cold front stretching from southeastern
South Dakota into northwestern Wisconsin.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms were widely scattered in the Tennessee
Valley, south-central Texas, and Florida.
   No site reported more than an inch of rain during the six hours
up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   In the Atlantic, Hurricane Dean veered away from the Virgin
Islands and Puerto Rico and wandered toward the west-northwest,
with hurricane watches posted for the Turks and Caicos islands of
the Bahama chain.
   A large upper-air high-pressure system centered over western
Kentucky carried warm and humid weather from the Gulf Coast to the
Great Lakes.
   Marquette, Mich., reached a record high of 88. In Florida,
Apalachicola hit a record 95.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 101 at Needles, Calif. Thursday's low
in the Lower 48 states was 30 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Friday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from sections of the middle and upper Mississippi Valley across the
Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes to the northern Atlantic Coast.
Showers and thunderstorms also were forecast from the eastern half
of the Gulf Coast region into Florida.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast;
in the 80s from inland sections of the Pacific Northwest across the
northern Rockies, the upper Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes
to northern New England; above 100 over the desert Southwest,
inland valleys of central and southern California, and near the Big
Bend of the Rio Grande in Texas; and in the 90s across much of the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
