<FIRST>r w AM-RadiationVictims     08-03 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radiation Victims,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Calls for Repeal of His Radiation Amendment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of a law that effectively denied a
day in court to victims of radiation exposure from government
testing on Thursday urged that the law be repealed.
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., told the Judiciary Committee's
Subcommittee on Courts and Administratve Practice his amendment to
the 1985 Defense Authorization bill was intended to help, not harm
veterans and civilian workers who had been exposed to radiation in
atomic weapons testing.
   ``However, what resulted was an unexpected dismissal of hundreds
of damage suits brought by those affected,'' said Warner.
   ``Let me repeat, that this was a completely unexpected and
inadvertent result,'' he said.
   Warner's bill allowed defense contractors to have the government
replace them as defendants in any suits brought by those who worked
or lived near nuclear testing sites.
   The amendment, called Section 1631, also placed all radiation
victim cases under the Federal Tort Claims Act, which granted the
government certain immunities based on national security and
defense concerns and denied exposure victims a trial by jury.
   Warner joined Nevada Democratic Sens. Harry Reid and Richard
Bryan in urging passage of the Radiation Victims Fair Treatment Act
to repeal the earlier legislation he sponsored.
   ``If this bill were to become law, the litigant would still have
to prove that the defendant was negligent,'' said Warner. ``But as
the law stands these veterans can't even have the opportunity to
have a trial before a jury of their peers.''
   Thomas R. Thomsen of AT&amp;T Technology Systems and James S. Kane
of the University of California's Office of Laboratory Affairs
urged the subcommittee not to repeal the law because, they said, it
rightfully made the government responsible for its weapons testing
program.
   They also argued the proposed repeal would flood the nation's
court system with new cases that could take years to resolve.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
