<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     08-03 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Plans to Ease Martial Law, Open Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling military council will reopen
some schools closed after last year's pro-democracy protests and
plans gradually to relax martial law, state media reported Thursday.
   Officials closed all schools in June 1988, during student-led
mass demonstrations against authoritarian rule.
   Radio Rangoon said Thursday junior high schools will reopen Aug.
14 and teacher training colleges on Aug. 21.
   Primary schools reopened on June 19.
   The Working People's Daily said high schools and universities
will reopen soon ``since the general law and order situation in the
country has improved considerably.''
   It quoted a government directive issued Wednesday to military
commanders and government officials in various states.
   The directive also told regional military commanders to take
``severe action'' against people who violate martial law.
   Burma has been under martial law since Sept. 18, when army
commander Gen. Saw Maung's troops crushed the pro-democracy
movement.
   On July 18, authorities increased the power of regional military
commanders and empowered military tribunuals to sentence martial
law violators to death.
   The directive says commanders ``are required to strive to
restore the normal situation.''
   ``With the progress in the enforcement of the rule of law,
martial law will be lifted step by step.''
   It repeats government pledges to hold free and fair elections
next year, the state newspaper said Thursday.
   Doubts about this pledge increased after opposition party
leaders Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo were arrested on July 20 and
confined to their homes under military guard.
   Rangoon-based Western diplomats reached by telephone from
Bangkok said Ms. Suu Kyi, 44, has taken only water since the first
day of detention. The government denies she is on a hunger strike
and no reports have emerged about her condition.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said she
wants a transfer to Insein Jail to be with other detained political
activists.
   Diplomats reported a wave of arrests of opposition party members
in the past two weeks.
   It coincides with a government amnesty for common criminals.
Officials said Thursday that 17,558 have been freed since the
amnesty was announced July 20.
   The amnesty covers offenses committed before the Sept. 18
military takeover and does not apply to martial law violations.
</TEXT>
