<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Government     08-03 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Government,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Non-Party Official Chosen for Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Soviet on Thursday confirmed the first
Cabinet member who is not a member of the Communist Party, a
biologist who will grapple with the country's ecological problems.
   The national legislature also approved for a Cabinet post a
regional Communist Party chief who last year shocked a party
conference by demanding that longtime Kremlin leaders such as
Andrei A. Gromyko retire.
   The Tass news agency said Nikolai Vorontsov, a 55-year-old
professor and biologist, was confirmed as head of the State
Committee for Nature Conservation. He replaced Fyodor Morgun.
   It was not clear why Morgun was not nominated again for the post.
   The legislature also confirmed Vladimir I. Melnikov, 54, as
lumber minister, and Leonid Filimonov, a 54-year-old engineer, as
oil and gas minister, according to Tass.
   Nikolai Rusak, 55, was confirmed as head of the state Sports
Committee, and Viktor Gerashchenko, 52, was chosen to head the
state bank, the news agency said.
   Although the Communist Party and government are separate, in the
past it has been impossible for anyone to rise in the government
structure without solid party credentials.
   Vorontsov's selection indicated that Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov
and the legislature now are willing to look outside the
20-million-member party for government officials.
   Tass said Vorontsov told legislators he favors mandatory
ecological impact studies before the construction of new factories
and giving the needs of the local population priority over the
demands of national ministries.
   During the two-month legislative session, which ends Saturday,
the government announced it is quadrupling the environmental
protection budget for the next 15 years to $612 billion.
   Melnikov, the new lumber minister, promised the Supreme Soviet
he would pay particular attention to ecological problems, Tass said.
   Melnikov shocked last summer's party conference by stating
publicly that longtime Kremlin figures such as former President
Gromyko and Politburo member Mikhail S. Solomentsev should retire.
   Less than six months later, both were removed from the
Politburo. Gromyko died last month.
</TEXT>
