<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1750EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CongressionalMail     08-03 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressional Mail,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel OKs Bill to Cut Appropriation for Congressional Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee approved
legislation Thursday that would reduce the amount of money Congress
is expected to spend next year on mail.
   The nearly $2 billion fiscal 1990 spending bill for Congress
earmarks $80 million for lawmakers' postage, compared to $124.7
million in the bill the House approved earlier this week.
   Official congressional mail expenses in the current fiscal year,
which ends Oct. 1, are expected to be $53.9 million. However,
members of Congress often feel a greatly increased need to
communicate with their constituents in even-numbered, or election,
years.
   ``It provides plenty of money for what is needed to keep in
touch with our constituents,'' said Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.,
chairman of the appropriations subcommittee on the legislative
branch.
   ``We have to get after the mail monster and get it under control
or it is going to eat us out of house and home,'' said Reid, who is
not up for election next year.
   The Senate, which has 100 members, would allocate $32 million
for its mailings and $48 million for the House, which has 435
voting members.
   The Senate bill would set a variety of new rules for
congressional mass mailings, reducing from 6 to 2 per year those
that go to all ``postal patrons'' in a district. Lawmakers who
exceed individual mail allowances would have to make up the
difference from their individual allowances.
   The House voted to cut postal patron mailings from 6 to 4, but
left a loophole so members could still advertise their town
meetings.
   Congressional franking privileges are frequently the target of
political reformers, who claim they help incumbents stay in office
at public expense.
   The legislative spending bill is commonly an arena for
House-Senate battles.
   The Senate in its bill stripped out a House-passed provision to
take away from senators the private ``hideaway'' offices they keep
in the Capitol.
   The Senate also would establish an Office of Senate Health
Promotion _ which would run exercise classes and similar services
for senators and their staffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ImprisonedFetus     08-03 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Imprisoned Fetus,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Argues State is Illegally Jailing Inmate's Fetus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer has filed suit contending
the state is illegally imprisoning a female inmate's fetus, citing
Missouri's anti-abortion law that says life begins at conception.
   ``If life begins at conception, then fetuses are supposed to be
like anyone else _ they're a person and they have constitutional
rights,'' Michael Box said Thursday in a telephone interview from
Oak Grove.
   Along with declaring that life begins at conception, the
preamble to Missouri's anti-abortion law, key portions of which
were upheld last month by the U.S. Supreme Court, extends to the
unborn ``all the rights, privileges and immunities available to
other persons.''
   ``I'm not pro-choice or pro-life or any of that stuff. But I
think there's some problems with the law and courts are eventually
going to have to rule on it,'' he said.
   Box filed suit earlier this week in federal court in Jefferson
City on behalf of Lovetta Farrar's unborn child.
   The suit on behalf of the fetus contends it has been imprisoned
at the Chillicothe Correctional Center without having been charged
with a crime, allowed an attorney, convicted or sentenced.
   It is also being denied adequate diet, medical care and ``the
opportunity to develop into a healthy live born'' child because of
conditions at the prison, the suit said. All are violations of
constitutional rights, the suit said.
   Box filed a companion suit that contends the prison violated
Farrar's constitutional rights by failing to provide her with a
proper diet, medical care, exercise and a safe environment in which
to carry the fetus.
   Farrar's baby is due in November, according to the suit.
   Prison officials said Farrar's release date is June 1991. She
was serving a three-year sentence for various counts of forgery and
stealing when she was released in February to an honor center. When
she failed to return from a work release program in April, she was
returned to prison.
   Named as defendants in the fetus' suit are Gov. John Ashcroft,
Attorney General William Webster and five senior officials of the
state Department of Corrections and Human Resources. All but
Webster are named in Farrar's suit.
   Gail Hughes, deputy director of the Corrections Department, said
he did not know about the suits.
   The one on behalf of the fetus is ``particularly interesting,''
Hughes said. ``I don't know about that idea.''
   Regarding the challenge to the conditions at the prison in
Chillicothe, he said: ``I think we've had suits like them and won
them all.
   ``Early to bed, early to rise, three meals a day, no alcohol or
drugs is probably a conducive environment to pregnancy,'' he said.
Pregnant inmates ``haven't had any difficulties brought about by
any cause of their incarceration.''
</TEXT>
