<HEAD>Medical Examiner Says Bones In Bundy Search Are Those Of Deer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bones found in a search of an area where
serial killer Ted Bundy claimed to have buried a victim are those
of deer or coyotes, the state medical examiner says.
   Medical Examiner Todd Grey examined the bones Wednesday and
found they weren't human.
   They were found during a search last weekend in which dozens of
Sanpete County deputies scoured sites in a 60-mile area.
   The latest search and several others aimed at finding the
remains of Debi Kent, a 17-year-old from the town of Bountiful whom
Bundy said he kidnapped in 1974. Bones turned up in past searches
also were those of animals. Sanpete authorities said no more
searches are planned.
   Bundy confessed to killing Ms. Kent and another woman and
claimed responsibility for six other slayings in Utah shortly
before his execution in Florida in January for the murder of a
schoolgirl.
   Investigators have said Bundy was suspected in dozens of
killings in several states, including Utah, where he once attended
law school.
