<FIRST>u w AM-Hostage-Diplomacy     08-03 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage-Diplomacy,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomacy Preceded Decision To Spare Cicippio</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by Shiite Moslem leaders to spare
the life of American hostage Joseph Cicippio followed an intense
U.S. diplomatic effort to gain cooperation from many countries,
including some long-standing U.S. adversaries.
   In addition, private experts said the Revolutionary Justice
Organization, the pro-Iranian group holding Cicippio, also may have
reached their decision to suspend the death sentence after deciding
Cicippio was worth more alive than dead.
   For days, U.S. diplomats were in contact with countries which
had either access to or influence with Iran, the country whose lead
the Lebanese Shiites follow.
   Perhaps carried along by the international outcry that followed
the reported hanging on Monday of Lt. Col. William Higgins, both
Syria and the Soviet Union made diplomatic appeals on Cicippio's
behalf.
   But the apparent intervention by Iran's leadership, U.S.
officials said, may have been decisive. Iran's new president, Ali
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, expressed regret Tuesday over the
reported death of Higgins and condemned terrorist acts in general.
   A shift in Iran's suppoort for international terrorism could
eventually lead to steps toward an accommodation between the two
one-time allies, American officials have said.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Iran
had been the target of an intense U.S. diplomatic campaign that
included a variety of channels.
   ``At this time we have no reason to believe that Iran is not
dealing with this matter in a serious way,'' she said, speaking
less than two hours before the announcement of Cicippio's reprieve.
   But officials cautioned Cicippio and the remaining seven
American hostages still face danger. They noted the Revolutionary
Justice Organization statement did not drop its demand that Israel
free Shiek Abdul Karim Obeid, the Shiite cleric kidnapped last
Friday by Israeli commandos.
   The statement said acceptance of the demand ``should be
announced within days, otherwise the initiative will be considered
canceled.'' This implied the death sentence for Cicippio would be
reimposed.
   Still, announcement of the reprieve lowered the temperature here
considerably. A sense of anxiety had permeated the administration
since Monday when Higgins' execution was announced and was followed
quickly by the announcement that Cicippio would be next.
   The execution of Cicippio, officials said, almost certainly
would have triggered a response by President Bush, possibly
including military action. This, in turn, would have polarized
factions in the Middle East even more.
   Geoffrey Kemp, a National Security Council official in the
Reagan administration, attributed the repreive partly to the
realization by the Revolutionary Justice Organization that any
leverage they believe Ciccipio gives them would have died with his
execution.
   ``He's not worth anything dead,'' said Kemp. He suggested the
organization had to take seriously the views of Iranian officials
who want to renew relationships with the United States.
</TEXT>
