<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1802EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bolivia     08-03 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Future President's Career Goes From Seminary, Jail To Presidential
Palace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaime Paz Zamora, all but assured of
becoming Bolivia's next president, is a former seminary student who
began his political career opposing former dictator Hugo Banzer
Suarez, who jailed him in the early 1970's.
   Today, the erstwhile opponents have joined together to form a
new government.
   Paz Zamora, 50, is expected to be elected president by Congress
Friday or Saturday and sworn in as Bolivia's 77th president Sunday.
The former vice president came in third in the May 7 presidential
elections but received the support of Banzer Suarez, the
second-place winner, to gain enough congressional votes to be
elected president.
   Paz Zamora is the son of an army general and a mother from a
prominant aristocratic family. He is the nephew of President Victor
Paz Estenssoro.
   After completing his high school at a Jesuit school in his
hometown of Sucre, he attended a Roman Catholic seminary in
Argentina but quit before he was ordained a priest. He received a
bachelor's degree in philosophy in Cordoba, Argentina.
   He continued his studies in Belgium where he began his political
involvement. Upon his return in 1971, he founded the Revolutionary
Movement of the Left, which opposed Gen. Banzer Suarez.
   Paz Zamora was arrested in February 1974 along with hundreds of
other political figures but was released five months later and
exiled to Venezuela.
   His resistance to the Banzer regime continued from exile and
after his return in 1977. He participated in the 1978 presidential
elections, the results of which were nullified due to widespread
fraud.
   During the 1980 presidential campaign, a private plane carrying
Paz Zamora and four other candidates crashed near La Paz. Paz
Zamora was the only surviver and suffered severe burns. He was
rushed to the United States for treatment and his face and hands
still show scars from the suspicious crash.
   In the 1979 and 1980 presidential elections he was candidate for
vice-president as part of the Popular and Democratic Unity
Coalition. The coalition won the largest number of votes in the
1980 elections but was prevented from taking office due to a bloody
military coup headed by Gen. Luis Garcia Meza.
   Paz Zamora was in the United States during the coup but members
of his party and coalition were arrested, persecuted or killed by
armed civilians and soldiers. On Jan. 15, 1981, 11 leaders of Paz
Zamora's party were meeting at a private home when paramilitary and
soldiers attacked. All but one of the leaders were brutally
tortured and killed.
   In response to domestic political and labor as well as
international opposition, military rulers stepped down and Congress
elected Hernan Siles Zuazo president and Paz Zamora vice president
in 1982.
   Within months of taking over the banrkupt economy, the coalition
split and Paz Zamora's party left the government. Within his party,
the more radical leftist leaders broke away in response to tough
austerity measures dictated by the government in an effort to
control an inflation rate that reached 24,000 percent by 1985.
   While Siles Zuazo and Paz Zamora were slated to remain in office
until 1986, serious social unrest and economic difficulties led to
early elections in 1985.
   Paz Zamora's party, weakened by internal rivalries, only won 8
percent of the vote in 1985 elections.
   In 1987, Paz Zamora's party, however, won second place in
nationwide municipal elections with 26 percent of the vote. By
then, the Marxist tendency within the party gave way to a more
pragmatic approach that tried to capture votes from the center.
   Paz Zamora supports a free market economy, flexible exchange
rates and economic stability. He now considers himself a
nationalist leftist with ties to the the European social democratic
movement and the international socialists.
   He differs, however, with the government's current economic
model because he favors greater protection for national industries,
programs to reactivate the economy and greater expenditures for
health and education.
   He is divorced and has two teenage sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
