<FIRST>r a AM-Crack-Juveniles     08-03 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack-Juveniles,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Shows 254 Young Crack Abusers Committed 223,000 Crimes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MIAMI (A P) _ A study of254 hard-core juvenile crack cocaine
users found they commit an astonishing total of 223,000 crimes a
year, counting both drug possession itself and other crimes such as
robbery, assault and shoplifting.
   The pioneering Dade County research on children age 12 to 17
shows that current drug-prevention programs in the inner cities are
too little and too late, researchers and local officials said
Thursday.
   ``A large segment of a generation is being severely put at risk
because of crack cocaine,'' said James Rivers, the county's top
drug abuse official and author of the final report. ``If they
continue in this pattern, it is very likely they are going to get
into heavier crime, serious health consequences, and will never be
able to integrate into society.''
   The research focused on juvenile violators known to be drug
users _ nine out of 10 adolescents in the study had been arrested
at least once. All were interviewed about when they began abusing
alcohol and drugs and how many crimes they committed to sustain
their drug use.
   ``First use is an average age of 7 for their first drink, and by
13, half of these kids had been behind bars,'' said Rivers.
   The average age for the first time they became drunk was 8 years
old, first drug use occurred at 9.9 years, and regular drug use
began at age 11.
   Rivers said the adolescents confessed to an average of about 880
crimes each in the previous year, an amount he called ``stunning.''
   That average breaks down, with some numbers rounded, to 37 major
felonies ranging from assault to burglary, 101 prostitution and
other vice offenses, 205 petty property crimes such as shoplifting
and 538 drug sale and possession violations.
   But only one out of 555 crimes resulted in an arrest, the study
found, and only 4 percent of the juveniles ever received drug abuse
treatment.
   ``We've got a population of adolescents out there _ we don't
know how large it is _ that is heavily involved in drugs and
crime,'' said University of Delaware sociologist James Iniciardi,
who conducted many of the interviews. ``The current methods of
interdiction are really not doing anything for this group.''
   As other studies have shown, crack generates far more crime than
other addictive drugs such as heroin, Rivers said.
   ``Cocaine is a stimulant _ you remain agitated and alert,'' he
said. ``The small dosage and the short duration of the high ...
predisposes the user to use it again and again and again.''
   And when the users run out of money, they turn to crime, he said.
   Both Rivers and Iniciardi emphasized that those studied were
hard-core cases, not average adolescents. And they said many had
committed crimes even before becoming involved with drugs.
   The interviews were done between October 1986 and November 1987.
   ``It seems to be consistent with what we're seeing on the
streets _ and it's scary,'' said Miami police Lt. Jon Brooks, who
runs the city's street narcotics unit.
   Solutions are difficult, Rivers and Iniciardi said.
   ``Drugs are not the problem in the ghetto, the ghetto is the
problem in the ghetto,'' Iniciardi said. ``Drugs are a coping
mechanism, and for some, drugs are seen as a mechanism for upward
mobility to get out of the ghetto.''
   The men said drug programs, especially in the inner city, must
begin as early as preschool.
</TEXT>
