<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSCommission     08-03 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Commission,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Chairwoman Says More Compassion Needed in AIDS Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Michigan pediatrician selected to head the
new National Commission on AIDS said Thursday the panel should try
to reverse a lack of compassion she said has marked the fight
against the disease.
   Dr. June Osborn, dean of the University of Michigan School of
Public Health and a professor of pediatrics and communicable
diseases, said she will strive to bring greater humanity to the
nation's response to the epidemic.
   ``It's been hard for the country to get a sense that there are
real people'' who are infected with the human immunodeficiency
virus that causes AIDS, she said.
   ``But everybody who dies is somebody's son or daughter,'' she
said. ``This is happening to real people.''
   At its first meeting Thursday, the 15 commission members
selected Osborn as chairwoman and David E. Rogers, a professor of
medicine at Cornell University Medical College in New York and a
former president of the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, as vice
chairman.
   The commission began its work two weeks after President Bush
announced his two selections to the panel, which was created by
Congress last year to advise the president and Capitol Hill on AIDS
issues.
   The members spent most of the day getting acquainted with each
other, picking their leaders and exchanging philosophies and ideas.
   Osborne said she sees the commission as a unique forum for
giving people with AIDS a chance to say how their lives could be
made easier.
   ``If we can communicate commitment and compassion, we will have
added to something that has been lacking and the federal government
can't provide on its own,'' she said.
   Rep. Roy Rowland, D-Ga., a physician, said the panel could
provide some needed guidance to Congress on how to respond to the
AIDS epidemic.
   ``I think they need some direction,'' he said, noting the
country has no national policy on such AIDS-related issues as
confidentiality of testing.
   Belinda Mason, a young mother of two who is infected with the
AIDS virus, said she hopes the panel will focus part of its efforts
on discrimination against people with AIDS, which she has
experienced personally.
   ``It's getting harder and harder for people (with AIDS) to lead
decent lives,'' she said.
   The commission will meet again Aug. 17 to make personnel and
staffing decisions and meet again Sept. 18-19.
   The panel is to submit an interim report within a year and a
final report within two years.
</TEXT>
