<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1818EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Contras     08-03 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Contras,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dodd Hits Administration Efforts to Keep Contras Going</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's efforts to forestall
the disbanding of Nicaragua's Contra rebels amount to a breach of
an agreement with Congress and could lead to a cutoff of all aid to
the rebels, a leading Contra critic said Thursday.
   ``I'm convinced that if the administration succeeds'' in
pressuring the presidents of the Central American countries to
delay disbanding the Contras, ``that you will see humanitarian aid
to the Contras cut off on Nov. 30,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Western
Hemisphere subcommittee.
   Bernard Aronson, assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, went to Guatemala on Wednesday to urge diplomats preparing
for a weekend meeting of the Central American presidents to keep
the rebels together until after Nicaragua's national elections,
scheduled for Feb. 25.
   At a Capitol Hill news conference, Contra leader Adolfo Calero
welcomed the Bush administration's position. ``We are elated that
President Bush has come out unequivocally in favor of having the
resistance remain as a viable force,'' he said.
   Calero said he is confident that the regional presidents ``have
enough information and realism to recognize that it was through the
efforts of the resistance that a political process was made
possible. This is still under way and can't be demobilized until
the process reaches a conclusion. You do not take down a scaffold
before a building is finished.''
   In a related development, the House Intelligence Committee
delayed action on a Democratic proposal to bar CIA political aid to
opposition parties in Nicaragua, bowing to a request from Secretary
of State James A. Baker III.
   The administration wants to keep the option of covert aid to
anti-Sandinista candidates, but the Intelligence panel may take up
the issue again when Congress returns in September from a
month-long recess.
   A senior State Department official, briefing reporters on the
Aronson trip, cited complaints that the Sandinista government is
raiding suspected Contra sympathizers in northern Nicaragua and has
failed to create fair conditions for political opponents.
   ``That is hardly the kind of action that the government should
be taking if it wants to create the conditions that would allow the
resistance to reintegrate,'' said the official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   ``Frankly, it is not clear that the Sandinista government really
wants to embrace national reconciliation and reintegration of the
resistance. Their narrow goal appears to be simply to take away
their weapons and let them scatter to the winds.''
   But Dodd, in an interview with a group of reporters, said the
administration's efforts to influence the regional peace process
threaten to unravel a bipartisan accord on U.S. policy reached
between Bush and congressional Democrats on March 24.
   That agreement called for some $40 million in renewed
humanitarian aid to the rebels through Feb. 28, 1990. But it also
provided that the aid could be used for voluntary relocation of
rebel fighters back into Nicaragua, and stipulated that it could be
cut off Nov. 30 if key Democrats on Capitol Hill believed the
administration was not adequately supporting peace efforts.
   Both sides said they believed that approach would permit the
armed opposition to be reintegrated into Nicaragua's political life
and would encourage the Sandinista regime to make bona fide reforms
in the electoral processes and to restore political freedoms.
   But if Bush is bringing pressure on the Central American
presidents to put off demobilization of the rebels until after the
February elections, Dodd said, ``the bipartisan accord may well
become a dead letter.''
   Dodd said he was not suggesting that demobilization of the
rebels begin immediately or be completed before the elections. But
he said neither should the start of the process be postponed until
after the balloting.
   He released a letter to Secretary of State James A. Baker III
asking that the administration release some of the $70 million in
U.S. economic aid to Honduras appropriated for the current year but
which is being held up.
   The administration clearly is using the money as leverage to
pressure the Hondurans into continuing to host the Contra camps
along their border with Nicaragua and into opposing demobilization,
he said.
</TEXT>
