<FIRST>r a AM-SheriffPleads     08-03 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sheriff Pleads,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Sheriff Pleads Guilty to Charges Stemming from Inmate's Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former sheriff pleaded guilty Thursday
to two federal charges stemming from accusations that he helped an
escaped inmate avoid capture.
   Judge F.A. Little of Alexandria gave former Natchitoches Parish
Sheriff Norm Fletcher a three-year suspended prison sentence and
fined him $12,600.
   ``I'm glad the whole thing's over,'' Fletcher, 58, said after
the court proceedings. ``In one or two instances I let my
compassion overtake my better judgment.''
   Fletcher pleaded innocent to a six-count federal indictment
charging him with helping Fred Bates Jr. flee the parish (county)
jail while awaiting prosecution on a 1984 burglary charge. Bates
was captured in August 1988 in St. Thomas, Virgin Islands.
   At Thursday's hearing, Fletcher changed his plea to guilty of
conspiracy after the fact and misprision of felony.
   Those charges concerned his failure to report Bates' whereabouts
after his escape and Fletcher's neglecting to use the National
Crime Information Center computer to check out an alias that Bates
may have taken.
   In return for the guilty pleas, Assistant U.S. Attorney John
Lydick of Shreveport dropped the four other charges, which accused
Fletcher of helping Bates escape.
   During federal investigations of Fletcher, Bates told
investigators that Fletcher granted him special privileges at the
jail in return for sexual favors.
   Fletcher denied this and no charges were ever brought in
connection with those allegations. Fletcher did admit to granting
special privileges to Bates and other prisoners _ including
allowing them to attend college courses _ because he believed it
helped in rehabilitation.
   The four counts dropped included one each of conspiracy; aiding
and abetting unauthorized flight to avoid prosecution; accessory
after the fact, and conspiracy after the fact.
</TEXT>
