<HEAD>Two Convicted of Setting Woman on Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Flemming is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men have been found guilty of setting
a woman on fire because she failed to pay a $50 cocaine debt.
   Lamont Anthony Flemming, 22, and Devonne Andre Johnson, 21, were
found guilty Wednesday by an Alameda County Superior Court jury of
attempted murder, burglary, attempted robbery, kidnapping for
extortion, kidnapping and causing great bodily injury.
   They are scheduled to be sentenced Sept. 22 and face a maximum
of life without the possibility of parole, according to prosecutor
M.J. Tocci.
   The victim, Camille Johnson, 36, suffered second- and
third-degree burns on the upper part of her body in the March 1988
attack.
   She also was beaten with a baseball bat and one of her fingers
was broken, according to court documents.
