<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DenverSymphony     08-03 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denver Symphony,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orchestra's Fate Awaits Board's Decision Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS M. SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of the Denver Symphony Orchestra, which
is $4 million in debt, meets Friday to decide whether the entire
concert season should be canceled for the first time in the
orchestra's 55-year history.
   Last season was cut short in March, two months early, because of
financial problems.
   The next symphony season, usually 41 weeks beginning in
September, already has been sharply scaled back, with a tentative
start date in January. There is a chance there may be no season at
all, orchestra officials have said.
   ``I am hesitant to say it is an absolute decision day,'' Denver
Symphony Association Chairman John Low said of the meeting.
``Nevertheless, I am hopeful we will reach a decision.''
   The orchestra's problems have been blamed on the region's
declining economy, the city's 10 percent seat tax and management
turnover, said Josi Callan, the marketing director. The orchestra
must raise $600,000 a month to keep operating.
   ``Maybe that's more than this area wants to pay for it,'' Ms.
Callan said.
   The orchestra averages 15,000 to 16,000 attendance at classical
concerts in the 26,000-seat Boettcher Concert Hall, but has sold
out the hall for pops concerts.
   Earlier this summer the board rejected a proposed 27-week season
which was to have begun in November. The board cited the symphony's
unresolved $4 million debt and the fact that musicians had not
agreed to contract modifications and other concessions.
   The recovery plan the board will examine Friday calls for the
symphony's endowment fund trustees to forgive a $2.5 million debt
from the orchestra.
   Symphony executives have also asked the City Council to write
off $700,000 the symphony owes the city in back rent on the concert
hall.
   City Councilman Ted Hackworth opposes forgiving the back rent
and said the symphony should declare bankruptcy.
   ``What it's going to take is for them to wake up and realize
they have to operate like a business, not a charity,'' Hackworth
said.
   Earlier this week, the symphony notified its 81 musicians that
their dental and health benefits were canceled effective Wednesday,
saving the association about $30,000 a month.
   Three years ago the musicians agreed to 20 percent pay cuts to
keep the symphony solvent.
   Since then the symphony's financial woes have multiplied.
   A year ago, then-board chairman Robert E. Lee threatened to put
the orchestra into Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings because of
debt, then resigned the next month after a fund-raising drive
brought $700,000 in private and corporate contributions.
   Later, music director Phillippe Entremont and executive director
Chris Dunworth resigned.
   Low said that the recovery plan the board will consider would
have the orchestra spend ``less money on high-priced guest artists
and rely more heavily on the music provided by the orchestra
itself.''
   Orchestras in Oakland and San Diego, Calif., New Orleans and
Nashville, Tenn., have filed for bankruptcy and then resumed
operations after reorganizing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
