<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Ivory     08-03 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Ivory,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Ivory Smuggling Network Broken</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police confiscated 106
elephant tusks and arrested people allegedly involved in the
biggest ivory smuggling operation yet uncovered in South Africa,
authorities said Thursday.
   Police found the ivory in the Cape Town home of Michael Shen, a
37-year-old Taiwanese citizen who has lived in South Africa for the
past nine years. Shen and an unspecified number of other men were
arrested Wednesday, police said.
   It was not immediately clear whether the tusks came from
elephants in South Africa or elsewhere on the continent, police
said. One rhino horn also was confiscated, they said.
   South Africa's well-managed wildlife parks have few reported
incidents of poaching, but conservationists say the country is a
major transit point for smugglers in other parts of Africa.
   The African elephant population has fallen from about 1.5
million in 1978 to as few as 400,000 today, mostly because of
poachers who seek the valuable tusks.
   Several Western nations, including the United States, have
banned the import of ivory in recent months. The 102-nation
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species will
consider a worldwide ban on the ivory trade in October.
</TEXT>
