<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0753 08-03 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0753,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Insists on Prisoner Swap for Obeid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to include Rabin comment; picks up 11th
pvs, `Cicippio should...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel welcomed the decision of Lebanese
captors to suspend their death sentence on an American, but stuck
to its position of freeing a Shiite Moslem cleric only in a trade
for hostages.
   The Revolutionary Justice Organization had said it would kill
Joseph Cicippio, but released a handwritten statement 45 minutes
before the deadline saying it had suspended the death threat and
including new demands.
   In addition to Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a Shiite Moslem cleric
abducted by Israel, it now wants the release of ``Palestinian and
Lebanese'' guerrillas in Israeli jails. It said the names would be
given to the Red Cross.
   ``Acceptance should be announced within days, otherwise the
initiative will be considered canceled,'' the kidnappers said,
without explaining what the vague language meant.
   ``I can tell you that all the sides now have more time,'' said a
senior Defense Ministry official.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told reporters in Jerusalem: ``If
indeed there are real grounds for the report on a proposal for
prisoners exchange, we shall examine it on a positive basis.''
   Officials declined to say whether they believed the new demands
provided an opening for negotiations.
   ``What remains to be seen is whether Hezbollah is ready to do
business and ready to negotiate the exchange we have proposed. This
is why we are cautious,'' said Avi Pazner, spokesman for Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Obeid is a spiritual leader of Hezbollah, a pro-Iranian group
believed to be responsible for the kidnapping Westerners in Lebanon.
   Yossi Ahimeir, a top Shamir aide, insisted Cicippio be freed
before negotiations.
   ``Cicippio should be released immediately,'' he added. ``He
should go back to his family. He is an innocent man.''
   Other Israeli officials expressed concern over a reference to
freeing Palestinian prisoners from the uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip. That could include more than 8,000
Palestinian detainees.
   Earlier Thursday, Israel issued a plea for the Shiites not to
carry out the threatened killing of Cicippio but said it would free
Obeid only if it got back Israeli soldiers and foreign hostages.
   ``We still stick to our position that we are ready to exchange
kidnap victims and hostages,'' Ahimeir said. ``Our goal is to
rescue, save our people in Lebanon in the hands of several
organizations there.''
   The Lebanese captors on Thursday released a videotaped plea from
Cicippio, who called for the release of Obeid and added: ``Don't be
late ... because they are very serious.''
   Israeli commandos abducted Obeid from his home in south Lebanon
on July 28. Israel says he planned guerrilla raids and directed the
kidnapping of Lt. Co. William R. Higgins, a U.S. Marine serving
with U.N peacekeepers, in February 1988.
   Higgins' captors said they hanged him Monday.
   Ahimeir reported ``all kinds of consultations'' within the
government about the hostage crisis.
   Yossi Ben Aharon, a top aide to Shamir, said Israel was in
``constant touch'' with the U.S. government, but he would not say
whether Shamir had talked by telephone with President Bush.
   The Foreign Ministry summoned the ambassadors of West Germany,
Italy and Britain, whose citizens are among the hostages in
Lebanon, and also the Japanese envoy.
   Israel radio said the Japanese ambassador was called in because
Japan was involved in contacts with Iran. The radio gave no details
and ministry officials could not be reached for comment.
   Higgins' captors released a poor-quality videotape of a man who
appeared to be the Marine colonel hanging from a gallows. There was
no way of telling when the tape was made, conflicting reports have
arisen about when he was killed.
   A Defense Ministry statement said Obeid told interrogators he
believed Higgins was alive last week.
   The statement said Israel continued to believe Higgins was
killed late last year. Officials said they might give Obeid to a
lie-detector test to determine what he knew about the American
officer.
</TEXT>
