<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Suffocation,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Church Calls For Inquiry Into Suffocation Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Uganda's Roman Catholic
Church condemned the recent suffocations of 69 civilians by
government troops and called for an independent investigation into
the killings, a newspaper said Thursday.
   ``We condemn in the strongest terms this criminal act of the
murder of innocent citizens in cold blood by the National
Resistance Army,'' said Cardinal Emmanuel Nsubuga. ``We hope that
such atrocities will never be repeated in our nation.''
   He was quoted in the government-owned newspaper New Vision.
   The government has said the victims were among 238 youths
detained June 10 and held in unused railroad cars in war-torn
northeastern Uganda. The soldiers, who were fighting rebels in the
area at the time, had rounded up the people in villages near the
city of Kumi, 155 miles northeast of Kampala.
   
   The government has also said that those who died were innocent,
because the rebels already had been taken to army headquarters.
   The army has arrested 14 officers in the case. The officers
could face the death penalty if convicted of murder.
   Nsubuga urged an independent inquiry into the incident.
