<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2230EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-TrojanHorse     08-03 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trojan Horse,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents of Slain Boys Win First-Round of Legal Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents of two boys shot to death
by police concealed in crates on a truck won an early victory
Thursday in their fight to prosecute the officers for murder.
   Supreme Court Justice D.M. Williamson rejected a request by the
13 defendants _ one army officer and 12 policemen _ that he order
the parents to post a deposit of $360,000 to cover possible legal
costs in event of acquittal. The parents' lawyers doubted such a
sum could be raised.
   Williamson noted the government is paying the defendants' legal
costs and said granting the request ``may be loading the scales in
favor of the accused.''
   The defendants went on trial for murder Tuesday in an
unprecedented private prosecution.
   The parents decided to pursue the case on their own after the
attorney general for Cape Province declined to prosecute despite an
inquest magistrate's finding that police were negligent.
   It is the first murder trial to proceed under a law allowing
private citizens to press a prosecution in certain instances where
the government declines.
   The killings took place in 1985 during anti-apartheid unrest in
a mixed-race township near Cape Town. The case became known as the
Trojan Horse incident because white police concealed themselves in
what looked like a delivery truck.
   According to evidence at the inquest, an army commandant and two
senior police officers ordered the truck into Athlone to draw
attacks from stone-throwers.
   Gunfire from the hidden policemen killed Shaun Magmoed, 16,
Michael Miranda, 11, and Jonathen Classens, 21. The magistrate
concluded no evidence emerged that the three were among a handful
of youths who threw stones.
   Miranda's mother and Magmoed's father instituted the
prosecution. Their lawyers are to be paid from a fund set up last
year which has received contributions from overseas human rights
organizations.
</TEXT>
