<FIRST>u w AM-DiplomaticNominations     08-03 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomatic Nominations,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Delays Action on Bush Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., on Thursday delayed
Senate action for at least a month on President Bush's nomination
of a senior black diplomat to be director general of the U.S.
Foreign Service, the nation's professional diplomatic corps.
   Exercising his rights under the rules of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, Helms put a ``hold'' on the nomination of
Edward J. Perkins, until recently the U.S. ambassador to South
Africa.
   Normally that would delay action for a week only. But because
the Senate is ready to leave on its summer vacation, Helms' move
effectively postpones Perkins' confirmation for more than a month,
until the beginning of September at the earliest.
   Helms refused to give a reason for his action.
   But he acted after complaining about delays in Senate
consideration of three ambassadorial nominees, all major
contributors to Republican campaigns and causes, who have been
rated as ``unqualified'' by the American Academy of Diplomacy.
   He also complained that some career Foreign Service officers on
a promotion list had been targets of State Department
investigations in the past for alleged expense account abuse.
   And he made clear he is also upset that no Senate action has
been scheduled on Bush's nomination of Donald P. Gregg to be U.S.
ambassador to South Korea.
   In two lengthy Senate hearings Gregg denied that he _ while
serving as Bush's vice presidential chief of staff _ was ever part
of the secret network set up by former Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L.
North to provide illegal military aid to the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels.
   But Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., has said he questions Gregg's
truthfulness.
   The committee did approve and send to the Senate a number of
diplomatic nominations.
   One of the nominees, Julia Chang Bloch, who was born in China
and emigrated to the United States as a refugee, would be the first
Asian-American ambassador in U.S. history.
   Named to be U.S. ambassador to Nepal, she most recently served
as an assistant director of the Agency for International
Development.
   Also approved by the committee were:
   Richard A. Clarke to be assistant secretary of state for
politico-military affairs; Eugene P. Kopp to be deputy director of
the U.S. Information Agency (USIA); Henry E. Hockeimer to be an
associate USIA director; Sheldon J. Krys to be assistant secretary
of state for diplomatic security; Alexander F. Watkins to be deputy
U.S. representative to the United Nations; Milton J. Wilkinson to
be deputy representative to the U.N. Security Council.
   Also, Morris D. Busby to be coordinator for counter terrorism;
Arthur W. Fort to be assistant secretary of state for
administration; Raymond G. H. Seitz to be assistant secretary of
state for European and Canadian affairs; Raymond C. Ewing to be
ambassador to Ghana; William L. Swing to be ambassador to South
Africa; Howard K. Walker to be ambassador to Madagascar; Michael G.
Sotirhos to be ambassador to Greece.
   And, Loret Miller Ruppe, former director of the Peace Corps, to
be ambassador to Norway; Richard A. Moore to be ambassador to
Ireland, and Jonathan Moore to be U.S. representative for refugee
affairs at the United Nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
