<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1917EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-FAA-Jetliners     08-03 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA-Jetliners,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Calls For Jetliner Study, Senator Says Ground DC-10s If Flawed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced
Thursday a design review aimed at increasing the safety of all
wide-bodied jetliners bercause of accidents where in-flight
failures damaged control devices.
   At the same time, a U.S. senator called for the immediate
grounding and alteration of all wide-bodied DC-10s if news reports
suggesting flaws in their design are true.
   The FAA said an industry and government task force would
recommend whether changes are necessary in ``all existing and
future wide-body aircraft,'' which would include planes made by
Boeing, Lockheed, McDonnell Douglas and the Airbus Industrie
consortium in Europe.
   Tony Broderick, head of FAA safety regulations, said he believes
safety improvements that will ensure against failure of flight
control systems when another component fails ``are within the realm
of technical and economic feasibility.''
   Broderick said in an interview he had no detailed idea of how
that might be done, but expects ``the best minds in industry and
government'' can solve the problem.
   The aegncy announcement came two weeks after the crash of a
United Airlines DC-10 in Iowa that killed 111 people. Investigators
believe an explosive engine failure knocked out all three hydraulic
flight control systems designed to back up each other.
   The plane crashed, broke apart and burst into flames, but 186
people, including the cockpit crew, survived.
   The FAA cited the Sioux City, Iowa, crash as well as a 1985
Japan Airlines crash of a Boeing 747 and a 1981 incident in which a
Lockheed-built L-1011 lost hydraulic control. Both DC-10s and
L-1011s are no longer in production, although hundreds are flown
throughout the world.
   The review will look into survivability of aircraft after major
in-flight structural damage, said FAA Administrator James Busey.
   Busey said the task force will explore ways of improving the
ability of an aircraft to survive after it suffers major in-flight
structural damage.
   ``The task force will explore feasible improvements to the
backup flight control systems,'' the FAA said.
   Other aircraft with similar controls to those that failed would
also be included at a later stage in the study, the agency said.
   ``It also will examine engine design with an eye toward possibly
preventing crippling damage to an aircraft in the event of an
engine explosion,'' the FAA said.
   The aviation agency approves design, construction, testing, and
operation of all airliners used by U.S. carriers, and many foreign
governments follow its lead. It now requires that jet engines be
built to contain fragments of fans, compressors or turbine blades
that may break off in flight.
   But, the FAA said its regulation recognize that ``there is no
practical way to contain the parts on which the blades are mounted
_ the disks _ when they fail becuase of their weight and the speed
at which they travel.''
   Investigators are exploring the possibility of such a failure in
the Iowa crash.
   Sen Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, in a letter to the FAA, cited
news accounts saying that if the DC-10 had four rather than three
hydraulic systems, as the L-1011 does, or a shut-off valve to
prevent hydraulic fluid loss, lives might have been saved.
   ``If these allegations are true, the FAA should ground all
DC-10s and correct their design flaws immediately,'' he said.
   Broderick, speaking for the FAA, said, ``There are no design
flaws in the DC-10 or any other aircraft presently flying that
warrant its grounding.''
   He said the agency would respond promptly to Metzenbaum's letter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
