<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-EmmyNominations 1stLd-Writethru a0731 08-03 1053</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emmy Nominations, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0731,1078</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Lonesome Dove' Herds 18 Emmy Nominations While `Roseanne' Snubbed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 7th, ``Series star ..., to UPDATE with
Barr's publicist's comment.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY33</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Lonesome Dove'' stampeded over
its TV rivals as CBS' cowpoke miniseries gathered a leading 18
nominations Thursday for the Primetime Emmy Awards, while ABC's hit
``Roseanne'' was all but snubbed.
   NBC's swank drama ``L.A. Law'' collected 17 nominations and
ABC's 30-hour World War II miniseries ``War and Remembrance'' drew
15 citations. The nostalgic ABC comedy ``The Wonder Years''
gathered 14 nominations, followed by the network's hug-heavy drama
``thirtysomething'' with 13 selections.
   ``It is very exciting and very gratifying to have the feeling
that win, lose or draw ... we are doing first-rate work,'' said
``L.A. Law'' co-creator Steven Bochco.
   The new CBS situation comedy ``Murphy Brown,'' a satiric view of
a television news magazine, got 11 nominations. ``I'm very excited;
I'm excited for all of us,'' said the show's star, Candice Bergen.
   Fox's offbeat variety series ``The Tracey Ullman Show'' finished
with 10 nominations, as did NBC's perpetual Emmy favorite ``The
Golden Girls.''
   ``Roseanne,'' the crass working-class comedy that was last
season's highest-rated new show, received only three nominations.
   Series star Roseanne Barr was not among the five choices for
best actress in a comedy series, and the series was not named in
the best comedy sweepstakes. John Goodman earned the show's only
major nomination for best actor in a comedy series.
   ``She's very pleased about (co-star) John Goodman's nomination
and she's disappointed the show didn't get nominated. That's all,''
said publicist Pat Kingsley.
   In its last, trouble-plagued season, ABC's ``Moonlighting'' was
handed only three nominations, all in minor categories.
   The syndicated series ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' and the
CBS drama ``Beauty and the Beast'' each received eight nominations.
   NBC's explosive abortion-law movie ``Roe vs. Wade'' _ which was
subjected to more than 17 network-mandated rewrites, abandoned by
advertisers and the target of anti-abortion protests _ earned six
nominations, all in major categories.
   ``It makes you feel that it is all worth it,'' said Alison
Cross, the writer and co-producer of ``Roe vs. Wade.'' ``This
rewards us for having survived the process. All those people who
say, `You can't get anything good on television' are wrong.''
   The Academy of Television Arts &amp; Sciences said it handed out 364
nominations in 84 categories, with NBC taking the most with 103.
   Among the nominations for ``Lonesome Dove,'' based on the
Pulitzer Prize- winning novel by Larry McMurtry, were best
miniseries and outstanding acting achievement by Tommy Lee Jones,
Robert Duvall, Diane Lane, Danny Glover, Anjelica Huston and Glenne
Headly.
   The eight-hour miniseries also snared nominations for directing
and writing.
   ``L.A. Law'' courted 17 nominations as best drama series and for
nine actors, Michael Tucker and Jill Eikenberry, who portray a
couple on the show and are married in real life; Susan Dey; Larry
Drake; Jimmy Smits; Richard Dysart; Michelle Greene; Susan Ruttan
and Amanda Plummer. The series also received two directing and
three writing nominations.
   ``War and Remembrance,'' the sequel to ``Winds of War,'' based
on Herman Wouk's sweeping novel, drew nominations for best
miniseries and lead acting awards for John Gielgud and Jane Seymour
and supporting honors for Polly Bergen. It also was nominated for
directing.
   ``I'm glad they haven't forgotten us,'' said Dan Curtis,
producer, director and co-writer of the 30-hour miniseries.
   Other nominees for best miniseries were NBC's ``I Know My First
Name is Steven,'' PBS' ``A Perfect Spy'' and ABC's ``The Women of
Brewster Place.''
   ``The Wonder Years'' was nominated as best comedy series and its
young star Fred Savage was nominated as best lead actor in a comedy
series. It also received three nominations for directing and four
for writing.
   Comedy series nominees along with ``The Wonder Years'' were
NBC's ``Cheers,'' CBS' ``Designing Women,'' and ``The Golden
Girls'' and ``Murphy Brown.''
   The yuppie-themed ``thirtysomething,'' winner of four Emmy
trophies last year, was nominated for best drama series. Co-star
Timothy Busfield was chosen in the supporting actor field, and
Melanie Mayron was among the picks for best supporting actress.
``Thirtysomething'' also was selected for outstanding directing.
   CBS' ``Beauty and the Beast,'' ABC's ``China Beach'' and CBS'
``Wiseguy'' joined ``thirtysomething'' and ``L.A. Law'' as nominees
as best drama series.
   Selected to compete for the best drama or comedy special were
ABC's ``David,'' HBO's ``Murderers Among Us: The Simon Wiesenthal
Story,'' ABC's ``My Name is Bill W.,'' ``Roe vs. Wade'' and CBS'
``Day One,'' giving a rare Emmy nomination to producer Aaron
Spelling.
   Nominated as best lead actor in a comedy series along with
Savage were Ted Danson for NBC's ``Cheers,'' Richard Mulligan for
NBC's ``Empty Nest,'' Michael J. Fox for NBC's now-defunct ``Family
Ties'' and Goodman for ``Roseanne.''
   Those picked in favor of Miss Barr for lead comedy actress were
Blair Brown for Lifetime's ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,''
Candice Bergen for ``Murphy Brown,'' and Betty White, Bea Arthur
and Rue McClanahan, all of ``The Golden Girls.''
   Ron Perlman was nominated as best lead actor in drama series for
``Beauty and the Beast,'' along with Edward Woodward of CBS' ``The
Equalizer,'' Carroll O'Connor for NBC's ``In the Heat of the
Night,'' Ken Wahl for CBS' ``Wiseguy'' and Tucker for ``L.A. Law.''
   Perlman's co-star in ``Beauty and the Beast,'' Linda Hamilton,
was nominated as best lead actress in a drama series, as were Dana
Delany in ABC's ``China Beach,'' Angela Lansbury in CBS' ``Murder,
She Wrote'' and Dey and Eikenberry in ``L.A. Law.''
   Trailing behind NBC's leading 103 nominations were CBS, with 95
selections, and ABC, with 85. The Public Broadcasting Service had
32 nominations, syndicated shows 21, Fox 12, Home Box Office eight,
Disney and MTV two and Lifetime, Turner Broadcasting Systems,
Turner Network Television and USA cable networks with one apiece.
   The late Lucille Ball was voted for the academy's Governors
Award.
   Selections of the winners will be made Aug. 26-27 at the Beverly
Hilton Hotel by various peer panels in which actors select actors,
directors select directors, writers select writers and the like.
   Winners will be announced in two ceremonies on Sept. 16 and 17,
with the latter show featuring major awards to be broadcast live by
the Fox Broadcasting Corp.
</TEXT>
