<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     08-03 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaders Still Hope For Peaceful Settlement in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Moerdiono is cq in 15th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Non-Communist Southeast Asia
leaders are disappointed by talks in Paris to end 10 years of war
in Cambodia but still hope for a peaceful settlement, Malaysia's
prime minister said Thursday.
   The foreign ministers of 19 countries, who met this week in
Paris, set up working committees to help monitor Vietnam's
withdrawal from Cambodia and an ensuing cease-fire, deal with
sovereignty questions and plan for repatriation of refugees.
   But talks between Cambodian Premier Hun Sen and leaders of the
three-party Cambodian resistance alliance led by Prince Norodom
Sihanouk reached an impasse July 25 after two days of negotiations.
   The talks were aimed at bringing warring Cambodian factions
together and ensuring peace after Vietnam withdraws its troops from
Cambodia, which it has occupied since December 1978.
   ``We are a little bit disappointed,'' said Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohammed. ``But we are realistic people. We know
we can't resolve things by sitting and looking at each other. More
discussions are needed.''
   Mahathir made the statement between meetings with Indonesian
President Suharto, President Corazon Aquino of the Philippines and
Prime Minister Lee Kwan Yew of Singapore.
   Mahathir is scheduled to meet Prime Minister Chatichai
Choonhavan of Thailand when the Thai premier visits Malaysia on
Friday.
   Southeast Asian leaders were gathered here for Wednesday's rites
symbolizing the ``coming of age'' of the eldest son of Brunei's
Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah.
   Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand are
Brunei's partners in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations _
the main proponents of the Paris conference.
   ASEAN, China, the United States and other Western countries back
Sihanouk's alliance, which includes the Khmer Rouge, whom the
Vietnamese drove from power.
   Vietnam does not want the Khmer Rouge, blamed for slaughtering
hundreds of thousands of Cambodians during their three years in
power, to play a major role in any new government.
   In Paris, Hun Sen blamed the faction for the breakdown in talks
among the various Cambodian factions. He said the Khmer Rouge
refuses to resume the talks.
   ``This is a problem that cannot be resolved overnight or over
one month,'' Mahathir said. ``We've been working on it for years.''
   A spokesman for Suharto told reporters earlier that the
Indonesian president and Mahathir agreed during their meeting that
prospects for peace in Cambodia remain good.
   But the spokesman, Moerdiono, would not elaborate. He said
Mahathir and Suharto agreed to meet again in Bali later this year
to review the Cambodian situation and discuss other issues.
</TEXT>
