<FIRST>u w AM-AIDS-AZT 1stLd-Writethru   08-03 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-AZT, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0815,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>AZT Shows Benefit For Early Symptoms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds four grafs comments and other development; SUBS graf 11:
``This study,'' to define ARC.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AZT, the only government-approved anti-AIDS
drug, significantly slows progression of the disease when given to
people with early symptoms according to result from a new clinical
trial, officials said Thursday.
   The drug was approved for use in people with AIDS, but new trial
results for the first time show that AZT also benefits patients
with early symptoms of infection with the human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV, that causes AIDS.
   Results were so good the trial has been stopped and patients on
placebo offered the drug instead.
   The finding could potentially benefit an estimated 100,000 to
200,000 people with early symptoms of HIV infection, said Dr.
Anthony Fauci, director of the National Institute of Allergy and
Infectious Diseases.
   ``It also emphasizes how critical it is that persons at risk for
HIV infection be tested and seek prompt medical care,'' Fauci said.
   ``This is real good news,'' said Frank Young, commissioner of
the Food and Drug Administration, which he said will work quickly
``to translate these important results into wider availability of
zidovudine (AZT)'' for earlier treatment of the disease.
   The trial has been underway in 29 locations since August 1987,
according to an announcement late Thursday by the Department of
Health and Human Services, the parent of both NIAID and FDA.
   The trial included 713 HIV-infected people who had one or two
HIV associated symptoms, such as oral thrush, chronic rash or
intermittent diarrhea, and levels of immune system cells, called T4
cells, between 200 and 800 per cubic millimeter. Some participants
received placebos and some received AZT over a period of three to
20 months.
   As of July, 50 of the participants had progressed to
AIDS-related complex or AIDS. Of these, 36 had been taking placebos
and 14 were on AZT.
   Fewer than 5 percent of the participants experienced serious
side effects from the AZT, said Margaret Fischl, a doctor at the
University of Miami, who coordinated the trials.
   ``This study clearly shows that early intervention is important
in HIV infection and that zidovudine is well tolerated in persons
with early ARC (AIDS-related complex),'' she said.
   On the recommendation Wednesday from the Data and Safety
Monitoring Board reviewing the trial data, Fauci stopped the trial
because the results were so promising. He said all study
participants now will be offered AZT.
   AZT is manufactured by Burroughs Wellcome Co. and is marketed
under the trade name Retrovir. It was approved in March 1987 for
treatment of AIDS patients who had recovered from Pneumocycstis
carinii pneumonia _ the leading killer of people with AIDS _ and
patients with advanced ARC.
   Young said: ``We pledge to analyze the data as rapidly as
presented to us so that we can make the appropriate recommendations
to practicing phsicians.
   ``It is important to emphasize in the meantime that physicians
do have the capability of prescribing drugs for different uses than
are on the label, and we fully recognize this. On the other, hand
we know the medical community relies on the analysis by FDA and we
want to complete this as expeditiously as possible,'' he said.
   In another AIDS development Thursday, the FDA licensed the first
diagnostic kit to detect the presence of HIV by detecting the
proteins, or antigens, of the virus. Other licensed kits detect the
presence of the body's response, the antibody, to these proteins.
   The kit is designed to help physicians monitor changes in the
infection rate of people with the virus. The kit is not recommended
for use in screening blood or plasma donations.
</TEXT>
