<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-GypsyConference     08-03 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gypsy Conference,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gypsy Protestants Say Religion Has Eased Acceptance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 30,000 Gypsy fundamentalists
opened a conference Thursday to celebrate a Bible-thumping
Protestantism they say has made them and their lifestyle more
acceptable to a still-wary outside world.
   More than 4,000 caravans, mobile homes and circus wagons are
camped on the outskirts of Amsterdam for the four-day World
Conference of Christian Gypsies.
   The four-day gathering will include twice-daily services, dozens
of prayer sessions and plenty of fire-and-brimstone preaching,
according to the organizers, the French-based Life and Light
mission.
   The Rev. Charles Welty, a Life and Light pastor, said that
despite the aura of conservative respectability, many old Gypsy
traditions remain, including some that are likely to raise frowns
among more conventional churchgoers.
   ``We're first of all Gypsies. When a French Gypsy gets together
with a Dutch Gypsy, it's not a Frenchman and a Dutchman meeting
each other, it's two Gypsies,'' Welty said.
   Most of the world's 40 million Gypsies are Roman Catholics. But
in 1951, Life and Light began an evangelical movement among
European Gypsies that now claims 100,000 members, the Paris-based
preacher told The Associated Press over a beer outside his
26-foot-long caravan.
   Like other fundamentalist Protestants, the Life and Light
Gypsies insist that a personal acceptance of Jesus and strict
adherence to the Bible's teachings are essential to a believer's
salvation.
   But they have maintained their wandering lifestyle, and most
still work as tinkers, musicians or itinerant salesmen, said the
burly, mustachioed Welty as his wife was doing household chores.
   In the 5,000-seat tent that dominates the campsite, a group of
elders debated the day's business. Others sat around a campfire,
played the guitar or repaired their Mercedes limousines. Dogs and
chickens strutted around everywhere, and children cavorted in the
mud or played chess.
   Welty, 48, maintained that acceptance of the Gospel ``has helped
us to make ourselves better known'' to the outside world. ``We have
preached in their churches and they've been among us. It's removed
prejudices.''
   He added that the Gypsy tradition of fortunetelling has fallen
by the wayside among converts because it is regarded as the work of
the devil, but said another custom has survived in an adapted form.
   Under Gypsy law, a couple get married by the simple act of
eloping and staying away for four days. They still do today, but
marry formally before a minister and civil authorities after the
wedding is consummated, Welty said.
   Conventionally minded Protestant preachers ``are a little
shocked because it's not their way of getting married,'' Welty
said. ``When Abraham married Sarah, they didn't go to the mayor's
office either.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
