<FIRST>u i AM-AfricaPrize     08-03 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa Prize,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Africa Prize Shared by Botswana President, Anti-Hunger Activist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Botswana's president was named a co-winner
of the 1989 Africa Prize for Leadership for having prevented famine
in his nation during the 1981-1987 drought.
   President Quett K.J. Masire shares the prize with Dr. Bernard
Ledea Ouedraogo of Burkina Faso. Ouedraogo, an anti-hunger
activist, heads grass-roots organizations that involve more than
500,000 people in nine countries.
   The New York-based Hunger Project, which awards the prize, said
not a single person died of starvation during Botswana's seven-year
drought, the worst in that country's history.
   During the seven years, Masire actually managed to reduce hunger
in his country, the project said.
   Before the drought, 25 percent of Botswana's children were below
average weight. By 1987, the figure had fallen to less than 15
percent.
   Infant mortality in Botswana _ now at 72 deaths for every 1,000
live births _ is the lowest in sub-Saharan Africa.
   Ouedraogo has organized more than 500,000 peasants to end hunger
through self-reliance and development.
   He heads the Naam movement and programs that teach peasant
farmers agricultural techniques, reforestation methods, road
building and how to improve health care. They also give villagers
literacy training.
   The program is active in Burkina Faso, Chad, Gambia,
Guinea-Bissau, Mali, Mauritania, Niger, Senegal and Togo.
   The $100,000 prize is to promote the winner's work.
   The Africa Prize For Leadership award was instituted two years
ago by the non-profit organization. About 5.4 million volunteers
and staff in 152 nations are helping the Hunger Project try to
abolish hunger worldwide, organizers said.
   Last year, President Robert G. Mugabe of Zimbabwe won the prize,
while in the previous year, the award went to President Abdou Diouf
of Senegal and professor Thomas R. Odhiambo of Kenya, a specialist
in insect studies.
</TEXT>
