<FIRST>u i AM-Haiti     08-03 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Grants Haiti $10 Million Worth Of Wheat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The United States granted Haiti $10
million worth of wheat on Thursday in the first resumption of
direct U.S. aid since violence aborted the 1987 elections,
state-run television said.
   Television Nationale d'Haiti said the Food for Peace Program
grant of 45,000 tons of wheat was signed by Cooperation Minister
Theophile Roche and Gerald Zarr, director of the Haiti office of
the U.S. Agency for International Development.
   The government will sell the wheat locally and the proceeds will
be used to ``fulfill the expectations of the socially and
economically disadvantaged population of urban and rural zones,''
Roche said.
   The money will finance an emergency program which includes
promotion of agricultural production through soil conservation,
irrigation and rural road building projects.
   ``This agreement indicates the veritable support of the American
government for change in Haiti and for the continuation of the
democratic process,'' Zarr said during the ceremony, broadcast by
state TV.
   The United States suspended two thirds of its $90 million annual
aid package to Haiti right after the Nov. 29, 1987 elections were
aborted by gunmen who, with army protection, killed at least 34
voters at polling stations.
   Thursday's signing was the first U.S. aid to Haiti since then,
Zarr said.
   He said the agreement ``will be a really positive step toward
the resumption of more substantial aid.''
   Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, who came to power in a soldiers' revolt
in September, has pledged to return Haiti to democratic rule. The
soldiers ousted Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, who came to power when
dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in France in 1986.
</TEXT>
