<SECOND>AM-Greece-Plane, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0820,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Airliner Crashes Into Mountain With 34 Aboard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, The military ... DELETING extraneous words. Picks
up 8th graf, Gelestathis said ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Olympic Airways plane with 34 Greeks
aboard crashed into a mountainside in thick fog on Thursday on the
eastern Aegean island of Samos, officials reported. A search found
no survivors.
   The twin-engine, British-built Short aircraft was on a 290-mile
domestic flight from Salonica, northern Greece to Samos, off
Turkey's western Anatolian coast. It carried 31 passengers,
including an infant, and three crew.
   The propeller-driven plane gave no sign of trouble before
disappearing from radar screens, officials said.
   Transport and Communications Minister Nikos Gelestathis said
commandos reported finding wreckage, bloody clothes and smashed
suitcases on Krounies mountain. Helicopters with medical teams were
ordered to fly to the rugged terrain to assist in search efforts.
   Gelestathis said that the chief of the army general staff, Gen.
Dimitri Veryvakis, was in radio contact with the search teams on
the mountain.
   They reported no survivors were found and that one part of the
plane was found split in half, with wreckage scattered over a wide
area, according to the minister.
   The military teams discovered the crash site after a shepherd
reported seeing an explosion on the mountain. A Greek air force
officer vacationing on Samos confirmed the shepherd's account.
   Gelestathis said troops would search for bodies throughout the
night.
   Earlier, the minister said he did not rule out the possibility
of terrorism ``since the piot gave no indication of any problems.''
But an official at Athens airport, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, later said the pilot apparently flew into the mountain
while blinded by the fog.
   The Athens airport duty officer, Emmanuel Fragiadakis, said the
control tower lost contact with the plane at about 4:55 p.m., an
hour after it left Salonika.
   It was scheduled to land on Samos at 5:30 p.m.
   The plane disappeared from radar screens when it was 25 miles
northwest of Samos.
   Olympic officials said the pilot, Petros Moutzoureas, was a
veteran with an excellent flight record.
   They said the aircraft was bought in 1981 and was used for
flights between the islands.
</TEXT>
