<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Debt     08-03 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Debt,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Parties Say Would Back Debt Moratorium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen major political parties said
Thursday they would back emergency measures to reduce Brazil's $112
billion foreign debt, including a new suspension of payments.
   In a 30-point document, the party leaders urged President Jose
Sarney to negotiate a reduction of both debt principal and interest
with international creditors.
   ``If an accord with creditors cannot be reached, the government
will have the political backing to declare an immediate suspension
of payments,'' the document said.
   Brazil, with the developing world's largest debt, is negotiating
an economic agreement with the International Monetary Fund that
will allow the country to receive more than $4 billion in new loans.
   Banks have balked at giving new money to Brazil, which is in
financial straits with 1,000 percent annual inflation. But the
country needs new money to meet an interest bill of $2.3 billion
due in September.
   Party leaders supported Sarney's decision in early July to
suspend debt interest payments to keep the country's money reserves
above ``an adequate level.'' Brazil paid less than half the $812
million due between June 30 and July 3 to foreign governments,
according to the Central Bank.
   ``The Congress is not willing to impose more sacrifices on the
Brazilian people in order to pay the debt,'' said Sen. Franco
Montoro.
   In July, cash reserves rose nearly $1 billion to $6.5 billion,
in part because of the suspension.
   Signers of the document included members of the Brazilian
Democratic Movement Party, the nation's largest, and the National
Reconstruction Party, which is backing presidential front-runner
Fernando Collor de Mello. In November, Brazilians vote for
president for the first time since 1960.
   In February 1987, Brazil declared a moratorium on $70 billion of
its debt with private banks saying the country was broke. The
government resumed payments a year later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
