<DOCNO> AP890803-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FugitiveScientist     08-03 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fugitive Scientist,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stump Sentenced to 5 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former chemist for Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory who was a fugitive for 20 months was sentenced
to five years in federal prison Thursday for swindling the
government out of $250,000.
   Ronald Stump, 50, also was ordered to repay the government his
$125,000 share of the money he got by faking a test result on an
electronic device bought by the U.S. Department of Energy.
   ``He does not fall into the category of a career criminal, yet
he participated in a very serious fraud,'' said U.S. District Judge
John Vukasin, who imposed the sentence sought by the prosecutor.
Vukasin described Stump as ``a very clever man, also very
manipulative.''
   Stump worked at the laboratory for 25 years before disappearing
in April 1987. He was arrested in December in Chandler, Ariz. The
FBI said he went to Mexico and worked as a water ski instructor and
bicycle tour leader at a resort before heading for Arizona.
   The FBI also said Stump held a top-level security clearance but
was not doing classified weapons work at the lab. ``There was no
reason to believe any (threat to) national security'' by Stump,
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Rodolfo Orjales.
   Stump pleaded guilty to making a false statement involving a
test report he submitted to the lab in March 1983. It said a device
called a mass spectrometer was effective in analyzing radioactive
tritium.
   Stump has admitted that he split the $250,000 price with Quantum
Mechanics Corp., seller of the spectrometer. He also pleaded guilty
to tax evasion. No charges were filed against the company, whose
owner died in 1985.
   Orjales said the device never worked. Assistant Federal Public
Defender Debra DeLambert, Stump's lawyer, disagreed, saying Stump
was working with the spectrometer at the lab before he disappeared.
   ``He recognizes that he abused the trust Lawrence Livermore
Laboratory put in him,'' DeLambert told the judge, urging him to
put Stump on probation. Stump also made a brief statement, saying
he was sorry.
   Orjales also told the judge there was evidence Stump defrauded
the government of an additional $60,000 for various types of
equipment bought by the lab. In addition, Stump did not tell the
truth to investigators when asked whether other employees knew
about procurement fraud, the prosecutor said. No charges were filed
in connection with those allegations.
   Since the fraud, security has been tightened at the lab, and the
problem appears to have been solved, Orjales told reporters.
</TEXT>
