<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings 1stLd-Writethru a0751 08-03 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: New throughout, raising doubts of senators and adding closing
arguments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators expressed doubts Thursday about
claims of innocence from U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Miami as a panel of 12 lawmakers in his impeachment trial finished
gathering evidence against him.
   ``I just have problems fitting together your actions,'' Sen. Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn., said as lawmakers asked their final questions
of the 52-year-old jurist accused to taking part in a $150,000
payoff plot.
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., chairman of the panel, expressed
doubts about the judge's explanation of how information may have
found its way from his Miami courtroom to a Washington lawyer
soliciting a bribe. He added: ``It seems to me this is a major
problem in our ability to believe your case.''
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said he wondered if documents
Hastings offered in an effort to refute claims by prosecutors were
``an after the fact contrivance.''
   Lawmakers and lawyers stayed late Thursday for closing arguments
to enable the 12-member Senate panel to wrap up its work a day
before the scheduled start of the congressional recess, which will
last through Labor Day.
   A report on weeks of hearings by the panel is to be prepared for
offering to the whole Senate to lay groundwork for a vote on
removing Hastings from the federal bench and depriving him of his
$89,500 annual salary.
   Hastings was impeached by the House a year ago on charges of
plotting with Washington attorney William Borders to obtain a
$150,000 bribe, lying to a jury that acquitted him in 1983 and
improperly disclosing wiretap information.
   Borders, who unlike Hastings was convicted in the case, has
refused to testify before the panel. Lawmakers say the
once-politically influential attorney is risking jail for contempt.
``Here's a man who literally walked the corridors of the White
House,'' Lieberman remarked.
   In their closing arguments, prosecutors from the House of
Representatives battered away at Hastings' explanation that he knew
nothing of any bribery plot and that Borders claimed to be able to
influence his actions as a way of drumming up business.
   They said there was too much evidence to explain away and that
the explanations are not plausible. For example, Borders boasted to
an FBI undercover agent masquerading as a convicted racketeer that
he could make Hastings appear in any restaurant on any day and time
of the ``racketeer's'' choosing.
   Hastings did appear on schedule in the main dining room of the
Fontainebleu hotel in Miami Beach at 8 p.m. on Sept. 16, 1981. The
judge says Borders had merely invited him there for a social
meeting.
   Prosecutors note that the attorney set the time and place
without consulting Hastings, the judge made a reservation for two _
himself and a woman companion, and that he made little if any
effort to hunt for Borders when the attorney failed to show up.
   ``The tangled web of Alcee Hastings now unravels in the Senate
of the United States,'' declared Rep. George W. Gekas, R-Pa., as
congressmen prosecuting the case made their closing arguments.
   Attorney Terence Anderson, defending Hastings, struck at what a
number of senators have conceded to be the circumstantial nature of
the evidence.
   ``This is a man who in my view is touched with greatness,''
Anderson declared. ``And you must decide _ are you satisfied _ is
there that degree of certainty on this occasion that you are
willing to say he should be thrust aside and consigned to infamy?''
</TEXT>
