<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     08-03 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Romania,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Recalls its Ambassador to Protest TV Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania has recalled its ambassador to
Budapest for consulations to protest a interview broadcast by
Hungarian television with exiled Romanian King Michael, state radio
said Thursday.
   The report did not say when Romania's ambassador, Traian Pop,
would return to Budapest.
   The move marked a blow to already strained relations between the
two Warsaw Pact countries over alleged discrimination against the
1.7 million-strong Hungarian minority in Romania.
   Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu also opposes Hungary's
economic and political reforms.
   Romania said the interview, part of which was broadcast on July
31, included ``anti-Romanian, anti-socialist and fascist-type
attacks against the independence and sovereignty of Romania.''
   The Hungarian Foreign Ministry said in a statement reprinted by
the state news agency: ``It is unacceptable that statements made by
the Hungarian media are viewed in Bucharest as reflecting official
Hungarian views.''
   Hungarian television on July 31 carried an excerpt from its
interview with the exiled monarch. The full program is scheduled to
be broadcast within the next two weeks.
   ``I have always, as a monarch, supported human rights and
restored the 1923 (Romanian) Constitution,'' which strengthened the
role of Parliament and stipulated some rights and freedoms, King
Michael said in a part of the interview in Romanian.
   ``The present leadership in Bucharest is an absolute monarchy, a
dynasty the members of which all rule at the same time, bleeding
the country dry.''
   The implication was that, by contrast, his was an enlightened
monarchy.
   King Michael toppled Romania's pro-Nazi leader Gen. Ion
Antonescu in 1944 and signed a peace treaty with the Allies. But
the communist-dominated government forced him to abdicate in 1947.
   The interview was recorded two weeks ago at King Michael's
residence outside Geneva.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
