<FIRST>r a AM-AutoSales 1stLd-Writethru a0847 08-03 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0847,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late July Car And Truck Sales Lag</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf, `August sales ..., to CORRECT to 1990, sted
1989, models.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks sagged
5.5 percent in late July, and July sales of foreign-made vehicles
dropped 9.6 percent, compared with the same periods last year,
automakers reported Thursday.
   Despite the Big Three automakers' continued incentive programs,
their car and light truck sales fell 7.4 percent to an average
daily rate of 37,113 in the July 21-31 period, from 40,096 in late
July 1988.
   Late-July average daily sales for the eight companies producing
cars and trucks in the United States were 41,004, compared with
43,394 in late July last year. For the month, domestic car and
truck sales were up 0.9, an average daily sales pace of 39,512
vehicles, compared with 39,163 in July 1988.
   July sales of imported cars and trucks slipped 9.6 percent to an
average daily rate of 31,260 vehicles, compared with 34,590 in July
1988.
   ``The incentives have had less and less impact,'' said Joseph
Phillippi, an automotive analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York. ``This is a tired market.''
   For the first seven months of the year, domestic car and truck
sales drooped 3.9 percent, while imported car and truck sales were
10 percent behind the same period of 1988.
   Last year was the second-best sales year in automotive history,
and the late-July sales rate was slightly above the average for
that year.
   Chrysler had the sharpest decline in car sales in late July this
year, a 15.5 percent drop to a daily rate of 3,049, from 3,611 a
year earlier. Chrysler car sales for the first seven months of 1989
were down 14.8 percent.
   GM said its late-July cars sales were down 13.1 percent to a
daily rate of 11,640 from a 13,394-a-day pace in that time last
year. GM car sales were down 8.9 percent for the year to date.
   Ford reported only a 0.2 percent decline to a daily rate of
7,860 for late July, from a rate of 7,873 a day in late July of
1988. Car sales for the first seven months of the year were down
2.4 percent, Ford said.
   For light trucks, GM said sales dropped 8 percent in late July
and 3.1 percent for the first seven months; Chrysler reported a 7.5
percent drop for the period and a 0.8 percent decline for the year
so far; and Ford said truck sales were off 3 percent for late July
and 3.1 percent for the first seven months.
   August sales may pick up, Phillippi said, as shoppers try to
avoid price increases coming when 1990 models are introduced in the
fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
