<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PlayboyChannel     08-03 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Playboy Channel,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playboy Folds Cable Channel to Launch Pay-Per-View Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Playboy Channel, the troubled
cable-television arm of Playboy Enterprises Inc., will be folded in
December and replaced with a new pay-per-view television service,
Playboy announced Thursday.
   Playboy also announced that it will launch a new one-hour
European television show this fall, titled ``Playboy Late Night.''
Because European broadcast standards are less stringent than those
in the United States, the magazine-formatted show will include
nudity but no explicit sex.
   Playboy has already reached agreements in principle with
television companies in Italy, France and Spain for ``Playboy Late
Night,'' said Christie Hefner, Playboy's chairman and chief
executive officer.
   ``The name of game we think is to find multiple outlets for
product,'' Hefner said. ``And because Playboy has differentiated
product and a global trademark, we're in a pretty good position in
that regard.''
   Hefner said that launching a pay-per-view service with an entire
evening's entertainment for a flat fee was more economical than
retooling the company's struggling pay-subscription cable channel.
   ``There is much more opportunity for us by running a Playboy
service as a pay-per-view service than as a subscription service,''
she said. ``It's pretty obvious that the cable industry is not
perceiving the pay-subscription business as a growth business. No
one is launching new pay-subscription services.''
   Hefner said that the new Playboy service will be available in
2.5 million homes with pay-per-view capability, making Playboy the
third-largest pay-per-view service.
   The Playboy Channel, launched in November 1982, claims 400,000
subscribers, said Playboy spokesman Bill Farley. It has been
plagued by a high ``churn'' rate, in which cable subscribers sample
the service but drop it.
   Hefner said that Playboy's pay-per-view will run 10 hours a
night and feature original programming and ``quality'' R-rated
movies such as ``Crimes of Passion'' and ``Betty Blue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Guatemala     08-03 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishops Alarmed At Deterioration of Political Situation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic bishops in this Central
American nation said Thursday that because of the political
violence coupled with labor unrest, ``Day by day Guatemala is
falling more deeply into chaos.''
   ``The paralyzing of essential services such as mail, telegraph,
education and public works (and) the violent death of a noted
politician are signs of a profound breakdown of the national
situation,'' the bishops' statement said.
   They recalled the bleak days of the early 1980s, when political
slayings by the hundreds and the military's bloody campaign against
foes or suspected foes of the government made Guatemala an
international pariah.
   ``Remembering the vivid horrors of only a few years ago and in
fear of returning to those tragic days, we turn to God in
humility,'' the bishops said.
   ``The only civilized way to find just and equitable solutions is
a frank, sincere and respectful dialogue.''
   About 50,000 government employees, including teachers and postal
workers, have been on strike for nearly two months for higher
wages. President Vinicio Cerezo has rejected the demands, saying
the government doesn't have the money.
   The strike has closed public schools nationwide and brought mail
service to a halt. Daily demonstrations by strikers have snarled
traffic in the capital and blocked border crossings into Mexico.
   The strike and the violence that followed it have raised fears
about the stability of Guatemala's fledgling civilian government.
   Cerezo's inauguruation in 1986 came after more than 30 years of
military or military-dominated rule in Guatemala. He has survived
two military coup attempts in 14 months and said recently he was
the target of a right-wing assassination plot.
   In the past few weeks, dozens of bombings and bomb threats and
several killings have hit this nation of about 9 million people,
including the slaying Tuesday of Danilo Barillas, a leader in the
governing Christian Democratic Party.
   Students sympathizing with the strikers on Thursday freed the
rector of the University of San Carlos, Roderico Seguro, and about
50 other university officials after holding them hostage for 24
hours.
   Hector Adolfo Cifuentes, the university secretary, said none of
the hostages were harmed.
   Fourteen public school teachers also ended an 18-day hunger
strike in Guatemala City's main plaza outside the National Palace.
   Mario Guillermo Munoz, a strike leader, told reporters they
ended their fast because ``they had made their point.'' The 14, on
the verge of collapse, were given first aid by Red Cross volunteers
and rushed to the hospital.
   Negotiations continued between strike leaders and government
officials without Cerezo, who walked out early Wednesday, saying he
was ``fed up.''
   Education Minister Ricardo Gomez Galvez said he was optimistic
about reaching an accord. Striking teachers said in a statement
they might consider going back to work if the government reinstated
500 fired strikers.
   The military on Thursday blamed Sunday's shooting death of
refugee leader Marco Juan Baltazar on leftist rebels.
   Baltazar represented repatriated Guatemalans on the National
Reconciliation Commission set up to discuss an end to the
27-year-old civil war, which has displaced tens of thousands of
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
