<FIRST>s i BC-50YearsOn-Recovery Adv13   08-03 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-50 Years On-Recovery, Adv 13,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scars Still Visible on the Rubble-to-Riches Miracle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-50 Years On-Legacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At times, Adolf Hitler's legacy is
painfully visible across the landscape of Western Europe.
   Other times you must look twice and you will still not see it,
so far-reaching has been Western Europe's transformation from
rubble to riches.
   In West Berlin the black, stunted steeple of the Kaiser Wilhelm
Gedaechtniskirche has been deliberately left unrepaired as a
reminder of the war, while the rest of the city is full of posh
shopping centers and traffic-choked streets.
   Young skiers and model airplane enthusiasts atop the Teufelsberg
could easily forget that the 360-foot hill is a pile of
grassed-over bomb rubble.
   London's East End, heavily bombed in the war, is now the site of
Europe's largest urban redevelopment project, although work is
occasionally delayed when an unexploded German bomb is discovered.
   The Dutch, Belgian and French coast lines are dotted with
fortifications the Nazis built against an attack from the West. But
many others were removed to make room for seashore apartments,
hotels and amusement parks.
   Near the southern Dutch town of Den Bosch, a former
concentration camp has been transformed into a housing project.
   Europeans older than 50 can still remember digging makeshift
homes out of the rubble, eating dogs and cats, begging GIs for
chocolate bars.
   Whole towns were flattened. London alone endured 57 consecutive
nights of bombing during the Blitz in which 15,000 people died.
   Today, the 320 million West Europeans enjoy a standard of living
surpassed in the West only by the United States.
   The economic jumpstart for the post-war miracle was U.S. aid
through the Marshall Plan and other programs, which by 1952 had
poured $45 billion into Europe.
   It was followed, in 1957, by the creation of the European
Economic Community.
   Now comprising 12 countries _ Britain, France, West Germany,
Italy, Spain, Portugal, Greece, Ireland, the Netherlands, Belgium,
Luxembourg and Denmark _ the EEC accounts for 20 percent of world
trade, compared with 13 percent for the United States and 12
percent for Japan.
   More important than statistics, however, is the fact that by
interweaving their economies, the Western Europeans have made war
among themselves unthinkable.
   The road to European integration is littered with disputes about
everything from farm prices to the color of the European passport.
But the success story is still being written.
   The EEC's internal borders are scheduled to come down by 1992,
creating a single, tariff-free trading bloc. This is to be followed
by monetary union, including a central bank and, eventually, a
single European currency.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
