<FIRST>s i BC-50YearsOn-Press Adv13   08-03 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-50 Years On-Press, Adv 13,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outbreak of War: What the Papers Said</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-50 Years On-Legacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening shots of what would become the world's most
devastating war wasn't enough to displace the classified ads that
filled the front page of The Times of London in those days.
   ``AT WAR WITH GERMANY,'' the headline proclaimed, spread over
two columns _ on page 8.
   Two days earlier, readers of Moscow's Izvestia had to turn to
page 4 to find a terse piece on the German invasion of Poland, on
Sept. 1, 1939, the start of a war that eventually would claim at
least 14 million Soviet lives. The headline: ``MILITARY ACTION
BETWEEN POLAND AND GERMANY.''
   On the same day, the Nazi party newspaper, Voelkischer
Beobachter, hardly made plain what was behind the German invasion.
   ``THE FUEHRER ANNOUNCES THE STRUGGLE FOR THE RIGHTS AND SECURITY
OF THE REICH,'' said the red-ink banner headline. ``Counterattack
has started,'' added a smaller subtitle, reflecting German
propaganda claims of Polish border violations.
   Some commentators on both sides thought the conflict could be
contained.
   Said a wishful editorial in the Koelnische Zeitung of Cologne:
``The voluntary confinement of our strategy ... and the respect of
Belgian, Dutch, Luxembourg and Swiss neutrality by Germany could
make it easy for London and Paris to let the German-Polish conflict
pass as a local dispute.''
   In Paris, Le Temps commented: ``We are certain that the
government will do everything to avoid a catastrophe, if this is
possible. The entire country stands behind it to fight ... for the
freedom of the peoples and its own independence but it is ready,
too, to listen to all voices that may still be raised in favor of
appeasement.''
   But The New York Times warned against further yielding to the
Nazis:
   ``The German government has used its strategic position in the
center of Europe to blackmail the small countries on its borders.
It has used every sign of hesitation on the part of its larger
neighbors, every offer of mediation on their part, and every
gesture of good will as a wedge for ever greater demands and
threats and seizure.''
   The Times of London had led the British press in calling for the
appeasement in the 1930s. But now it had no doubts:
   ``Britain and France will not cease from war until the defeat of
Hitler and their duty to themselves and the civilization have been
fully and finally accomplished. They have entered upon the war
without illusions. No setbacks, no sacrifices will turn them from
that end.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
