<FIRST>s i BC-50YearsOn-Chronology Adv13   08-03 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-50 Years On-Chronology, Adv 13,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-50 Years On-Legacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the major events leading up to
the outbreak and spread of World War II:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1939</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 23 _ The Nazi-Soviet non-aggression pact, signed by Foreign
Ministers Joachim von Ribbentrop of Germany and Vyacheslav Molotov
of the Soviet Union, carves Eastern Europe into spheres of
influence.
   Aug. 25 _ Britain and Poland sign a mutual assistance treaty.
   Sept. 1 _ Germany invades Poland.
   Sept. 3 _ Britain and France declare war on Germany, but refrain
from full-scale operations for nine months in what becomes known as
the ``Phony War.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1940</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   May 10 _ Winston Churchill replaces Neville Chamberlain as
British prime minister.
   May 26-June 4 _ British and French soldiers are evacuated from
Dunkirk in the face of German forces advancing across the
Netherlands and Belgium.
   June 16 _ French front collapses, leading to armistice six days
later.
   July 10 _ Start of the Battle of Britain, a 12-week aerial
struggle that frustrates Hitler's plans to invade Britain.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1941</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   June 22 _ Germany invades the Soviet Union.
   Dec. 7 _ Japan bombs the U.S. fleet in Pearl Harbor, bringing
the United States into what is now a world war that will continue
until mid-1945.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
