<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Israel-Viruses Adv07   08-03 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Israel-Viruses, Adv 07,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Aug. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scientists Report Progress In Creating Immune Farm Animals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM RON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers who created gene-engineered cells
immune to a class of viruses that causes foot-and-mouth disease and
diarrhea say it could lead to farm animals that are hereditarily
immune to such diseases.
   Researchers Yehudit Chebat and Michel Revel of the Weizmann
Institute of Science reported that they have created a gene that
immunizes cells, and that they have produced a line of
virus-resistant hamster cells.
   Cells were rendered immune by introducing an altered gene, which
triggered the production of anti-viral enzymes, Revel said. ``The
next step is immunizing a whole animal'' through a genetic
engineering process known as transgenics.
   That entails removing a newly fertilized egg from an animal,
inserting the altered gene and reinserting the treated egg into a
foster-mother. The newborn animal would be expected to have the
immunizing gene throughout its body.
   It will then posses a genetically inspired resistance to a class
of viruses called picornaviruses, which cause diseases such as
polio and the common cold in humans. The animal would pass on this
immunity to its offspring.
   Commercial production of virus-resistant animals, which may
prove ethically controversial, is years away.
   ``his type of genetic engineering is also theoretically possible
with humans,'' Revel said. ``But it would be ethically
inconceivable to attempt such an experiment.''
   Until now, the only genes that produced anti-viral enzymes were
those treated with interferon, a protein known for its
virus-fighting abilities. The newly created gene operates without
prompting from interferon.
   The altered gene, known as the 258-synthesis, is also unique in
that it does not adversely affect the normal activities of the
cell, a hurdle that had previously proved insurmountable, the
researchers said.
   Revel predicted that with adequate funding the research team
would be able to produce a fully resistant farm animal in two to
five years.
   Similar research involving a different virus of the influenza
family is being conducted at the University of Munich's Center for
Molecular Biology. The 2-year-old project uses similar techniques
to genetically modify mice.
   That experiment has proved inconclusive because the hoped-for
resistance has not been strong enough, said Ernst Winnacker, the
Munich center's director. In addition, creating genetically altered
animals has aroused considerable controversy in West Germany,
Winnacker said. ``We have a series of self-imposed guidelines on
genetic research. The West German Cabinet recently recommended that
these guidelines be made into law.''
   The limitations, unlikely to take effect for two years, would
not affect research under way, he said, adding he has no doubt
``commercially producing genetically altered farm animals will be
extremely controversial.''
   Amos Shapira, an expert on bio-medical ethics at Israel's Tel
Aviv University, said stringent precautions should be observed by
the scientists in cases where altering genes are involved. He
advocated limiting altered animals to the laboratory for several
generations to study potential side effects.
   Revel said the genes used in his experiment are taken from a
human.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
