<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv07   08-03 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 07,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Aug. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>East Coast To Get Good View of Aug. 16 Lunar Elipse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After missing out on the last 14 lunar
eclipses, North America on Aug. 16 will get its first glimpse in
seven years of the Earth's shadow slowly advancing across the face
of the moon.
   Recent lunar eclipses have been visible only from the Eastern
Hemisphere because that was the side of Earth facing the moon, or
they have begun before moonrise or ended after the moon set,
astronomers say.
   ``For the past seven years, we've been in the wrong place for
all 14 lunar eclipses,'' said University of Florida astronomer
Billy Cooke. This time, ``we happen to lie smack dab where you want
to be to see the whole darn thing, and it will be a spectacular
sight.''
   The East Coast will have the best view of the eclipse, which is
expected to turn the moon orange or blood-red at its peak. Viewers
on the West Coast will be able to see only the tail end of the
eclipse.
   The full moon will darken slightly beginning at 8:23 p.m., and
will be its most brilliant from 10:20 to 11:56 p.m. ``Skywatchers
will be able to see the earth's shadow taking bites out of the
moon,'' Cooke said, ``But instead of being black where the bite is
the moon will glow orange or red.''
   Earth's atmosphere bends light onto the surface of the moon,
causing the orange-red color, he said.
   Unlike solar eclipses, lunar eclipses can be watched with the
naked eye, as well as through binoculars or telescopes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Study Links Teen Sunburn, Later Melanoma Skin Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Girls who get bad sunburns as teen-agers double
their risk of dangerous melanoma skin cancer later in life, a new
study shows.
   ``Sunbathing should be recognized as a potentially hazardous
behavior,'' conclude Brigham and Women's Hospital researchers. The
findings add to growing evidence that sunburn during childhood and
adolescence is especially dangerous.
   The study found that teens who got five or more blistering
sunburns between ages 15 and 20 had twice the risk of melanoma as
those who avoided bad burns.
   It turned up no evidence of a link between blistering sunburns
after age 30 and skin cancer, but researchers cautioned that this
doesn't mean unlimited sunbathing is safe for older people.
   The analysis, directed by Dr. Martin A. Weinstock, was based on
130 women with melanoma who participated in Harvard Medical
School's long-running Nurses' Health Study.
   The doctors recommended that people try to stay out of direct
sun between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m., when the sun is strongest, and
cover up with clothing and sunscreen. They noted that the incidence
of melanoma is increasing rapidly and is likely to exceed colon
cancer among people born after 1950.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 7</NOTE>
