<HEAD>Job Cuts In The Cards At J.P. Morgan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan &amp; Co., which has suffered declining
profits in the first two quarters of this year, says it plans to
trim its work force through 1990.
   But the nation's third-largest banking company refused to
comment Wednesday on a report in Wednesday's Wall Street Journal
that it wants to cut 10 percent of its work force, or 1,500
employees, over the next 18 months.
   The newspaper quoted an unidentified Morgan executive as saying
that percentage was accurate.
   ``Our normal policy is not to comment on the planning process,''
said Kathleen Baum, a Morgan spokesperson.
   Baum said that as part of regular planning goals Morgan senior
managers have been asked to address ways to boost earnings,
including a reduction in employees.
   ``The goal is to bring about a broad-based reduction in head
count and take into account normal attrition and turnover,'' Baum
said.
   ``At the same time, we expect to continue to increase staffing
certain busineess, including the underwriting and trading of
corporate debt securities in the United States ...,'' she said.
   Last month Morgan reported second-quarter earnings of $206.3
million, down 10 percent from the same period a year ago. In the
first quarter its profit fell 36 percent.
</TEXT>
