<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Oil-IRS     08-03 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil-IRS,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon, Texaco To Challenge IRS Claims For $1.1 Billion In Back Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has billed Exxon
Corp. and Texaco Inc. for more than $1.1 billion in back taxes but
both of the huge oil companies said they would challenge the claims
in court.
   The claims concern oil the companies purchased from Saudi Arabia
a decade ago at prices below those set by the OPEC oil cartel, and
in turn sold to refiners at those lower prices.
   Texaco's claims could total nearly $1.8 billion, including $863
million in back taxes and $925 million in interest, while Exxon
said Wednesday it was being billed $269 million in back taxes but
declined to give an interest figure.
   ``They're trying to get us to pay for something we never earned
and which the American public benefited from,'' said Exxon
spokesman Bill Smith. ``We sold oil at lower prices. The American
public got the benefit of those lower prices.''
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., said the company
``vigorously disputes the IRS's interpretations of the law and will
contest the agency's position.''
   The IRS had notified Texaco about possible claims stemming from
the earlier oil transaction with the Saudis during an audit last
year in connection with Texaco's Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization.
   The claims are based on an IRS theory concerning the handling of
crude oil purchased from Saudi Arabia during 1979-1981, when the
official price set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries was $34 per 42-gallon barrel.
   Saudi Arabia, OPEC's largest exporter, was selling its crude for
$28 a barrel to Texaco, Exxon, Mobil Corp. and Chevron Corp., its
four partners in the Arabian American Oil Co.
   One provision of the arrangement was that if any of the
companies resold the oil, they could not resell it at a profit.
   Texaco said the IRS apparently believed that when it resold the
crude to its foreign affiliates, it should have charged the $34
rate despite the restrictions by Saudia Arabia _ and paid taxes on
the difference.
   Because it did not, Texaco said it is being held liable for
taxes on the profits that its foreign affiliates made by being able
to sell refined products made from the cheaper Saudi oil.
   ``The IRS is saying `you have used too low a price in
calculating your profit. ``You've calculated according to a ($28)
oil price but really it should be ($34).' That's all the IRS is
saying,'' said Paul Ting, analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   IRS officials have declined to comment on the matter, saying
federal law prohibits the agency from commenting on the affairs of
any taxpayer.
   Analysts said it was not unusual for the IRS to contend that a
multinational company had wrongly booked to its foreign affiliates
revenue that actually should be attributed to the parent, and
therefore taxed in the United States.
   ``Texaco maintains that the IRS's position is wrong and that it
cannot tax the company for revenues it never received when it
resold the Arabian crude oil and which, under mandate of the Saudi
Arabian government, it could not receive,'' the company said in a
statement.
   Texaco began setting aside reserves to cover its possible
liability last year when the IRS notified the company that it could
owe back taxes.
   Exxon also was notified of possible tax claims but said at the
time that it would not set aside any money because it believed the
new IRS theory was flawed and that if the IRS did lodge a claim it
would be dismissed by the tax court.
   Both companies said current reserves were adequate to cover any
tax liabilities stemming from the claims.
   Exxon said Wednesday it filed a petition in U.S. Tax Court late
last month challenging the IRS claim after being notified June 29
that it owed the taxes. Texaco said it planned to file a formal
challenge within 90 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Mexico-Economy     08-03 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Economy,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Announces Tax Breaks to Attract Capital, Low-Priced Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government has announced tax
breaks to lure back money that investors took abroad to escape
Mexico's financial crisis and made a deal with auto manufacturers
to offer low-priced compact cars.
   A recent agreement on reducing the $107 billion foreign debt
``has generated confidence in Mexico and desire among many
investors to repatriate their capital,'' the Treasury Department
said Wednesday in a statement.
   The measures apply to capital returned to the country after Jan.
1, 1989.
   Officials hope the debt reduction agreement signed with foreign
creditor banks last month will ease economic uncertainty and
stimulate the private investment needed to revive Mexico's stagnant
economy.
   The agreement gives the more than 500 creditor banks the options
of writing off 35 percent of Mexican debt, lowering interest rates
to 6.25 percent or granting Mexico new loans. It covers $53 billion
of the debt, which is the second-highest in the developing world
after Brazil.
   Under the Treasury Department decree, deposits abroad over the
past three years earned no taxable income.
   It establishes a 3.7 percent tax on deposits or investments made
abroad in 1985 and a 5 percent tax for those made before 1985. The
maximum income tax for private indivduals is 40 percent.
   A second decree Wednesday provides tax exemptions for low-priced
compact cars and imported component parts used to make them. It
applies to cars that sell for no more than $5,500 and use low-lead
gasoline.
   ``The high prices of vehicles are outside the reach of most
national consumers,'' the decree said.
   Volkswagen, whose popular ``beetle'' is the lowest-priced
Mexican-made car, immediately took advantage of the new regulation,
setting its new price at $20 less than the $5,500 limit and $1,377
below its previous price.
   Morgan Guaranty Trust, one of Mexico's main creditor banks,
estimates that $84 billion in capital left the country between 1977
and 1987, but a private economist estimated the figure at about $50
billion.
   Capital flight began when, after years of stability, the peso
currency was devalued against the U.S. dollar in late 1976.
   In 1982, over-borrowing abroad and falling oil prices quickly
deflated the country's oil boom. Mexico could no longer keep up
with its foreign debt payments and the currency began a slide.
   In late 1982, about 70 pesos were equal to one U.S. dollar but
that rate is 2,500 to one today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
