<DOCNO> AP890803-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Princeton-Newport Bjt   08-03 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport, Bjt,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendants Ordered to Forfeit $3.8 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six defendants convicted of racketeering in
the landmark Princeton-Newport securities fraud case must forfeit a
total of $3.8 million, significantly less than what the government
wanted, a jury ruled.
   Federal prosecutors had asked that the defendants relinquish
salaries and other interests of more than $21 million.
   The largest forfeiture amount decided Wednesday, $3 million, was
against James Sutton Regan, a former partner in Princeton-Newport
Partners LP, a defunct securities house.
   His partnership interest was placed at $13.3 million and his
salary at $1.75 million.
   Four other defendants were each ordered to forfeit $200,000.
They are former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader Bruce Lee
Newberg, and former Princeton-Newport partners Charles M. Zarzecki,
Jack Z. Rabinowitz and Paul A. Berkman.
   The sixth defendant, former Princeton-Newport controller Steven
B. Smotrich, must forfeit $1,245.85, the jury ruled.
   ``We thought that what the government asked for was
exorbitant,'' said juror Michelle Rodriguez.
   Another juror, Judith T. Larabee, said she was not comfortable
having to decide the forfeiture question.
   ``It is just very difficult for a lay person, no matter what
their education and background, to assess something like forfeiture
when you are dealing with such large sums of money,'' she told The
New York Times.
   Defense attorneys, who have said they will appeal the
conviction, argued that the forfeiture the government sought was
excessive and violated the constitutional ban on cruel and unusual
punishment.
   After the forfeiture verdict, Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark
Hansen said he planned to file a motion that said the defendants
were liable under the racketeering statute to forfeit all the
partnership interests and salary that the government sought.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Carter indicated that he agreed.
   ``I'm definitely going to rule that way if the government makes
a motion,'' Carter said. ``In my view, the partnership interest is
totally forfeitable.''
   The judge then softened his remarks by saying he would review
the matter when both sides submitted written arguments.
   On Monday, the jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
convicted the defendants after a five-week trial of racketeering,
racketeering conspiracy, conspiracy and numerous counts of mail and
wire fraud.
   The jurors returned to court to consider forfeiture because the
federal anti-racketeering law allows it.
   The case marked the first time securities professionals were
accused of racketeering under the controversial law aimed at
combating mobsters and drug pushers. The Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations law provides heavy fines and lengthy prison
terms.
   The trial received widespread attention because it grew
indirectly out of the Ivan Boesky insider-trading scandal that
rocked Wall Street three years ago.
   ``We're pleased with the verdict because we hope it sends a
strong message to the securities industry that the Justice
Department is committed to a course of vigorous enforcement,'' said
U.S. Attorney Benito Romano.
   When asked about criticism of use of the racketeering statute in
this case, Romano said, ``We will use the RICO statute where
appropriate. We never viewed the RICO statute as being on trial in
this case.''
   The government had sought $2.5 million from Newberg and the
following forfeiture from the other defendants: Zarzecki, $1.1
million partnership interest and $267,483 in salary; Rabinowitz,
$791,191 partnership interest and $454,507 in salary; Berkman,
$762,613 partnership interest and $558,328 in salary; and Smotrich,
$124,583 in salary.
   The case involved a series of prearranged stock transactions
between 1984 and 1986. The government alleged that the defendants
illegally bought and sold stocks to generate phony tax losses.
   The case overlapped the government's 98-count fraud and
racketeering indictment of former Drexel junk-bond chief Michael
Milken. Much of the same evidence is expected to be introduced at
Milken's trial, scheduled to begin in March 1990.
   Princeton-Newport, based in Princeton, N.J., and Newport Beach,
Calif., went out of business after the indictment was brought last
August. Defense lawyers said at the time that the charges alone,
though unproven, destroyed the firm's ability to do business.
   Besides forfeiture, the defendants face up to 20 years in prison
on each of the two racketeering counts, three to five years for the
other charges, and fines. Carter scheduled sentencing for Oct. 16.
</TEXT>
