<FIRST>r f PM-Coke-Hispanic     08-03 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coke-Hispanic,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Plans New Hispanic Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. plans to salute Hispanic
contributions to American culture with a new advertising campaign
featuring such prominent Hispanic-Americans as actress Rita Moreno.
   The campaign, which will be coordinated with local bottlers in
five markets with large Hispanic populations, is being tied to the
1992 quincentenary celebration of Columbus' landing in America,
officials said Wednesday.
   The campaign is the latest example of the increasing importance
major advertisers are placing on reaching the fast-growing
population group.
   Coca-Cola officials declined to say how much they planned to
spend on the three-year effort but said it would be in the millions
of dollars.
   According to government figures, there are about 19 million
Hispanics in the United States, with buying power exceeding $130
billion a year.
   Hispanic Business magazine has estimated that the 50 leading
Hispanic market advertisers spent $550.1 million to reach Hispanics
in 1988, up 12 percent from $490.7 million in 1987.
   Top-ranked was Procter &amp; Gamble Co., at $20.8 million.
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola and its arch-rival, Pepsico Inc. of
Purchase, N.Y., have also ranked among the heaviest spenders aiming
at Hispanics.
   Coca-Cola ranked 25th on the magazine's list with spending of
$1.6 million aimed at the Hispanic market in 1988.
   Pepsico, which also has snack food and restaurant operations,
ranked 15th with $2.9 million in spending, Hispanic Business said.
   Pepsi spokesman Jeff Brown said the company is currently running
commercials featuring the Latin pop rock performer Chayanne on
Spanish-language television. He declined to say how much Pepsi is
spending to reach Hispanics, however.
   The first ads in the Coca-Cola's ``Discovery '92: Heritage and
Future'' campaign were to run this week in the New York market,
where Coca-Cola Bottling Co. of New York planned to place them
first on Spanish-language TV stations.
   English-language versions also are planned, as well as ads in
both Spanish and English for the radio, print and outdoor media,
officials said.
   The New York ads feature one of five prominent Hispanics from
the area who recount their difficulties and persistence in
achieving success in fields such as classical music, ballet, social
services and state government.
   In one ad, film scholar Richard Pena recalls how his
grandparents took him to Spanish-language movies when he was young.
He said he remains grateful for their guidance and thinks of them
whenever he selects films in his role as head of the program
committee for the New York Film Festival.
   At the end of each commercial, an announcer says, ``Coca-Cola
Classic salutes all Latinos for 500 years of contribution to our
America.''
   A specially-designed logo appears at the end of each ad showing
the outlines of three white sailboats against a blue background
atop red and white swirls that evoke the design of the Coca-Cola
Classic label.
   Yvonne ``Bonnie'' Garcia, director of Hispanic Consumer Markets
for Coca-Cola USA, said similar campaigns will be aired in the
Chicago, Miami, California and Texas markets featuring prominent
Hispanics from those areas starting next year and running through
1992.
   In addition, she said, a national version of the campaign
featuring Rita Moreno will be run on broadcast and cable networks
in 1990.
   Coca-Cola Co. is headed by a Latino. Its chairman and chief
executive, Roberto C. Goizueta, is from Cuba.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
