<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: version also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched up today against the
Japanese yen after a three-day decline, and the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's main index fell.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 119.53 points, or 0.34
percent, finishing at 34,779.81. It had gained 0.88 points
Wednesday.
   The dollar closed at 136.40 yen, up 0.20 yen from Wednesday's
136.20-yen close. In the previous three days, it had fallen a total
of 3.25 yen.
   Traders said currency trading was thin as the market awaited
Friday's scheduled release of U.S. jobless data for July.
   The dollar was pressured by predictions of further U.S. interest
rate declines, said Toru Kanai, foreign exchange analyst at New
Japan Securities Co. Lower U.S. interest rates make the dollar less
attractive to foreign investors.
   On the stock exchange, Masahiro Umemori, an analyst with Nomura
Securities, said, ``Following the index's rapid rise, surpassing
the 35,000-point mark yesterday, investors started to sell issues
for fear that prices had gone too high.''
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 500
million, down from Wednesday's 800 million.
