<DOCNO> AP890803-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0738EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-FarmScene     08-03 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Spent More in '88 to Raise Crops, Livestock</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers spent $118.4 billion in 1988 on
animals, feed, labor, machinery and other items needed to raise
crops and livestock, the Agriculture Department says.
   The 1988 figure represented a 7.5 percent increase over the
$110.1 billion spent in 1987, the department said Wednesday in the
report, ``Farm Production Expenditures.''
   Still, the figure falls short of the record $131.8 billion
farmers spent in 1981, just before the general financial crunch
that stalled expansion in the nation's agricultural sector.
   Annual spending by farmers reached its nadir this decade in 1986
_ $106 billion _ when many massively cut back their capital
investments during a time of plummeting land values and rising debt
burdens.
   Average expenditures per farm were $54,956, an increase of
$4,165 from 1987. The top 16.8 percent of farms _ those with annual
sales of $250,000 or more _ accounted for more than 68 percent of
the total expenditures.
   The figures suggest that raising livestock is a big-time
investment.
   Feed was the highest single cost item at $17.9 billion in 1988,
accounting for 15.1 percent of total costs. The previous year, feed
cost $14.9 billion and accounted for 13.5 percent of expenses, the
highest single expense item that year as well.
   The livestock and poultry that devour that feed cost $13.6
billion, accounted for 11.5 percent of the total. The previous
year, the cattle, swine and poultry cost $10.7 billion, accounting
for 9.7 percent of the total.
   Farmers bought $3.9 billion worth of agricultural chemicals in
1988, about the same amount and percentage as the previous year;
about the same percentage and dollar amount of fertilizer, lime and
soil conditioners, $6.9 billion worth; and the same percentage and
dollar amount of seeds and plants, 3.7 billion. Those items
accounted for 12.3 percent of the total.
   The machinery to do farm work cost $11.5 billion, for 9.7
percent of total expenses, up from $10.9 billion.
   A composite category _ farm services, including rent, _ was the
largest, $24.6 billion or 21 percent of the nation's production
expenses. That's up from $24 billion in 1987.
   That category includes cash and share rent, vet supplies and
services, marketing and storage expenses, insurance, utilities,
leasing and transportation.
   The only expenses to fall were interest, which decreased 3.7
percent to $8.37 billion, and building and fencing, which fell 10.3
percent to $2.23 billion.
   The analysis dealt only with production expenditures and did not
include figures for net income or profits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China and India together produce more than
half the world's rice, but both are importing huge amounts this
year, the Agriculture Department says.
   China is forecast to become a net importer of rice for the first
time in recent history, the department said in a report released
Wednesday.
   The report, ``Rice: Situation and Outlook Yearbook,'' says
demand in China, Indonesia and India will bring trade this year to
a record 13.4 million metric tons, surpassing the 1981 high of 13.1
million metric tons.
   China imports rice to feed its urban populations. The 1990
forecast says farmers will keep more rice on the farm because of
the government system of paying farmers with IOUs that can't be
redeemed immediately.
   China is expected to buy 1.2 million tons of rice this year from
all sources, the report said. That is triple the amount bought the
previous year.
   ``It is unclear how or if the current turmoil in China will
affect its short-term rice trade,'' the report said.
   Indonesia is expected to import 400,000 tons and India will
likely take in 500,000 tons in 1989 as they try to replenish stocks.
   Although the United States will increase its exports 10 percent
this year, to 2.5 million metric tons, Thailand will be the big
winner, exporting a record 5.5 million metric tons.
   World rice prices soared to $8.91 per hundredweight in July,
after having fallen to $5.90 in December.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Asia, especially Japan and Korea, are
major buyers of U.S. fruit juices, the Agriculture Department says.
   The foreign agriculture service said Wednesday that shipments of
horticultural products such as fruits, juices, nuts, vegetables and
hops to points other than Canada were valued at $252 million in May.
   That was is up 3 percent from April and 4 percent from May 1988,
the agency said.
   Shipments to East Asia accounted for 64 percent of fruit juices
exports, with Japan receiving the bulk.
   Canada is the primary market, accounting for 60 percent of total
horticultural exports.
</TEXT>
