<FIRST>r f PM-EnginePlant     08-03 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Engine Plant,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan to Produce Australian Company's Engine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan officials and an Australian
industrialist have joined together to build a smaller, more
fuel-efficent engine that could herald a new phase for the auto
industry.
   Orbital Engine Co. of Perth, Australia, will convert a former
General Motors Corp. plant in Tecumseh at a cost of $250 million to
build a three-cylinder engine, Gov. James Blanchard said at a news
conference at Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn Wednesday. The plant
will employ 700 people.
   The engine uses 30 percent less fuel, is 40 percent as large as
a conventional engine and would cost $80 to $200 less each to
produce, according to Ralph Sarich, president and founder of
Orbital who developed the engine.
   ``This is a very appropriate setting because what you see here
is an amazing invention,'' Blanchard said.
   The engine is a major advance in engineering technology that
could make all engine technology obsolete, Blanchard said.
   Operating with two strokes instead of the standard four, the
engine is quieter, lighter, more fuel efficient, cleaner burning
and cheaper to produce than conventional engines, Sarich said.
   Treasury Secretary Robert Bowman said the state has invested $5
million from its pension fund in the project.
   ``This is not a social investment, we expect to make a great
deal of money,'' Bowman said.
   The state also will provide job training and start-up
assistance. The plant, owned by GM, will be leased to Orbital by
the Lenawee County Development Corp., Orbital said in a written
statement.
   Conversion of the Tecumseh plant would begin in 1990, Commerce
Director Doug Ross said, with production of a marine engine getting
under way in 1992. Production of the auto engine is scheduled to
begin in late 1993 or early 1994, Sarich said.
   The Australian entrepreneur credited the state's aggressive
pursuit of the project with his decision to build here.
   Members of the Commerce Department traveled to Australia in 1986
to recruit the company.
   ``We believe it was essential to work with an organization with
the same ambition and dynamics as us,'' said Sarich, whose said his
company has $480 million in capital.
   Sarich Technologies Ltd., which owns Orbital, has licensing
agreements with Ford Motor Co., GM, Walbro Corp., Outboard Marine
Corp. and Brunswick Corp. Marine Division.
   Sarich said Ford and GM assisted in testing the engine.
   ``There's no sophisticated industry in Perth,'' Sarich said,
referring to the area as ``bamboo country.''
</TEXT>
