<DOCNO> AP890803-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 0958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-China-Economy     08-03 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Economy,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>China to Crack Down on Tax Evasion by Private Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has announced it will inspect the
nation's 14.5 million private businesses in a bid to recover almost
$5 billion in revenue lost through tax evasion.
   The State Taxation Bureau will check the books and tax
registrations of private industrial, commercial and service
enterprises in August and September for signs of tax evasion or
other illegal activities, Chinese newspapers reported Wednesday.
   About 70 percent to 80 percent of all private businesses evaded
a total of more than $4.94 billion last year, far exceeding the
$2.53 billion in tax revenue collected, the bureau said.
   ``What is more serious is that a few lawbreakers attack tax
collectors and prevent them from carrying out their duties,''
stated the Communist Party newspaper, the People's Daily.
   The inspections are intended to establish a ``clear-cut order
for private business people to fulfill their obligations to the
state,'' said tax bureau director Jin Xin.
   Jin said illegal businesses would be closed and illegal income
confiscated.
   Private companies in China are required to pay 52 percent of
their profits to the government as taxes and to reinvest 30 percent
in business expansion, leaving only 18 percent as income for the
owners, he said.
   The inspections are part of an effort to more strictly regulate
China's small private sector, which is flourishing at the expense
of state-owned firms, Jin said.
   At the end of last year, there were 14.5 million private
businesses employing more than 23 million people in China.
   The government also is cracking down on corrupt tax collectors,
who are prohibited from accepting gifts from tax-free and
tax-reduced businesses to help ``ensure an honest and clean
government,'' the official Xinhua news agency said.
   Employees of the tax bureau are not allowed to go on junkets or
hold meetings in tourist spots, live in luxurious hotels during
inspection trips, build luxurious office buildings or apartments,
host banquets or send gifts, Xinhua said.
   The restrictions are part of a national anti-corruption drive
triggered by the student democracy movement that was crushed in
June after drawing hundreds of thousands of supporters with such
slogans as, ``oppose corruption.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1009EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Plessey     08-03 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Plessey,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>GEC, Siemens Make Bid $3.3 Billion For Plessey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG on
Thursday made a fresh offer for Plessey Co. PLC that values the
British electronics company at 2 billion pounds, or about $3.3
billion.
   The $4.46-a-share offer followed Wednesday's news that the joint
bidders had reached an agreement with the British government on
conditions for a renewed bid.
   Plessey had no immediate comment, a secretary said.
   The new offer replaces an original $2.8 billion bid that
automatically lapsed in January following the government's decision
to investigate the impact the combination would have on competition
in Britain's electronics industry.
   Plessey shares sank 20 cents a share to $4.36 on London's Stock
Exchange following the news.
   In a statement, the West German and British electronics giants
said they ``believe that Plessey on its own lacks the resources and
capability to sustain, let alone improve, its profitability over
more than the short-term.''
   The Department of Trade and Industry cleared the companies to
bid for Plessey provided they agreed to several conditions intended
to preserve competition in the defense electronics industry.
   GEC and Siemens have pledged that GEC won't take any interest in
the Plessey radar, military communications and traffic controls
businesses. Originally the companies had planned for GEC to take a
35 percent interest in Siemens' defense interests after the merger.
   The two also agreed to make available the technology on the
Joint Tactical Information Distribution System, a project for which
Plessey and GEC were competing. The British defense ministry
insisted on this measure in hopes of encouraging a new company to
take up Plessey's role as a rival developer.
   The companies also agreed that Siemens, as the potential owner
of the Plessey defense companies, would name only British citizens
directors of the units and that Siemens employees given access to
sensitive Plessey defense contract work would undergo British
security clearance procedures.
   Apart from the defense-related areas, GEC and Siemens plan to
take equal shares in Plessey's electronic components and other
businesses. GEC also intends to make Siemens a minority partner in
its existing telecommunications joint venture with Plessey, GEC
Plessey Telecommunications.
   GEC is not related to the similarly named U.S. company.
</TEXT>
