<FIRST>r f BC-Belgium-Coins     08-03 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Belgium-Coins,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgium To Issue New ECU Gold Coin Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The royal mint will issue a series of
four gold coins denominated in European currency units next
December, the mint's director said Thursday.
   Director Romain Coenen said the mint has received instructions
from the Finance Ministry to produce the ECU coins using gold
reserves held by the Banque Nationale de Belgique.
   Coin sales are expected to result in a $71 million profit for
the treasury, newspapers said. The ECU is a marker for the
currencies of the 12-nation European Community.
   The series will include a one-ounce, 100-ECU coin bearing the
image of Austrian Empress Marie-Therese valued at $112.
   Similar one-ounce gold coins, such as the American Eagle and the
Canadian Maple Leaf, currently trade for about $383.
   A half-ounce, 50-ECU, or $56 coin, depicting the European ruler
Charlemagne will also be minted, as well as a quarter-ounce,
25-ECU, or $28 piece of Roman Emperor Diocletien.
   The lowest denomination coin will be a one-tenth ounce _ 10-ECU,
or $11.20 piece with an image of Charles V.
   The mint plans to produce 160,000 of each type of coin.
</TEXT>
