<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern     08-03 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Signs $210 Million Sales Agreement with Midway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines plans to seek federal bankruptcy
court approval of an agreement to sell routes, gates and aircraft
to Midway Airlines for $210 million.
   The agreement is part of the Miami-based carrier's strike
recovery plan, the companies announced Wednesday. Eastern plans to
seek the approval within 10 days.
   The sale involves gates at Philadelphia International Airport
and Eastern routes from Philadelphia to Montreal and Toronto. The
deal also includes operating slots at Washington's National Airport
and New York's LaGuardia Airport, 16 DC-9 jetliners with spare
engines and parts.
   Eastern has begun a restructuring that includes the sale of $1.8
billion in assets, including the sale to the Chicago-based Midway,
to emerge from bankruptcy court as a smaller carrier.
   The two carriers reached a tentative agreement on the package in
mid-June, about six weeks after the disabling strike by Eastern
machinists forced the carrier to file for financial reorganization.
Midway arranged the financing for a closing this fall.
   ``This is part of our asset-disposition program,'' said Eastern
spokesman Robin Matell. ``We said that we would be disposing of
$1.8 billion in assets, so this is a fairly significant component
of that program.''
   At a public meeting of creditors in New York Wednesday, an
Eastern attorney said the company still expects to reorganize and
emerge from bankruptcy protection by the end of the year.
   ``This has not been a usual case from the outset. It's been an
extremely accelerated case,'' said Bruce Zirinsky, a bankruptcy
attorney for Eastern. ``At this time, we still think it's
realistic,'' he said, to come out by year's end.
   More than 1.2 million meeting notices were sent to creditors and
ticket holders. About 60 people attended the session in the Felt
Forum auditorium at Madison Square Garden, which seats around 4,500.
   A contingent of non-union employees from Eastern's reservations
center in Woodbridge, N.J., wanted to know if they would receive
outstanding overtime payments and other benefits.
   Also on Wednesday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland
approved the pilots union's request that its pay claims against
Eastern be submitted to arbitration. The company's liability could
be as much as $250 million in back pay, according to the union.
   ``The pilots still have to prove their claim, and we don't
believe that they will,'' Matell said late Wednesday.
   Eastern succeeded in boosting its daily flights to 350 Tuesday
as part of its strike-recovery plan. Eastern's first service to Rio
de Janeiro started Wednesday, and three flights are scheduled each
week, Matell said.
   The number of scheduled flights is 60 percent higher than last
month and about one-third of the pre-strike level.
   Eastern's reorganization plan filed July 21 proposed full
repayment to creditors and ticket holders totalling around $3.3
billion. Consumers would have the option of either a cash refund or
tickets for new flights.
</TEXT>
