<FIRST>r f BC-Ferruzzi-Soybeans     08-03 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ferruzzi-Soybeans,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferruzzi Drops Suit Against Board of Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian grain company has dropped its lawsuit
challenging a Chicago Board of Trade order that may have prevented
the firm from cornering the U.S. soybean market, exchange officials
said today.
   But the Italian concern, Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA, said its
withdrawal of the U.S. District Court lawsuit was ``a technical
matter only'' and that it is still preparing a suit seeking
compensation for the losses it incurred as a result of the Board of
Trade's order.
   Ferruzzi has denied trying to corner the market.
   The suit had sought to bar the exchange from enforcing its July
11 order requiring all traders to reduce their holdings in the July
soybean futures contract.
   U.S. District Judge James Zagel in Chicago denied the request on
July 13 and the July soybean contract expired on July 20, rendering
the lawsuit moot.
   Ferruzzi said it withdrew the lawsuit on Tuesday.
   ``Withdrawing the suit, which applied to an act governing a
period which is now over, is a technical matter only,'' the company
said in a statement.
   Nevertheless, the Board of Trade hailed the action as a victory,
saying the exchange ``welcomes this action, which demonstrates the
integrity of futures market self-regulation at the Board of Trade.''
   Prior to the Board of Trade's order, Ferruzzi said it held
contracts to take delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans, while
Board of Trade officials said that at the time, only about 12
million bushels of soybeans were available for delivery against
those contracts.
   Ferruzzi, one of the world's largest soybean processors, has
denied trying to corner the market, saying it needed all the
soybeans it had contracted to buy in order to keep its plants
running and meet the demand for its products.
</TEXT>
