<FIRST>r f BC-American-Aeroflot     08-03 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-American-Aeroflot,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Talks to Soviet Airline About Access</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two American Airlines vice presidents
met with officials of the Soviet national airline Aeroflot in
Moscow last month about gaining access to the Soviet air travel
market.
   American spokesman John Hotard said Wednesday the American
executives involved in the meetings were Hans Mirka, vice president
for international services, and Arnold Grossman, vice president for
international marketing and planning.
   ``They went over there and had some very good meetings with
Aeroflot, but it's too early to say what will come of it,'' Hotard
told The Dallas Morning News.
   Aeroflot is the largest airline in the world; American is the
biggest U.S. carrier.
   In June, Aeroflot launched its first major marketing campaign in
the United States and increased its flights from New York and
Washington to Moscow from five a week to eight. The Soviets also
plan to build about 25 new hotels in the next two years to handle
an increase in foreign tourists.
   The U.S. government last month turned down American's request
for the right to fly from Chicago to Moscow. Pan Am Corp., which
flies from New York to the Soviet capital in a joint venture with
Aeroflot, is the only U.S. airline authorized to fly to Moscow.
   ``If you don't have route authority, you have to look for ways
to get around that,'' Hotard said.
   The two airlines may set up an arrangement under which American
would buy a set number of seats on Aeroflot flights from, for
example, New York to the Soviet Union. American could then sell the
seats to travelers making connections from American flights to New
York.
   Likewise, Aeroflot could buy seats on American flights from New
York to major U.S. cities not served by the Soviet airline.
</TEXT>
