<DOCNO> AP890803-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-RetailSales     08-03 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chain Stores Post Modest Sales Growth in July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's big retailers today reported modest sales gains
for July, continuing a trend that illustrates the weakness in
consumer spending.
   Results varied, with some store chains enjoying better business
than others, but industrywide the month was a ho-hum one for
retailers, said Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   Feiner said sales growth was ``in general modest and to a large
degree reflected the generally sluggish overall economic
environment.
   ``Importantly, slowing growth in employment, weak personal
income growth and continued relatively high interest rates have
continued to pressure consumer confidence,'' he said.
   Although July is normally a slow time for shopping, analysts
keep track of monthly sales figures from department stores,
discounters and general merchants for clues about consumer
behavior. Consumer spending supplies about two-thirds of the power
for total economic activity.
   In recent months, mediocre sales at many stores across the
country have signaled that consumers have reacted to rising
mortgage payments and increases in other credit costs by curtailing
shopping trips.
   With sales tallies coming in below expectations, retailers will
face extra pressure to capitalize on business during the rest of
the year as the peak shopping season gets into full swing. Shopping
usually picks up in August with back-to-school promotions and gains
momentum leading up toward Christmas.
   Many industry analysts don't expect fickle customers to do too
much damage to retailers' profitability because store managers have
been carefully controling expenses and keeping inventories of
unsold merchandise to a minimum.
   Store executives' reactions to their July performances ranged
from pleased to dissatisfied.
   Michael Bozic, chairman of the merchandise group at industry
leader Sears, Roebuck and Co., said business was adversely affected
by weakness in sales of durable goods, which are expensive items
that consumers typically refrain from buying when they are feeling
financially pinched.
   Bozic said Sears' sales this year were being compared against
fairly strong results last year, which made the percentage growth
appear weaker than it was.
   The pickup in sales at K mart Corp. stores that began in June
continued into July said, Joseph E. Antonini, chairman and chief
executive officer.
   K mart, the country's second-biggest retailer had suffered
through several disappointing months earlier this year when Sears
created a stir with its new everyday low-pricing policy to win back
market share from discounters.
   Kenneth A. Macke, chairman and chief executive of Dayton Hudson
Corp., a Minneapolis-based owner of department stores and discount
chains, said the retailer will report strong second-quartern
earnings later this month based on recently good sales growth.
   F.W. Woolworth Co.'s Chairman and Chief Executive Harold E.
Sells said domestic sales of the New York-based chain were
unexpectedly robust, partly due to seasonal promotions and solid
growth in childrens' wear.
   At stores owned by Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc., headquartered
in Los Angeles, sales were described as satisfactory by Philip M.
Hawley, chairman and chief executive. He said women's apparel
posted the best gains while cosmetics and women's accessories sold
well.
   The figures reported today were from major general merchandise
chains and apparel retailers. The government's monthly retail sales
report is more comprehensive, including sales at auto dealers,
supermarkets, restaurants and elsewhere.
   Here are some of the results:
   Sears said its sales edged up 0.4 percent in the four weeks
ended July 29 to $2.4 billion from $2.39 billion. But comparing
results at stores open at least a year, Sears' sales slumped 2.4
percent.
   Retailers and analysts consider these same-store or
comparable-store sales a more accurate reflection of a company's
performance than totals that include sales a newly opened stores.
   K mart, based in Troy, Mich., said its July sales rose 6.2
percent to $2.07 billion from $1.95 billion a year earlier.
Comparable-store sales were up 2.7 percent.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the third-biggest U.S. retailer based in
Bentonville, Ark., said July sales rose 24 percent to $1.98 billion
from $1.59 billion. Same-store sales gained 10 percent.
   Dayton Hudson's July sales rose 15.6 percent to $896 million
from $775 million in the year-ago month. Comparable-store sales
were up 6.9 percent.
   Carter Hawley Hale's July sales rose 4.9 percent to $180.7
million from $172.3 million in July 1988. The same-store sales
growth was 4 percent.
   Woolworth's July domestic sales went up 9.7 percent to $339
million from $309 million a year earlier. Same-store sales rose 4.8
percent.
</TEXT>
