<HEAD>Crop Futures Decline In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were modestly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting a variety of bearish factors topped by forecasts for
more rain in the Midwest.
   The National Weather Service issued a six-to-10 day forecast
late Wednesday calling for above-normal rainfall over much of the
Midwestern soybean and corn growing areas during the middle portion
of next week.
   Weak cash markets prompted further selling of corn and soybean
futures, traders said.
   News that the Italian grain processor Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA
had dropped a lawsuit against the Board of Trade also weighed on
soybean prices. The action suggests Ferruzzi may reduce its soybean
holdings rather than risk another confrontation with the exchange.
   The lawsuit challenged an exchange order requiring traders to
reduce their holdings in the July soybean contract, which expired
on July 20, rendering the lawsuit moot. The order was seen as a
move to prevent Ferruzzi from cornering the soybean market.
   Wheat futures were lower in sympathy with the corn and soybean
markets.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.88\ a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.20 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to } cent lower with September at $1.32} a bushel.
soybeans were 1\ cents to 5\ cents lower with August at $6.03 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August
at 73.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .20 cent
higher with August at 83.67 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with August at 46.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .08 cent to .28 cent higher with August at 26.20 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
