<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishAirways     08-03 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Airways ,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways' Profit Up 17 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC said its fiscal year got off
to a good start with a 17 percent gain in its first-quarter profit.
   The airline reported Thursday that its net profit for the three
months ended June 30 was 62 million pounds, or about $102 million,
compared with 53 million pounds, or $87.5 million, in the same
period a year earlier.
   Per-share earnings rose to 8.6 pence, or 14 cents, from 7.4
pence, or 12 cents.
   First-quarter revenue rose 14.7 percent to 1.17 billion pounds,
or $1.9 billion, from 1.02 billion pounds, or $1.7 billion.
   British Airways was privatized by the Thatcher government in
February 1987.
   ``We have made a competent takeoff into our new financial year
but as we fly through our peak season, we are aware of a small
patch of turbulence,'' said the airline's chairman, Lord King.
``There may be further softening of the economy, we must take
further action to control our costs and we must alert ourselves to
increasing competition.''
   King noted that the year-earlier results were depressed by the
acquisition of rival British Caledonian Airways. He said British
Caledonian was still being integrated into British Airways'
structure.
   Capacity on scheduled flights was limited to an increase of only
2.4 percent, largely because of late delivery of new Boeing 747-400
aircraft, British Airways said.
   The airline said it is still holding discussions on taking a 20
percent share in Sabena World Airlines of Belgium. KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines also is expected to take a 20 percent share in Sabena,
according to a preliminary plan, with the remaining 60 percent to
be held by the Sabena SA holding company.
</TEXT>
