<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Midland     08-03 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Midland,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midland Posts Loss; Lambastes Brady Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midland Bank PLC on Thursday posted a $632 million
loss for the year's first half after boosting its provisions for
losses on loans to Third World countries.
   Midland, Britain's third-largest bank based on deposits,
increased its loan loss reserves by $1.4 billion, from $81 million
a year earlier and blamed a United States initiative for
encouraging delinquency among debtors.
   Among its peers, Midland has the greatest exposure to debts of
less developed countries.
   Losses totaled $632 million in the first six months of the year,
compared with a $295 million profit in the same period a year
earlier.
   Pre-tax profit before exceptional provisions was $520 million,
little changed from $516 million a year ago. Total assets were up
by 17.6 percent to $108 billion, from $92 billion.
   Speaking at a news conference, Midland Chairman Sir Kit McMahon
criticized U.S. Treasury Secretary James Brady's Third World debt
initiative as ill-conceived and destabilizing.
   McMahon cited a ``greater reluctance of a number of debtor
countries to service their debt'' following the Brady Plan's
announcement in March.
   McMahon said the plan ``encouraged worse behavior by debtors''
since countries would delay payments amid expectations that their
debts would be reduced.
   McMahon echoed the sentiments expressed recently by the chairmen
of other top British banks, although his criticism was harsher.
   The Brady Plan calls for banks to design debt-reduction packages
for highly indebted countries that plan economic reforms. The
packages are to be supported, in part, by the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and Japan.
   The agreement between Mexico and its 15-bank advisory committee,
announced last week, marked the first breakthrough for the Brady
initiative.
   Under the accord, which covers the country's $52.5 billion of
commercial bank debt, banks can choose from three options: they can
exchange their loans for new 30-year bonds with a below-market
annual interest rate of 6.25 percent; or for bonds with a discount
from face value of 35 percent that have floating market rates. Or
they can provide new loans.
   McMahon said Midland would choose the second option, which would
cover $1.4 billion of its medium- and long-term loans to Mexico.
   ``We do this sadly because we do not believe in debt forgiveness
for debtors,'' he said.
</TEXT>
