<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     08-03 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.H. Whitney Negotiating Lower Offer for Prime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., under pressure from its banks,
said Thursday it has entered negotiations to reduce its $1.2
billion offer for Prime Computer Inc.
   After Prime, a Natick-based minicomputer maker, reported a $19
million quarterly loss last week, two of Whitney's banks asked it
to obtain additional financing.
   Whitney, a New York-based venture capital firm, indicated it has
been unable to find that financing at its current offer of $21.50
per share of Prime's outstanding common stock.
   ``Although we are willing to continue to seek financing at the
$21.50 level, we believe, based on our efforts to date, that such
financing will probably not be available from our current financing
sources on a basis satisfactory to all financial participants,''
said Don E. Ackerman, a Whitney partner.
   Prime spokesman Joseph Gavaghan confirmed that the companies are
negotiating possible changes in their June 23 merger agreement but
declined to comment on how much the price might drop.
   Prime's board of directors agreed to the merger with Whitney
while fending off a hostile, $970 million bid from MAI Basic Four
Inc. of Tustin, Calif.
   MAI, a computer firm controlled by New York investor Bennett S.
LeBow, has since offered to buy Prime's minicomputer business for
$525 million.
   Wall Street analysts said if Whitney cuts its offer
significantly, LeBow might be able to launch another bid for all of
Prime.
   ``It's like an on-going soap opera on TV. It doesn't go away,''
analyst Jay Stevens of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. said of the long
takeover battle, which began with MAI's offer last November.
   An MAI spokeswoman in New York said it had no immediate comment
on Whitney's announcement.
   Prime, which has 11,200 employees worldwide, reported revenue of
$1.6 billion last year, about one-third from minicomputers. The
company also produces computer-aided design and manufacturing
systems, a business that was enlarged substantially when Prime
acquired Computervision Inc. for $435 million in a hostile takeover
last year.
   As the minicomputer industry faces a general slump, Whitney's
banks apparently believe Prime needs more financing to withstand
continuing losses and turn itself around.
   Stevens said he is ``very concerned about the survivability of
Prime'' but believes it has a better chance of returning to
profitability if it remains whole than if the minicomputer business
is sold separately.
</TEXT>
