<HEAD>London Shares Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended slightly lower Thursday as the
market struggled to find direction in a crosscurrent of conflicting
signals.
   A price-cutting exercise by market makers, poor company earning
reports, and new weakness in the pound combined to depress buying
interest, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended down
1.5 points, or 0.06 percent, at 2,306.3, below a session high of
2,310.3. At its lowest, the index touched 2,298.0, a fall of 9.8
points.
   Volume was 550.1 million shares, up from 424.8 million shares
Wednesday.
   News of a renewed, 2.04 billion-pound ($3.4 billion) bid by
General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG for Plessey Co. PLC, and a
slight upturn on Wall Street, helped support the market at lower
levels.
   Dealers said selling pressure remained minimal. ``Any decent
line of stock up for sale at a reasonable price sells pretty
quickly,'' one trader said.
