<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies
in Europe Thursday on fears over the hostage situation in the
Middle East.
   Gold prices moved up in quiet European trading after falling in
Asia.
   Dealers said it was unclear how far the dollar would rise on the
news of American ships moving to the Middle East.
   Some speculated that traders were talking the dollar up ahead of
Friday's release of U.S. unemployment figures for July. If the
figures prove disappointing, traders will be cushioned from a sharp
fall in the dollar by its already higher levels.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose .20 yen to close at 136.40 yen. Later
in London, the dollar traded at 136.40 yen.
   The pound was down even though the Bank of England entered the
market to support their sagging currency, dealers said. The pound
traded at $1.6475 Thursday, down from $1.6635 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.8650 West German marks, up from 1.8505; 1.6065 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5915; 6.3192 French francs, up from 6.2695; 2.0950 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0895; 1,338.00 Italian lire, up from 1,332.00;
1.1715 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1755.
   Gold traded in London late Thursday at a bid price of $369.75 a
troy ounce, up from $368.25 late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold was little changed in moribund trading after a
two-day holiday. The closing price was $369.00 a troy ounce, up
from Monday's close of $368.25.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell 40 cents an ounce to close at
$370.05.
   Silver was trading in London at $5.23 a troy ounce, down from
$5.27 an ounce late Wednesday.
