<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0339</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, following
through on Wednesday's advance after some early hesitation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 16.32 points
Wednesday, rose another 3.79 to 2,661.23 by 3 p.m. Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 796 up, 647 down and
516 unchanged.
   The Commerce Dpartment reported that the index of leading
economic indicators dipped 0.1 percent in June, following a
downward-revised drop of 1.3 percent the month before.
   Analysts had been forecasting a decline of 0.2 percent to 0.3
percent for June. They said the actual figure had little apparent
impact on the market, leaving significant questions unanswered
about the economic outlook.
   The debate continues among market analysts over whether slowing
growth will lead to a relatively benign ``soft landing'' or
something with more severe effects on the pace of business and
corporate profits.
   Walt Disney jumped 6| to 121\ in active trading. The company
said this week it will to double the capacity of its new theme park
in Orlando, Fla. The stock has also been buoyed lately by takeover
speculation.
   Elsewhere among the blue chips, International Business Machines
rose } to 113{; American Express ] to 38[; Union Carbide [ to 28{,
and Philip Morris 1| to 164[.
   Ashland Oil rose } to 38\; Nicor gained 1\ to 39{, and Oracle
Systems, traded in the over-the-counter market, was up 1 at 16].
   The three were added to Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock composite
index, prompting buying by index funds set up to duplicate the
performance of that measure of market trends.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.25 to 192.03. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .74 at 376.22.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 141.77 million shares with an
hour to go.
