<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-03 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge To 20-Month Low; Selling Linked To Ferruzzi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plummeted to their lowest
levels in more than 20 months Thursday on the Chicago Board of
Trade on selling linked to the Italian grain merchant Ferruzzi
Finanziaria S.p.A.
   Traders said several brokerages that are believed to have close
ties to Ferruzzi were heavy sellers in the soybean pit.
   The sell-off followed news that Ferruzzi had dropped a lawsuit
it had filed against the Board of Trade challenging the exchange's
July 11 order requiring traders to reduce their holdings in the
July soybean contract.
   The order was widely perceived as a move to prevent Ferruzzi
from cornering the U.S. soybean market.
   But a federal judge had denied Ferruzzi's request for an
injunction and the July soybean contract expired on July 20,
rendering the lawsuit moot.
   Ferruzzi was believed to have complied with the order by
shifting its huge market position from the July contract into the
August contract, which sustained the steepest losses Thursday.
   At the close, soybeans were 2 cents to 26\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in August at $5.82 a bushel, the lowest close
for a near-month soybean contract since Nov. 19, 1987.
   Wheat was 1} cents to 6 cents lower with September at $3.87 a
bushel; corn was 4 cents lower to 1\ cents higher with September at
$2.17{ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 3 cents higher with
September at $1.35} a bushel.
