<FIRST>u f AM-American-Miami     08-03 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American-Miami,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Eagle To Open Miami Hub</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines significantly boosted its
presence at Miami International Airport Thursday by announcing that
its commuter carrier, American Eagle, will open a hub at the home
base of strike-crippled Eastern Airlines.
   American Eagle President Robert E. Martens said the commuter
carrier plans to open the hub Oct. 1 with 20 flights daily from
Miami to the Florida cities of Key West and West Palm Beach. It
plans to expand to 66 a day by adding flights to Fort Myers,
Marathon and Naples, all in Florida, by the end of the year.
   The commuter service also will seek approval from the U.S.
government and the government of the Bahamas to schedule flights
from Miami to the Bahamian towns of Freeport, Marsh Harbour and
Treasure Cay.
   The announcement at a news conference at the airport marked the
latest in a series of moves by American, the nation's largest
carrier, to expand operations out of Miami, a market once dominated
by Eastern.
   American set up a pilot and flight crew base in Miami last
January, announced plans to expand in the market last April and
last week opened a new concourse at Miami International.
   ``By closely coordinating the Miami schedules of American Eagle
and American,'' Martens said, ``we are able to provide our
customers with the convenient connecting service that they have
come to expect from us.''
   Most of Eastern's flight attendants and pilots walked off the
job March 4 in support of striking Machinists, and the airline has
been under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection while struggling to
stay in the air as a smaller carrier.
   Eastern managed to boost the number of its flights Tuesday to
350, about a third of its 1,100 pre-strike daily flights. American
Eagle announced Thursday that combined American and American Eagle
flights from Miami should total 144 a day by the end of the year.
   Barbara Lind, manager of sales development for American Eagle,
denied that the Miami expansion of the commuter service and of
American was prompted by Eastern's weakened position.
   ``American has always planned to have a Miami hub,'' Ms. Lind
said. ``It has been part of our 5-year plan for quite a few years,
so it's not something that happened overnight because of the
misfortunes of Eastern Airlines.''
   The new connecting hub would mark the start of American Eagle
operations in Miami.
   American Eagle now serves 138 small and medium-sized cities, Ms.
Lind said, feeding passengers into major cities for American.
   She said American Eagle, which has acquired a 5,500-square-foot
passenger lounge at Miami International, has begun hiring for the
approximately 75 positions it expects to open in Miami.
   ``We would like to keep our hiring local to all of the cities
that we are opening,'' she said.
   Asked if American Eagle would hire striking Eastern employees,
Ms. Lind responded, ``yes, if they qualify.''
   She also confirmed American's interest in buying Eastern's
profitable Latin American routes, if the routes come up for sale.
   ``We would love to expand in Central and South America, and
Miami would be a perfect place to do that from,'' she told The
Associated Press.
   But both Ms. Lind and American spokesman Jim Brown, at the
carrier's Dallas headquarters, refused to say if American and
Eastern were negotiating such a deal.
   ``I'm afraid I can't comment on any specific negotiation,''
Brown told AP. ``We are a buyer of assets, of route authorities, a
buyer of gate facilities, a buyer of slots. Whenever a company
approaches us, we certainly listen to what they have to say.''
</TEXT>
