<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Plessey Bjt   08-03 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Plessey, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>GEC, Siemens Renew Bid For Plessey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG on
Thursday made a fresh, $3.4 billion bid for Plessey Co. PLC and
quickly boosted their stake in the British electronics company to
29.9 percent.
   Sources said the joint bidders spent $495 million snapping up
Plessey stock, bringing their holdings to the maximum allowed under
British takeover rules.
   Plessey rapidly rejected the offer as ``totally inadequate,''
saying the British and German electronics giants had made ``a major
price miscalculation.''
   Analysts conceded that the price was at the low end of Plessey's
recent trading range but noted that the joint bidders were likely
to be successful.
   The $4.46-a-share offer came one day after the British
government announced an agreement with the bidders on conditions
for renewing their bid for Plessey.
   The new offer replaced the original $2.8 billion bid that GEC
and Siemens launched in November. That bid automatically lapsed in
January when the government decided to investigate what impact such
a combination would have on competition within Britain's
electronics industry.
   The purchase of 113 million Plessey shares lifted GEC's and
Siemens' stake a further 15 percent, sources said. The bidders are
prohibited from buying more Plessey shares until after the first
closing date of their offer.
   On London's Stock Exchange, Plessey sank 15 cents a share to
finish at $4.41.
   Analysts said they were doubtful that Plessey could find a white
knight or devise an effective defense at this stage. But several
said the offering price might not be high enough to win over some
institutional shareholders.
   ``I'm surprised that they've made it a final offer,'' said John
Tysoe, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Securities in London.
   GEC and Siemens said they wouldn't increase the offer under any
circumstances, including the emergence of a counter-offer.
   In a statement, they said, ``Plessey on its own lacks the
resources and capability to sustain, let alone improve, its
profitability over more than the short-term.''
   But the bidders may have provided Plessey with a slight
possibility of fending off the bid as too low, Tysoe said.
   It ``does give Plessey the chance to wriggle away,'' said an
electronics industry analyst at a London brokerage firm, speaking
anonymously.
   Plessey Chairman Sir John Clark said in a statement: ``To have
offered such a low price for Plessey after an attempt which has
lasted almost nine months shows a total lack of understanding of
Plessey and of its immediate and long-term value to its
shareholders.''
   Plessey's strategy has been to criticize the lack of value that
the bidders have placed on Plessey's recent acquisition-driven
expansion into such areas as computer equipment as well the
company's core electronics businesses.
   It also has said that in trying to put together a merger plan
that was palatable to Britain's defense and trade ministries, GEC
and Siemens have come up with a contrived structure that has
``nothing to do with industrial logic.''
   The Department of Trade and Industry cleared GEC and Siemens to
bid for Plessey provided they agreed to several conditions intended
to foster competition in the defense electronics industry.
   Among other things, GEC and Siemens have pledged that GEC won't
take any interest in the Plessey radar, military communications and
traffic controls businesses. Originally the companies had planned
for GEC to take a 35 percent interest in Siemens' defense interests
after the merger.
   GEC is not related to the similarly named U.S. company.
</TEXT>
