<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     08-03 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hit New Record of $337.03 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 467 money market mutual
funds rose by $4.24 billion in the latest week to an all-time high
of $337.03 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday came despite
declining interest rates, which tend to make money market funds
less attractive than other investments.
   It broke the record set a week earlier, when the assets rose a
revised $1.86 billion to $332.79 billion, said the institute, a
Washington-based mutual fund trade group. That weekly gain
initially was reported as $1.85 billion.
   The institute said that in the latest week, assets of 231
general purpose funds rose $361.5 million to $106.32 billion,
assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $1.18 billion to $143.21
billion, and assets of 141 institutional funds rose $2.71 billion
to $87.50 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.47 percent from 8.60 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.64 percent from 8.73 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
42 days, up from 41 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.45 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.51 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, remained unchanged at 5.12 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.32
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.47
percent the previous week. Yields were 8.32 percent on 1-year CDs,
down from 8.47 percent; 8.23 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.35
percent; and 8.21 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.33 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
