<DOCNO> AP890803-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MedicalDevices 1stLd-Writethru f0152 08-03 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medical Devices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0152,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says FDA Negligent in Enforcing Reporting Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs FDA reaction for 5th graf pvs, `FDA spokesman...;
PICKS UP 6th graf pvs `Reps. John...; Also moved on general news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group said Thursday that government
regulators have been ``negligent and reckless'' in failing to
enforce a law requiring makers of medical devices to report deaths
and injuries associated with their products.
   Public Citizen Health Research Group said its analysis of Food
and Drug Administration documents found that manufacturers of
devices such as heart pacemakers, wheelchairs and breast implants
routinely ignore the reporting requirement and that the FDA has
failed to seek prosecution of the companies.
   ``The FDA has been negligent and reckless in not enforcing this
law,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of the health research
group. In addition, ``medical device companies are doing a reckless
and dangerous job in failing to report these deaths, injuries and
malfunctions,'' he said.
   FDA's inaction has meant that hazardous devices remain in use
``causing further needless harm to patients,'' the group said in
letters asking members of Congress to investigate the matter.
   The FDA, through spokesman Jeff Nesbit, said it ``does not agree
with Public Citizen's assessment.'' He said that while many of the
figures the group used are correct ``they have been incorrectly
interpreted as to the actual public health risk.''
   As to the delay Public Citizen cited between the time a company
is alerted to a problem and the FDA issues a reprimand, he said
that when FDA inspectors find a violation they inform the company
of it during the inspection. If the problem warrants a recall, the
FDA advises the company on the spot, he said.
   Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee, and Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the
panel's health subcommittee, cited the Public Citizen study in
announcing Thursday that they have introduced a bill to tighten the
reporting provision of the law.
   In addition to device makers, hospitals and physicians would be
required to report deaths and injuries associated with malfunctions.
   The documents obtained by Public Citizen through the Freedom of
Information Act contained the findings of routine FDA inspections
of medical device manufacturing companies between December 1985 and
June 1988.
   The documents also included letters, called Notice of Adverse
Findings, that the FDA sent to companies failing to report deaths,
injuries and malfunctions.
   Wolfe called the FDA letters a ``slap on the wrist.''
   ``I believe the general attitude at FDA is you treat industry as
your partner, not your adversary,'' Wolfe said.
   The law requires manufacturers of medical devices to report to
the FDA within five days a malfunction that results in death or
serious injury, he said. But the group's review found that an
average of eight months passed from the time the company was
alerted to a problem to its discovery by the FDA.
   Further, the group said, the FDA took an average of six months
to issue a reprimand.
   During the period reviewed, FDA inspectors found reports of at
least seven deaths, 109 serious injuries and 265 malfunctions and
one design defect, none of which had been passed on to the FDA,
Wolfe said.
   Also, 33 companies had failed to report device problems within
the required deadline, he said.
   The group found serious violations relating to 76 products, he
said.
   In one case, four infant deaths and four serious injuries were
associated with alarm failures on an infant respiration and
heart-rate monitor, the group said. In another, two deaths, a
serious injury and 178 malfunctions were linked to use of
intra-aorta balloon catheters, it said.
   Also, 21 serious injuries were associated with a pacemaker, and
at least 31 serious injuries resulted from leaking breast
prostheses, the group said.
   For violations that are shown to be deliberate, the law provides
for a fine of up to $10,000 and three years in prison. Violations
that are not deemed to be deliberate can be punished with a fine of
up to $1,000 and up to a year in prison, said Katherine Meyer, a
lawyer with the group.
   A General Accounting Office report in February said the FDA's
system for handling medical device reports was ``not adequate to
handle the volume of reports currently received.'' It pointed to
long delays in getting information into the system and analyzing
submitted reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1729EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe-Soybeans     08-03 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe-Soybeans,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Say Crooked Soybean Futures Traders Profited From Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Commodites Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES REINDL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year's drought devastated many Midwestern
farmers, but the federal government says crooked traders in the
soybean pits of the Chicago Board of Trade reaped illegal profits
from the parched fields.
   As the searing sun dried up soybean fields, concern grew over
how much damage the crop would suffer.
   The potential for profit was high enough for legitimate traders,
because fears of a scarce crop sent the price of futures contracts
skyrocketing. But the government says 19 traders in the chaotic
soybean pit wanted more.
   With orders to buy abundant and orders to sell scarce, the
crooked traders held sell orders off the open market and illegally
passed them to friends who profited, the government alleges.
   ``In those instances, the orders of thousands of other customers
were unfulfilled,'' said U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas.
   Traders later split the ``substantial profits'' realized from
the illegal trades, according to a federal indictment.
   In all, a federal grand jury returned indictments Wednesday
against 46 traders at the Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange alleging they systematically conspired to skim profits
from customer accounts and attempted to hide earnings from the
Internal Revenue Service.
   The indictments, the first stemming from a 2{-year
investigation, offer an insider's view of what the government says
were widespread fraud schemes in four trading pits at the world's
largest futures markets, where deals are made with a flash of a
hand signal and fortunes made or lost in the wink of an eye.
   In more than 700 charges, the government alleges 19 traders in
the frenzied soybean pit ran illegal schemes designed to cover
their losses and increase their profits.
   The indictment uses the colorful language of the trading pits to
describe the alleged scheme: Traders hold ``decks,'' or handfuls of
customer orders; ``bagmen'' are traders who agree to ``bagged,'' or
pre-arranged trades, that are used to cover theft.
   The government said traders used a variety of tactics to run
their scheme, including destroying trading cards and rewriting
cards to conceal illegal trading. The indictment alleged the
traders even kept account ledgers to record money due to and from
one another on illegal deals.
   The methods the government says Martin J. Dempsey used to handle
a losing day last year provide an example of one of the more common
frauds alleged in the indictments.
   Dempsey was charged with racketeering, conspiracy, 37 counts of
mail and wire fraud and 83 counts of violating the Commodities
Exchange Act.
   But on June 28, 1988, Dempsey's troubles amounted to a $70,000
personal trading loss.
   The government said he tried to shift the loss to other traders
and succeeded in laying off $34,000. But his willing accomplice was
undercover FBI Special Agent Richard Ostrom, posing as a crooked
trader.
   The scheme worked like this:
   A broker who wanted to offset personal losses would pre-arrange
trades with an ``accommodating trader'' and later repay the
``accommodating trader'' by misappropriating customer money.
   In Dempsey's case, the government said, he assured Ostrom that
he would repay him by offsetting the loss against previously
converted customer funds as well as through future thefts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1735EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-03 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices declined Thursday with
little news to drive the market forward.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
fell 7 cents to close at $18.21 a barrel after trading as high as
$18.50 during the session. The contract had finished 25 cents
higher on Wednesday. Contracts set for delivery later in the year
also declined.
   Refined oil products traded on the exchange also finished lower.
The September contract for unleaded gasoline closed down 0.19 cent
to 50.66 cents a gallon and heating oil for September delivery fell
0.42 cent to 49.12 cents a gallon.
   Other contract months also closed lower.
   Analysts said nervousness about the U.S. hostage situation in
the Middle East helped buoy prices early in the day. But once the
crisis passed, investor concern about excess oil returned.
   Traders have attributed some price strength in recent days to
investor concern that political events involving the U.S. hostages
could disrupt oil shipments from the Middle East.
   Gasoline and crude oil prices have weakened recently in the face
of slowing demand and growing inventories. Refineries are pumping
at over 90 percent capacity, the highest level in several years.
But high gasoline prices have softened demand.
   ``Fundamentally, there's just too much crude and product out
there,'' said James R. Fiedler, vice president in charge of energy
brokering for E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
