<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Coastal     08-03 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Coastal,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastal Second-Quarter Earnings Up 15 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. said Thursday its second-quarter
earnings, inflated by profits the company reaped from its failed
takeover of Texas Eastern Corp., rose 15 percent from the same
period last year.
   Net income for the three months ending June 30 were $35.3
million, or 58 cents per share, on revenue of $2.1 billion. That
compared to $30.6 million, or 50 cents per share, on $1.86 billion
in revenue in the comparable 1988 quarter.
   The 1989 earnings included a $32 million pretax gain realized
when Coastal tendered its shares of Texas Eastern, which spurned
Coastal's hostile takeover bid and instead agreed to merge with
Panhandle Eastern Corp.
   Coastal's operating profit was $148 million in this year's
quarter, compared to $156 million last year.
   Operating profit for natural gas, Coastal's largest profit
contributor on a segment basis, was $67.4 million for the second
quarter _ a decline from the $104 million posted a year ago.
   For the first six months, profits rose 24 percent to $95.7
million, or $1.58 per share, on revenue of $4.47 billion. Earnings
were $77.1 million, or $1.35 per share, on revenue of $4.22 billion
for the same 1988 period.
   Houston-based Coastal, a diversified energy firm with $8 billion
in assets, has operations in natural gas transmission and storage,
oil and gas exploration and production, refining and marketing,
coal, trucking and independent power production.
</TEXT>
