<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1823EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-03 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Tumble; Traders See Ferruzzi Selling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures plunged to a 20-month low Thursday on selling
linked to good growing weather, poor demand and apparent
liquidation of a large holding by Italian grain merchant Ferruzzi
Finanziaria S.p.A.
   On other markets, precious metals rallied strongly, energy
futures were lower; cattle were mostly higher and pork futures were
mixed.
   At the Chicago Board of Trade, soybeans for delivery in August
settled 26 cents lower at $5.82\ a bushel, the lowest settlement
for a near-month soybean contract since Nov. 19, 1987.
   Wheat settled 1} cents to 6 cents lower with September at $3.87
a bushel; corn was 4\ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with September
at $2.17\ a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 3 cents higher with
September at $1.35} a bushel.
   Forecasts for a continuation of near-perfect growing conditions
in the Midwest provided a bearish atmosphere for the soybean
market. But traders and analysts said the steep decline probably
was triggered by signs of weak demand and selling by Ferruzzi, a
leading European grain dealer that has had a large holding in
soybean futures.
   The slack market for soybeans and soybean meal also reflected a
reluctance among users to make large purchases ahead of the
September harvest period, when new supplies typically drive prices
down.
   Analyst Dale Gustafson of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said cash
soybean meal prices had dropped $2 to $4 a ton on Wednesday and the
futures market reacted from the opening bell.
   The sharp drop in August soybean prices occurred near the close
on heavy selling by Central Soya Co. and Refco Inc., thought to be
on behalf of Ferruzzi, which owns Central Soya.
   ``I think the trade suspects that, yes,'' said analyst Dale
Gustafson of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago a.
   One soybean trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, was
more certain.
   ``It was Ferruzzi that sold,'' he said. ``That pressured most of
the beans and meal and down we went.''
   Central Soya President David Swanson said the company was an
``aggressive'' buyer in the cash market but declined to comment on
futures market activities.
   Heavy selling by Ferruzzi would suggest the company is
liquidating its position in the August contract, possibly because
of the increased availability of supplies on the cash market.
   Earlier in the day, the Board of Trade announced that Ferruzzi
had dropped a lawsuit against the exchange challenging its July 11
order requiring traders to reduce their holdings in the July
soybean contract.
   The exchange's order was widely perceived as a move to prevent
Ferruzzi from cornering the U.S. soybean market.
   A federal judge had denied Ferruzzi's request for an injunction
on July 13 and the July soybean contract expired on July 20,
rendering the lawsuit moot.
   Ferruzzi was believed to have complied with the order by
shifting its huge market position from the July contract into the
August contract, raising the potential for another confrontation
before the contract's Aug. 22 expiration.
   Gold and silver futures posted strong gains on New York's
Commodity Exchange, despite a rise in the dollar's value against
other major currencies. Precious metals and markets usually move in
the opposite direction.
   The unusual behavior of gold and silver indicated the market was
reacting to the political tensions stemming from the threat to U.S.
hostages in Lebanon, said Jack Barbanel, director of futures
trading for Gruntal &amp; Co. in New York.
   Gold settled $3.50 to $3.70 higher with August at $373.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 7 cents to 7.2 cents higher with August at $5.296
a troy ounce.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 12 cents
lower with September at $18.21 a barrel; heating oil was .38 cent
to .48 cent lower with September at 49.12 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .16 cent to .32 cent lower with September at 50.66
cents a gallon.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled
unchanged to .25 cent higher with August at 73.55 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .10 cent to .45 cent higher with August at 84.07
cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .55 cent higher with August
at 46.52 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.05 cents lower
to .28 cent higher with August at 26.20 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
