<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NewsChannel     08-03 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-News Channel,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Satellite Viewers To Get News Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viacom Network Enterprises and Hubbard
Broadcasting Inc. announced Thursday they plan a 24-hour news
service for the home satellite TV market and local broadcasters.
   The news channel, scheduled to debut in late November, will
consist of continual newscasts modeled on the concept of all-news
radio.
   Showtime Satellite Networks will market the service to home
satellite dish owners. Conus Communications will produce the news
programming at its Twin Cities facilities in Minnesota.
   The service will draw on domestic news programs from the Conus
Satellite News Cooperative representing more than 130 TV stations
in the United States, Japan, Europe and Australia.
   Viacom, based in New York City, is a diversified communications
and entertainment company. Hubbard Broadcasting, based in
Minneapolis-St. Paul, is the managing general partner and majority
shareholder of Conus Communications.
   The news service was announced at the convention of the
Satellite Broadcasting and Communications Association of America.
</TEXT>
