<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1902EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     08-03 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sink in Spite of Government Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-term bond prices sank Thursday, driving
yields higher, even though a government report added to signs that
the economy might be slipping into a mild recession.
   A recession would be good for the bond market because it would
help squelch inflation, which erodes the value of interest-paying
securities.
   The Commerce Department said its Index of Leading Economic
Indicators edged down 0.1 percent in June. It was the fourth
decline in five months and renewed speculation that the longest
peacetime economic expansion may be at an end.
   Bond prices fluttered slightly higher after the figures were
released but sank later and ended with a substantial loss.
   The U.S. Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond fell 21-32 point, or
about $6.56 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from price, rose to 7.90 percent from 7.84
percent late Wednesday.
   Shorter-term bonds had smaller declines. The 30-year bond was
the biggest loser, evidently because of a threat by President Bush
to veto a savings and loan bailout in favor of his own plan.
   Bush's plan would bring a huge supply of long-term bonds from a
new agency onto the market to finance the savings and loan debt,
depressing prices. Many bond investors had speculated that Bush
would yield to Congress's plan, in which the money would be raised
with bonds of all maturities instead of just long-term ones.
   For the bond market, the threatened veto ``was the straw that
broke the camel's back,'' said Ward McCarthy of Stone &amp; McCarthy
Research Associates Inc.
   Also hurting bond prices was general nervousness that the
market's recent rally was overextended. Some traders saw unwelcome
signs of economic health in figures this week on auto sales, chain
store sales and new home sales.
   ``The market had run an awful long way in this rally and it was
beginning to get some cold feet,'' said William Griggs, a principal
in Griggs &amp; Santow Inc.
   Some traders were mildly concerned by the weakness in the
dollar. If the dollar continues to fall it could limit the Federal
Reserve's willingness to lower interest rates for fear of weakening
the dollar even more, said Hugh A. Johnson, a senior vice president
at First Albany Corp.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments were down between 3-32 point and 3-16 point,
intermediate maturities fell [ point to 7-32 point and long-term
issues were | point to 11-16 point lower, the Telerate Inc.
financial-information service reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, was down 4.49 to 1,200.80.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities
of five years or longer, fell 0.30 to 335.30.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3-32 point. The average yield to
maturity, because of rounding, remained at 7.16 percent.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.88 percent as the
discount fell 2 basis points to 7.63 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 7.82 percent as the discount rose 2 basis points to
7.43 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 7.68 percent as the
discount rose 1 basis point to 7.17 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 8~ percent, unchanged from late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
