<FIRST>r f AM-OilAntitrust     08-03 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Antitrust,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Opens Antitrust Investigation of California Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Thursday it has
opened an antitrust investigation of oil prices in California, the
subject of a long-running lawsuit there.
   The state and the city of Long Beach charged in their suit
against six companies that the companies held down prices they paid
for heavy crude oil while secretly agreeing to exchange oil among
themselves at higher prices.
   The companies had agreed to pay the city and the state the
highest price for oil from their wells that they paid anyone else
for oil.
   In their 1985 complaint, the plaintiffs charged that a
conspiracy among the companies cost them $789 million from 1971
through 1977 and from 1980 through 1985.
   The six companies are Chevron, Texaco, Union, Mobil, Shell and
Exxon. A seventh, Arco, paid $22.5 million to settle in 1984.
   A federal appeals court in San Francisco reinstated the lawsuit
in April. It had been dismissed by a lower-court judge in Los
Angeles.
   Assistant Attorney General James F. Rill said in a statement
that ``the antitrust division is looking at crude oil pricing in
the state of California.''
   ``We are monitoring this situation and related developments in
the litigation that was initiated by the state of California and
the city of Long Beach,'' Rill said.
</TEXT>
