<FIRST>u f AM-HomeShopping-GTE     08-03 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Shopping-GTE,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Shopping Gambled And Lost Big With GTE Suit, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Shopping Network Inc. gambled and
lost big in its lawsuit claiming GTE Corp. supplied it with an
inadequate phone system, a setback that only adds to the video
retailer's problems, industry analysts say.
   A jury Wednesday rejected HSN's $1.5 billion suit, instead
awarding two GTE subsidiaries $50 million each in a libel and
slander countersuit.
   ``This really puts Home Shopping Network behind the
eight-ball,'' said William Block, an analyst at Newhard Cook &amp; Co.
in New York. ``At one time, they were really soaring.''
   Home Shopping, which replaced the GTE phones with an MCI system,
reported a profit of $7 million on sales of $586.9 million for the
nine-month period ended May 31. HSN's stock has plummetted from the
mid-40s in 1987 to less than $4 a share.
   In its September 1987 suit, HSN claimed it lost millions of
calls from viewers of its cable TV show and $500 million in
potential sales in 1986 and early 1987 because GTE telephone
equipment it contracted for could not handle the volume of calls.
   During a six-week trial in Pinellas County, the jury rejected
charges of fraud, negligent misrepresentation, breach of trust and
confidence, and breach of fiduciary duty against GTE.
   The panel instead agreed with GTE's countersuit, maintaining
that the electronic retailer's financial problems were actually the
result of bungled management. GTE argued that over-expansion,
competition and customer dissatisfaction, rather than insufficient
equipment, caused HSN's losses.
   Analysts said the victory mattered more to HSN than to the
communications giant.
   ``GTE is such a huge company that this is seen as just a
one-time gain with little long-range implications,'' said James
Stork of Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Chicago. ``But most investors are
just glad it's over. When something like this goes to a jury, there
is no telling what could happen.''
   ``There's definitely a sigh of relief,'' said Greg Sigmund, an
analyst at A.G. Edwards Inc. in St. Louis. ``No one was really
expecting an adverse decision for GTE, but it was on the back of
the minds of a lot of people.''
   GTE Florida and GTE Communications received awards for damages
to their reputations and credibility by Home Shopping Network and
its two top executives.
   ``The jury heard a lengthy and complex presentation of technical
issues, and it understood that the GTE companies had provided
quality service and equipment to help a small company grow very
quickly into a major business,'' said James C. Carideo, GTE Florida
vice president and general counsel.
   HSN was cited for $20 million of the total award, with $40
million each levied against HSN Chairman Roy Speer and President
Lowell Paxson.
   HSN said it would appeal.
   Nando DiFilippo, HSN's executive vice president and general
counsel, said the company would claim the court should not have
presented GTE's libel and slander counterclaim to the jury.
   Under HSN's format, viewers can only buy HSN merchandise as long
as the item is displayed on the screen. The network said it lost 42
million calls when up to half of its incoming calls never reached
sales operators because of the allegedly faulty equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
