<FIRST>u f AM-Chile-Citibank     08-03 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Citibank,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citibank President Says Mexican Concessions Won't Be Repeated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citibank president John Reed said
Thursday that concessions made by creditor banks in a recent accord
with Mexico won't be repeated for other debtor countries.
   Speaking before the local Chilean-American Chamber of Commerce
breakfast, Reed, who runs the biggest U.S. bank, also said he
strongly opposed the notion of government control of the foreign
debt problem and observed that the world banking community's
attention has shifted away from the Third World.
   Reed is on a tour of several Latin American countries, including
Venezuela, which is seeking a refinancing of its debt.
   He said he has been asked if other countries will get the same
kind of relief that Mexico received, which included a 35 percent
reduction in its obligations and $2.3 billion in fresh credit.
   ``It was a plan especially for Mexico,'' he said. ``Personally,
I don't believe there will be another of this type. Really, there
won't be another.''
   ``There are certain things that were done in that case which I
don't think the banks will do again. We have learned that they are
very difficult transactions,'' Reed said.
   He said the accord required abandoning about $15 billion in
claims by creditor banks, ``and that comes directly from the banks'
shareholders.'' About 30 percent of the loss in earnings was
absorbed by U.S. banks and the rest by European and Japanese banks,
he said.
   Reed argued that the banking community was much better equipped
than governments to deal with the Third World's foreign debt
problems, and said he strongly opposed a so-called political
solution.
   He said the leading industrialized democracies often have
discussed the debt problem but ``they never come out and say,
`Okay, we're going to take our government resources and resolve the
problem.' ''
   Reed said U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's plan for
easing the debt problem relies on the banks, and not on public
coffers, for fresh credit.
   ``It's better that we, in the private sector, try to resolve
these problems exchanging debt for investment, extending credits
for the long term, giving time.''
</TEXT>
