<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Economy     08-03 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Economy,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repatriated Capital Boosts Foreign Reserves to $6 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High interest rates have lured $2.3
billion home from foreign banks, boosting the nation's foreign
reserves to $6 billion, the head of Mexico's national bank said
Thursday.
   The first half of 1989 saw an ``abundant repatriation, lured by
high interest rates,'' Banco de Mexico general director Miguel
Mancera said.
   He spoke at the fifth National Banking Meeting, the most
important financial meeting of the year in Mexico.
   Mexicans are estimated to have $28 billion stashed in foreign
banks, mostly in the United States. Much of the money fled because
of the economic crisis that began in 1982 with the worldwide drop
in oil prices.
   Mancera said Mexico's balance of payments showed a $585 million
deficit through July. He called it ``relatively modest considering
the circumstances.''
   Mexico paid out $600 million to service its public debt and $700
million on private debt service, he said. During the same period,
Mancera said, net foreign direct investment was about $900 million.
   The banking meeting in this northern industrial capital of 3
million came in the aftermath of a July 23 accord between Mexico
and private foreign creditors to restructure $54 billion of
Mexico's $107 billion foreign debt.
   ``The agreement doesn't constitute a magic solution to our
problems,'' Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe told the
standing-room-only crowd of banking and government officials from
Mexico, the United States and other countries.
   About 1,500 people are attending the two-day banking meeting at
Monterrey's City Theater.
   ``The current agreement won't permit us to recover overnight
what the crisis of over-indebteness took from us over several
years,'' Aspe said.
   Private analysists have said the debt accord should bring
substantially lower interest rates by generating more confidence in
the national economy.
   With inflation down, the threat of an abrupt currency
devaluation off, and the debt accord signed, the federal government
can begin to tackle its huge internal debt, estimated at $48
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
