<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 1925EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     08-03 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Machinists Leader Starting Investment Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Machinists union leader Charles Bryan marked the
start of the fifth month of the Eastern Airlines strike Thursday by
pledging $100,000 of his own money to a new effort to help the
union-backed buyout bid of Chicago businessman Joseph Ritchie.
   Bryan said he was urging Eastern employees who could afford it,
along with people across the country who support the strikers, to
contribute to an investment fund he hopes will add $50 million to
the Ritchie effort. Bryan, who made the announcement at a news
conference, declined to identify the investment house that is
establishing the fund and said legal details were still being
worked out.
   In a separate development Thursday, the master executive council
of Eastern's pilots union unanimously passed a resolution asking
pilots at carriers nationwide to initiate a suspension of air
service. The parking of planes on runways would be aimed at putting
pressure on Congress to investigate the fitness of Eastern owner
Frank Lorenzo to run Eastern and its sister carrier, Continental
Airlines.
   Bryan said there's enough money already behind the Ritchie bid,
which has been scoffed at by Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp. and
received coolly by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York. The court
has been overseeing Eastern since it filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization on March 9, five days after being hit by
the crippling strike.
   Ritchie has offered $50 million and the unions have kicked in
another $50 million as well as wage concessions totaling $210
million. In addition, the unions have pledged up to $175 million
from their wages if certain goals aren't met during the first six
months of operation under joint ownership.
   Bryan said the AFL-CIO also is willing to offer a line of credit
ranging from $65 million to $200 million for the bid.
   Texas Air has indicated it wants $100 million to $200 million in
cash up front from any buyer for Eastern.
   ``We are not doing this because we need the money,'' Bryan said,
referring to the new investment fund. He said the effort was meant
to counter Eastern ``misinformation'' about its ability to rebuild
without the unions and also to show the commitment of Eastern's
employees to the airline.
   ``I'm making it because I know it will work,'' Bryan said,
saying that in 33 years at Eastern he has accumulated that money
through an austere lifestyle but is willing to put it into buying
the airline.
   He said money for the fund would be returned if the buyout bid
never comes to fruition. Most of Eastern's striking employees have
no money left for such a fund, Bryan agreed, but he said all
employees would benefit because the investment funds would reduce
the amount of wage concessions they would have to make in the
purchase from Texas Air.
   Eastern pilots union spokesman Ron Cole said he thought the fund
was a good chance ``for people to put their money where their mouth
is and show their commitment to Eastern's employees.''
   Eastern on Aug. 1 increased its schedule to 350 daily flights
and says it will be back to 800 daily flights and out of bankruptcy
by year's end.
   Bryan said Eastern is ``in desperate straits,'' losing money on
each flight because of sharply discounted fares and that it lacks
pilots, mechanics and spare parts for its planes.
   Eastern officials said Bryan's announcement wouldn't change
anything.
   ``Our position has not changed. The airline is not for sale,''
said spokesman Robin Matell.
</TEXT>
