<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HelpWantedIndex     08-03 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Help Wanted Index,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Help Wanted Ads Down in June, Third Straight Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Help wanted advertising declined in June for the
third straight month, substantiating other evidence of a nationwide
economic slowdown, the Conference Board business research group
said Thursday.
   Its Help Wanted Advertising Index fell 6 points to 148 after
falling in April and May by similar amounts. The index, calculated
on the volume of employment advertising in 51 major newspapers,
uses 1967 as a base year of 100.
   ``Employment growth has slowed, especially in the cyclically
sensitive durable-goods industries,'' Conference Board economist
Ken Goldstein said in a press release.
   Ad volume fell in all regions of the country except the region
comprising parts of Texas, Louisiana and Oklahoma, the index
results showed.
   The Conference Board, based in New York, is a leading business
information and research concern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
