<DOCNO> AP890803-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AmericanExpress-Safra     08-03 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Express-Safra,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Express Exec Plans to Retire Over Safra Matter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top American Express Co. executive said
Thursday he plans to retire because of ``mistakes made on my
watch'' that led the company to issue an unusual public apology to
international banker Edmund J. Safra.
   The financial services giant said that Harry L. Freeman, 57,
advised Chairman James D. Robinson III that he planned to retire as
executive vice president of corporate affairs and communications by
year's end.
   Freeman would be the first American Express employee to leave
his job as a result of the company's admission that people acting
on its behalf had been involved in a campaign to discredit Safra.
   In a letter released by American Express, Freeman told Robinson
he was convinced that the company's ongoing review of the matter
will show he performed his duties ``faithfully and honestly.''
   ``However, a well-intentioned effort for which I had executive
responsibility went awry,'' he wrote. ``Mistakes were made on my
watch, and accordingly I believe my decision to retire while
painful is appropriate.''
   Freeman, a 14-year veteran of American Express, was unavailable
to comment on the letter and was said to be en route to joining his
family for a long-planned vacation to Africa. He was expected back
at work Aug. 21.
   People familiar with the matter said Freeman felt responsibility
for allowing an operation designed to collect information about
Safra, who at one time managed a bank for American Express, to get
out of control.
   After Safra left the American Express operation in 1984, he
turned his attention to his other holding, Republic New York Corp.
and its Republic National Bank.
   But American Express collected information on Safra because
Republic had an agreement not to compete with the American Express
bank in the lucrative Swiss banking market until 1988 and wanted
the pact enforced.
   Last Friday, Robinson apologized publicly to Safra, who lives in
Geneva, for ``an unauthorized and shameful effort by people acting
on American Express' behalf in fueling false media reports that
linked Safra's banks to money laundering.
   American Express also agreed to pay $8 million to charities of
Safra's choice to settle the dispute.
   Robinson told American Express employees in a memo Thursday of
his ``deep regret'' that Freeman intended to retire.
   ``Harry is much loved throughout our organization, and like
others, I will miss his wisdom and his great sense of humor,''
Robinson wrote. ``I wish him the best in future endeavors and look
forward to his counsel as a loyal American Express alumnus.''
</TEXT>
