<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2157EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-InsiderTrading-Lawyer     08-03 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insider Trading-Lawyer,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Lawyer Settles Insider Trading Charges With SEC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top labor lawyer for Burlington
Northern Railroad has agreed to settle fraud and insider trading
charges, the Securities and Exchange Commission announced Thursday.
   But the SEC said it isn't finished looking at the trading of
Burlington Northern Inc. stock, even after the settlement by lawyer
Richard Schreiber.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Schreiber agreed to pay
$23,889 in alleged illegal profits as well as an equal amount in
fines.
   According to a complaint filed at federal court in Fort Worth,
Texas, Schreiber allegedly traded on confidential information in
1988 about the then-pending restructuring of Burlington Northern,
the parent company of the nation's largest railroad.
   But Herbert Janick III, an SEC lawyer in Washington, said the
investigation was continuing because ``there's been other trading
in Burlington Northern that requires scrutiny by us.''
   ``This was a classic insider case,'' said Janick, ``a lawyer
working for the company in question.''
   Theodore Levine, a Washington-based lawyer for Schreiber, said
his client, now an attorney in private practice, ``wanted to settle
to avoid protracted litigation.''
   Levine would not disclose where Schreiber, formerly of
Arlington, Texas, lives.
   According to the complaint, Schreiber learned about a possible
Burlington Northern restructuring in March 1988 from a senior vice
president who was consulting him about possible labor problems that
might arise from the move.
   The SEC charged that Schreiber bought Burlington Northern common
stock on March 31, 1988, and after further discussions with company
officials about the restructuring, the lawyer allegedly bought 60
Burlington Northern June call options at $1 per contract.
   A call option is the right to buy 100 shares of a particular
stock at a predetermined price by a certain date in exchange for a
premium. As a strategy, call options allow investors who believe a
stock will rise dramatically to profit from a small stake.
   After Burlington Northern announced the restructuring June 2,
1988, the SEC charged, Schreiber sold his positions and made
$23,889 in alleged illegal profits.
   The company spun off its natural resources division into a
separate company called Burlington Resources.
</TEXT>
