<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Newmont-Peabody     08-03 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Newmont-Peabody,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newmont Cancels Planned Recapitalization of Peabody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing the impacts of the continuing coal industry
strike and the uncertain impact of new acid rain legislation,
Newmont Mining Corp. on Thursday canceled plans for a
recapitalization of Peabody Holding Company Inc., in which it holds
a stake.
   The recapitalization plan did not have the ``flexibility to
accommodate the possible negative implications of those two recent
events,'' said Newmont Chairman Gordon R. Parker.
   Denver-based Newmont had announced plans for a transaction that
would have yielded a $425 million pre-tax dividend from Peabody to
Newmont together with a $75 million payment to Newmont from new
Peabody investors, while allowing Newmont to retain its current
equity in Peabody.
   Newmont said it planned to use the cash to cut its debt.
   The other current shareholders of Peabody were simultaneously to
surrender their entire interest in a redemption by Peabody. Salomon
Brothers Inc. and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. would have become
shareholders in their place under the plan.
   The decision to halt the plan, which called for a $1 million
redemption option payment Thursday to the current holders of 50.03
percent of Peabody's shares, was based on the strike and President
Bush's announcement of plans to cut acid rain emissions, the
company said.
   ``As originally conceived, the recapitalization, including the
redemption price and the dividend level, were sound, and Salomon
and Shearson were prepared to give Newmont the right in the
mid-1990's to become the sole owner of Peabody, if Newmont so
chose,'' Parker said.
   ``The strike that began in June at Pittston and spread to much
of the rest of the coal industry, and the potential impact on the
entire coal industry of the administration's newly proposed acid
rain legislation, have made the redemption price under the option
from our co-shareholders in Peabody potentially uneconomic to
Peabody,'' he said.
   ``We do not wish to compromise our ongoing 49.97 percent
investment in Peabody...,'' he said.
</TEXT>
