<FIRST>u f AM-Lang-Magazines     08-03 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lang-Magazines,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media Investor Agrees To Buy Stake in Publisher of Ms., Sassy Magazines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Magazine entrepreneur Dale W. Lang has agreed in
principle to become a joint owner of the company that publishes Ms.
and Sassy magazines, it was announced Thursday.
   Executives at Matilda Publications Inc. have been looking for an
infusion of capital for the publishing concern for several months.
   Lang agreed to invest an undisclosed amount of money to assume
joint ownership of Matilda Publications with Citicorp's Venture
Capital Fund, which arranged financing for a management-led buyout
of the magazines last summer.
   As part of the deal, Lang said in a statement he would take over
management of both magazines, possibly as early as the October
issues.
   Ms., which was founded by the feminist Gloria Steinem and others
in 1972, has a circulation of 550,000, Lang said. Sassy, launched
in March 1988, is a magazine for teenage girls and has a
circulation of 450,000.
   Anne Summers, editor-in-chief at both magazines, said she and
the other Matilda founders knew when the company was formed in July
1988 that more capital would be needed eventually.
   ``The magazines are healthy. Their circulation is very good and
although neither of them is profitbale, we are looking for them to
move into profitability within the next year or so,'' she said.
   Lang has been involved since 1987 in a joint venture with Time
Inc. called Working Woman-McCall's Group.
   That partnership published McCall's, Working Woman and Working
Mother magazines, and it recently sold McCall's, a women's service
magazine, to New York Times Co. for what insiders estimate was
about $80 million.
   Lang said plans are underway for him to buy Time's 50 percent
stake in Working Woman and Working Mother.
   He said that once that purchase is completed, he hopes to place
those magazines with his interests in Ms. and Sassy under a new
corporate unbrella called Lang Communications Inc.
   ``Our new company intends to bring together a strong stable of
well-focused, editorially-driven, high-demographic magazines,'' he
said.
   Working Woman, which Lang says has a circulation of 950,000,
focuses on business management for career women. Working Mother,
with a circulation of 625,000, is a lifestyle magazine devoted to
helping the working mother balance family and career
responsibilities.
   Lang also owns Success magazine, which is aimed at entrepreneurs
and has a circulation of 450,000.
</TEXT>
