<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Hanson     08-03 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Hanson,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hanson Shareholders Approve Offer For Consolidated Gold Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Hanson PLC at a meeting in London
Thursday approved the British conglomerate's 3.5 billion pound, or
$5.7 billion, offer for the mining giant Consolidated Gold Fields
PLC, Hanson said.
   Approval was expressed in an overwhelming show of hands among
those present. Shareholders voting by proxy also were
overwhelmingly in favor of the offer, said Hanson, Britain's
fourth-largest company.
   On June 22, Hanson, in a move that took the stock market by
surprise, offered 3.1 billion pounds, then worth $4.8 billion, for
Consolidated Gold Fields.
   Consolidated Gold Fields accepted Hanson's bid in early July.
Under the agreement, Hanson said it would offer 14.30 pounds, or
the equivalent of $23.45 a share, for Consolidated and give
Consolidated shareholders warrants to purchase new Hanson shares.
   Also under the agreement, Consolidated agreed to pay
shareholders the equivalent of a 65-cent dividend for the fiscal
year ended June 30. The warrant and dividend together increased the
value of Hanson's offer to $25.09 a share.
   Consolidated has interests in South African gold and platinum
and U.S. construction materials.
   Hanson has interests ranging from bricks and EverReady batteries
to light industry.
   In April, a U.S. court blocked a merger bid for Consolidated
from South African-controlled Minorco SA, an investment group.
Minorco's bid was valued at 3.65 billion pounds, then worth $6.2
billion.
   A majority of Consolidated shareholders indicated that they
wanted to accept Minorco's bid. But the U.S. court refused to lift
an injunction against a Minorco takeover arising from an antitrust
suit.
   U.S. courts had ruled that Minorco had ambitions to create a
world gold monopoly.
</TEXT>
