<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-CIGNA     08-03 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-CIGNA,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>CIGNA Reports $12.4 Million Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CIGNA reported Thursday a 3.9 percent
increase in second-quarter earnings despite a decrease of 68
percent in the insurance company's operating profits on property
and casualty underwriting.
   Wilson H. Taylor, president and chief executive officer, said
the decrease, which totaled $106 million for the first half of the
year, was caused by ``generally inadequate pricing'' in the
property and casualty market.
   He warned the situation could worsen because ``there are no
clear signs that the underwriting cycle's decline has ended.''
   For the second quarter, net income totaled $144 million, or
$1.77 a share, on revenue of $3.8 billion. For the same period in
1988, the company reported income of $138.8 million, or $1.65 a
share, on revenue of $3.6 billion.
   For the first six months of 1989, the company reported income of
$229.5 million, or $2.80 a share, on revenue of $7.5 billion. The
figures represent a 5.7 increase over the $217.1 million, or 25
cents a share, from last year's first half.
   The largest quarterly increase in operating profit was in
investment gains, with $17.4 million reported for the past quarter,
a 241 percent increase over the $7.2 million reported last year.
   The property and casualty operations had operating income of
$26.6 million in the second quarter, down 68 percent from the $83.9
million reported a year ago.
</TEXT>
