<FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0335 08-03 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0335,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firm, Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar remained firm against the Japanese
yen during morning trading Friday, while share prices fell
moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
119.53 points Thursday, lost 71.35 more points, or 0.20 percent, to
close the morning session at 34,708.46.
   The dollar was changing hands at 137.40 yen at late morning, up
1.0 yen from Thursday's close of 136.40 yen. After opening at
137.08 yen, the currency ranged from 137.00 to 137.58 yen.
   Traders said many market participants were reluctant to take
major moves prior to the release of U.S. unemployment figures for
July, due out in Washington later Friday.
   Norio Takeda, a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, said
dollar-buying during morning trading came from securities companies
wanting to procure the American currency to prepare for an issuance
of U.S. government bonds, slated for Tuesday.
   Other dealers said the dollar's firmess reflected the tension
due to threats by a group to kill another American hostage in
Lebanon. The dollar is considered a safe haven in times of
international tension.
   On the stock market, dealers said the market was very quiet
because of the start later this week of the ``obon'' season, an
annual summer festival.
   Many brokers take time off during the following week, and some
have already left, leaving many offices at less than full staff,
according to traders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
